http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-1&fd=R&url=http://lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/Local/2007/05/31/4223337.html&cid=1116761338&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ London Free Press - Local News - Mike Harris used racist slur: Ipperwash report Movie reviews! Get the lowdown on all the latest releases in the pages of our Today section Thursday, 31 May, 2007 Place a Classified Ad Top 5 on Web FOR SALE: Quads Easter Poster Drive -- Spring Edition Mike Harris used racist slur: Ipperwash report Thu, May 31, 2007 Also finds former Ontario premier did not interfere in park occupation The head of the Ipperwash inquiry has ruled that former premier Mike Harris told a high-level meeting on the day Dudley George was killed that "I want the f---ing Indians out of the park." But Justice Sidney Linden also found that while Harris's comment was "racist" and the premier was critical of police, Harris did not interfere or give inappropriate directions to the police at Ipperwash. "Although one may disagree with his views, it was legitimate for the Premier to take the position that the First Nations people were illegally occupying the park, and that he wanted them out of Ipperwash Park as soon as possible." Harris had denied he made such a remark during his testimony at the inquiry, but Linden wrote that after carefully reviewing the evidence he believed Harris said it. Linden, who had been urged by the police union to find that Dudley George was armed with a gun when he was shot, found that Dudley George did not have a gun on the night he was killed by Acting OPP Sgt. Ken Deane. "Ken Deane's assertion that Dudley threw his rifle on the ground is implausible," wrote Linden. "I accept the evidence of the aboriginal people that the occupiers did not have guns at the park during the confrontation with police." Four years in the making, the 1,500-page report of the judicial inquiry into the police shooting of native protester Dudley George on Sept. 6, 1995 contains 98 recommendations, covering future police operations and federal and provincial government relations with natives. George was part of a group of natives who had moved into the park after it was closed for the season, claiming it was the site of a native burial ground, an assertion that was later confirmed by the federal government. Based on recorded conversations and radio transmissions, Linden found that the racism and cultural insensitivity among some members of the Ontario Provincial Police contributed to the lack of a timely, peaceful resolution to the Ipperwash occupation. "There is no place for racial taunts or slurs of any type by police officers," Linden wrote. Police who were ordered to the park on the night of Sept. 6, 1995 were acting on mistaken and unverified information, the report said. "The OPP's assessment of the risk at the park was incorrect. This mistake had severe and tragic repercussions." In the early part of the native occupation, the police commander and other officers spent an inordinate amount of time and effort on armoured vehicles, weapons and other equipment, valuable time taken away from important issues such as speaking to a negotiator, Linden wrote. The report calls for the OPP to ensure the involvement of First Nation police services and mediators when it responds to future aboriginal occupations and protests. Linden also calls for the OPP to issue a public apology to Cecil Bernard George for the blows to his head and face at the hands of one or more unidentified police officers when he was arrested in the sandy parking where Dudley George was shot. A Kettle Point band councillor, Cecil Bernard George hadn't been part of the occupation, but was arrested during the clash between natives and police. "The apology should be delivered in person by the current Commissioner, or his delegate, and via a press release and conference," Linden said. In a blunt recommendation, Linden calls for the federal government to immediately return the former army camp to the peoples of Kettle and Stony Point First Nation and guarantee it will assume complete responsibility for an appropriate environmental clean-up of the site. "The federal government should issue a public apology with appropriate compensation to the Kettle and Stony Point First Nation for the failure of the federal government for more than 60 years to honour its promise to return the lands to the First Nation." Linden also recommends the creation of a permanent, independent and impartial agency, the Treaty Commission of Ontario, to oversee the settling of native land claims in Ontario. "The single biggest source of frustration, distrust, and ill-feeling among aboriginal people in Ontario is our failure to deal in a just and expeditious way with breaches of treaty and other legal obligations to First Nations. If the governments of Ontario and Canada want to avoid future confrontations like Ipperwash or Caledonia, they will have to deal with land and treaty claims effectively and fairly," the report said. In his report, Linden refers to "missed opportunities" during the Ipperwash crisis by government officials, including the burial-ground issue raised by the native protesters. "Had more effort been exerted, had more concern been attached by political staff and civil servants to this issue, and had there been due diligence, government officials would have realized that documents stored for decades in the basement of the Whitney Block showed that the First Nations people had voiced their concerns about these burial grounds," the report notes. As for the future of Ipperwash Provincial Park, which still remains occupied by the natives, Linden said allowing the status quo to continue "is not in anybody's interest." "It is a tribute to the patience and restraint of the occupiers and the local residents that there have been no serious, adverse incidents since 1995. But this unresolved status should not continue," the report said. But Linden wrote there are no perfect solutions and it wouldn't be acceptable if the park were re-opened unilaterally by the Ontario government as a provincial park. One possiblity, he suggests, is a co-management arrangement with the native community that would see the park operated by the aboriginals for the benefit of all Ontarians and visitors. Other recommendations of the inquiry include: - Public education about treaties to improve relations. "At the very least, every Ontarian should understand that this province and our country were built upon the treaties negotiated with our First Nations, and that everyone shares the benefits and obligations of those treaties. Every Ontarian should also realize that treaties are not historical artifacts from some distant past. They remain vitally important and relevant today." - Ontario should create a Ministry of Aboriginal Affairs to administer and support a revitalized land claims process. For the latest local coverage, read The London Free Press To subscribe to the print edition, click on our John Miner and Joe Belanger are Free Press reporters. Funeral furor rocks Tories Mike Harris used racist slur: Ipperwash report Lead scare hits Queen's Park Classroom aides on chopping block Trial begins for 1964 slayings Canadian dies in chopper attack McGuinty, Schwarzenegger ink climate, stem cell pacts Delaying hip surgery can be fatal Canada in top 10 peaceful countries GST cut had little spending impact Woman involved in killings, Pickton witness suggests Air Canada to talk safety Tobacco firm to go on trial Prosecutors rest case against Conrad Black Passengers exposed to TB narrowed down Royal protester eats part of corgi Peres seeks Israeli presidency Bush, Putin to meet in Maine Everest climber oldest to top out Lawyer says Harris should apologize FOREST, Ont. (CP) - The brother of Dudley George says the aboriginal protester's legacy is that he stood up for what he believed in. Canadian dies in chopper attack Lawyers denied access to hearings in torture probe Quarantined TB p