http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-5&fd=R&url=http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php%3Fenewsid%3D74615&cid=1116589853&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ On entering northern Iraq - Turkish Daily News May 31, 2007 Thursday, May 31 2007 7:12 pm GMT+2 On entering northern Iraq Thursday, May 31, 2007 mail to a friend On entering northern Iraq As Turkey gets stressed out by terror, “Army to Iraq” discourse finds ground&#8230; Let's recall quickly: Chief of General Staff Gen. Yaþar Büyükanýt said a military operation in northern Iraq is necessary and they wait for a relevant decision to be made by political mechanism. While the heaviest military build-up of recent years goes on in the Iraq border in eastern Turkey, preparations for a possible operation were launched. The retired general at a key post to provide cooperation and communication between Turkey and the U.S. regarding the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party's (PKK) terror, removed from office by the government. Last week's suicide bombing in Ankara and confessions of terrorists caught in numerous cities in this process strengthened the conviction that the PKK targets big cities. The violation of Turkish airspace last week by two U.S. F 16s created the impression that the government and armed forces are at odds. And finally, Kurdish administrators in northern Iraq made statements in the meaning “Turkish tanks cannot find way to these lands.” Operation by press releases?: Undoubtedly the key issue needs to be clarified here is the situation that produces reservations about politics-military relations and confuses the minds. By all means, neither from the military nor the politics perspective sharing thoughts about an imaginary military operation through press releases is normal. It is even needless to say that this is against the traditions of Turkish Army and the general principles of military professional. And only to know this requires a deduction that something is odd, there is something unusual. If you ask, what is “unusual”, my answer would be: The U.S. factor&#8230; Let me elaborate this a bit more: In the good old days, “Army to Iraq” meant a “hot pursue” or a “cross border operation”. And in legal perspective, all military operations before the U.S. invasion in Iraq were held by the approval of Baghdad and in the frame of mutual agreement with the neighboring country. But now, the situation has changed. Neither the approval of Baghdad nor of Washington is the point at issue. To the opposite, statements made by both capitals give the impression of an objection and even an implicit/explicit threat against Turkey. Therefore regardless of the decision by political body in Ankara depends on the ground of “terror” it will blatantly have the characteristic of a “declaration of war”. Intervention at all odds?: Let me get to the point. I am of the opinion that the public impression of a communication break down between the military and the politics stems from that the Turkish army will be facing the U.S. forces in northern Iraq. Because the presence of Kurdish peshmerga in northern Iraq does not justify who the dominant power is in the region. Therefore it is reasonable to explain the limped communication between the Turkish Armed Forces and the government by the desire to reach a prompt conclusion in the diplomatic initiatives with Washington. Observation of escalating desire “intervention at all odds” in the Turkish army might strengthen the hands of foreign affairs having hard time to express itself in Washington. But if you ask the question whether the army will enter Iraq, the answer of course will be it is possible if suicide bombings similar to the one in Ankara continue. Apparently as long as the investigation about the suicide attack of Anafartalar Avenue in Ankara is in progress, opportunities will rise to make some new assessments beyond clarifying the incident as an attack by the PKK. I previously mentioned that there are some groups in Washington making calculations to provoke Turkish military and dragging it into the quagmire in Iraq. And the military will be worn out in a “nightmare period”, civilian decision making mechanism will be strengthened etc&#8230; I hope we will not end up loses because of the incertitude originates from election and politics discussions. The realm of the state cannot afford the games of “pretends”&#8230; &copy; 2005 Dogan Daily News Inc. About Turkish Daily News Add TDN headlines to your site Add a link to TDN from your site Created in 0.43818306922913 seconds.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-0&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DaNapusUTpfxY%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116836088&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ , May 31 12:12 , May 31 17:12 , Jun 01 01:12 U.S. Loses 6 Soldiers in Iraq; Worst Month Since 2004 (Update1) May 31 (Bloomberg) -- Six U.S. soldiers died in Iraq, taking American losses to at least 123 in the deadliest month for coalition forces in the country since Marines battled to drive insurgents from Fallujah in November 2004. Last month, 102 U.S. service members were killed in action, making April and May the deadliest two-month period for the American military since the March 2003 invasion. The highest number of deaths in a single month was 135 service members killed in action in November 2004, when Marines fought the battle for Fallujah. Four U.S. soldiers were killed in two separate roadside bomb attacks yesterday. A soldier seriously wounded in a May 28 roadside bomb attack died of his wounds a day later. A sixth soldier died from a non-combat related cause on May 29. The military detailed the deaths in separate e-mailed statements yesterday and today. U.S. deaths in Iraq have risen each month since intensified efforts to secure Baghdad and the western province of al-Anbar began in February. President George W. Bush ordered the deployment of the additional forces in January. At least 436 U.S. personnel have been wounded so seriously this month that they couldn&#39;t return to duty. Eight soldiers and an Iraqi child were hurt in a suicide bomb attack on a military checkpoint in Baghdad yesterday, the military said in a separate statement. ``It&#39;s been a tough month,&#39;&#39; Brigadier-General Perry Wiggins, deputy director for regional operations for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said in a televised Pentagon briefing yesterday. The fifth and final brigade of the roughly 30,000 additional U.S. forces deployed as part of the so-called ``surge&#39;&#39; has arrived in Iraq and will be operational by mid-June, Wiggins said. There has been an ``increase in fights with terrorists and extremists of all affiliations&#39;&#39; since the deployment of additional forces, U.S. military spokesman Major General William Caldwell said on May 23. ``We now have more troops conducting more operations involving more troops resulting in more confrontations,&#39;&#39; Caldwell said. Some 3,459 U.S. personnel had died in Iraq, of whom 2,834 were killed in action, as of 10 a.m. New York time yesterday. More than 25,000 had been wounded, 11,526 of them so seriously that they couldn&#39;t return to duty, according to the Department of Defense Web site. Pentagon figures showed that since the 3,342 U.S. deaths recorded in Iraq by the end of April, a further 117 service members had died this month, prior to the latest casualties. To contact the reporter on this story: Robin Stringer in London at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 09:49 EDT Related Media on Demand Saif Says Iraqis&#39; Impact on Jordan Is `Exaggerated&#39; Jordanian Economy Feels Strain from Iraq War Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Treasury 10-Year Yield at 2007 High on Chicago Business Index Increase
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-5&fd=R&url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/americas/05/29/cuba.castsro.ap/&cid=1116704827&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ In essay, Castro says Bush waiting for him to die - CNN.com In essay, Castro says Bush waiting for him to die &#8226; Ailing Cuban leader Fidel Castro says President Bush cannot kill his ideas &#8226; Castro's remarks, the latest in a series of essays, appeared in communist paper &#8226; Castro criticizes the Bush administration for its spending on weaponry &#8226; Communist leader's exact ailment and condition remain state secrets (AP) -- Fidel Castro said in a statement published Tuesday that President Bush is waiting for him to die but that the American leader cannot kill his ideas. The latest in a series of essays by the 80-year-old Castro, who has not been seen in public since becoming ill more than 10 months ago, was published on the front page of the Communist Party daily Granma. The Cuban leader said that Bush, asked recently about his Cuba policy, replied: "I'm a hard-line president and I'm only waiting for Castro to die." "I'm not the first, nor will I be the last, who Bush has ordered to be deprived of life," said Castro, who offered no details of the alleged conversation. American law now prohibits the U.S. government from ordering the assassination of foreign leaders, but declassified U.S. documents show that the CIA made numerous attempts to kill Castro in the early years after the 1959 Cuban revolution. "Ideas are not killed," Castro wrote. He criticized the Bush administration for spending on weaponry while people in developing nations go hungry. "I ask myself how many doctors can graduate with the 100 billion dollars that in just one year fall into Bush's hands to continue to sow mourning in Iraqi and American homes," he wrote. "The answer: 999,990 doctors, who could attend to 2 billion people who today receive no medical care." Castro shocked Cuba on July 31 when he announced that he had undergone emergency intestinal surgery and was stepping aside provisionally for his younger brother Raul, the defense minister, during his recovery. Although senior Cuban officials have said Castro is on the mend, it seems more unlikely with time that the bearded leader will return to power. In one of his essays this month, Castro offered a few new details about illness, saying that he had numerous operations and that the first procedure did not go well. Castro's exact ailment and condition remain state secrets, but he is widely believed to suffer from diverticular disease, which causes sacs in the colon that can become inflamed and bleed. . All rights reserved.This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Next story in World Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) What are E-mail Alerts? Bush urges 15 nations to set global emissions goal President Bush on Thursday urged 15 major nations to agree by the end of next year on a global emissions goal for reducing greenhouse gases. Russia missile test signal to U.S. Quarantined TB patient moved Spain sues over shipwreck booty NZ power firm denies wrongdoing Dad: Lohan on alcohol, OxyContin Ex-KGB spy: UK tried to recruit me TB patient moved to Denver hospital Putin says test missile is signal to U.S. Power company denies role in death Spain sues U.S. firm over shipwreck booty Convertible crash test results A TB victim's odd journey U.S. lawmakers, traders in Cuba Now In The News (Updated: 11:12 a.m. ET) Cuban leader Fidel Castro has not been seen in public since becoming ill more than 10 months ago. Castro talks of illness for first time Entry Level - New Grad Installation - Maint - Repair QA - Quality Control Restaurant - Food Service Skilled Labor - Trades &copy; 2007 Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company. All Rights Reserved. under which this service is provided to you. External sites open in new window; not endorsed by CNN.com Pay service with live and archived video.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-6&fd=R&url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_6023854&cid=1116798859&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ The Denver Post - Jeppesen unit sued over alleged CIA "torture flights" 3 10 14 18 28 33 7 23 35 54 55 (28) pp-2 Denver & The West Economy / Real Estate Subscribe / Customer Care Jeppesen unit sued over alleged CIA "torture flights" The ACLU says Jeppesen's Dataplan unit helped take terrorist suspects to nations where they were tortured. By Kelly Yamanouchi Denver Post Staff Writer Article Last Updated: 05/30/2007 09:29:46 PM MDT A lawsuit filed by the American Civil Liberties Union contends that a unit of Arapahoe County-based Jeppesen Sanderson Inc. provided flight support for the Central Intelligence Agency to transport suspected terrorists to facilities where they were tortured. Jeppesen, through its International Trip Planning Services, provides support such as itinerary planning, route planning and ground handling to businesses and government agencies. The ACLU filed the suit in San Jose, Calif., against Jeppesen's Dataplan unit, which does international trip planning and has U.S. operations in San Jose. The lawsuit says Jeppesen facilitated more than 70 secret "extraordinary rendition" flights over four years to countries "where it knew or reasonably should have known that detainees are routinely tortured or otherwise abused" against legal standards. "Extraordinary rendition should be condemned. It should not be seen as a source of corporate profit," said ACLU executive director Anthony Romero. The suit cites an article from The New Yorker magazine that quotes an anonymous former Jeppesen employee recounting that Bob Overby, managing director of Jeppesen International Trip Planning, said during an internal corporate meeting, "We do all of the extraordinary rendition flights - you know, the torture flights. Let's face it, some of those flights end up that way." Jeppesen spokesman Mike Pound called the reported Overby comment "a third-hand report of something that somebody said - in other words, it's hearsay." "We really don't know much of anything about a trip of that nature," Pound said. "We don't need to know why a customer is taking a trip, and we don't ask." CIA spokesman George Little said in an e-mailed comment that the United States "does not conduct or condone torture, nor does it transport anyone to other countries for the purpose of torture. The goal of renditions is to get terrorists off the streets in a way that complies with our laws and treaty obligations." "Renditions have occurred far less frequently than some press reports suggest, and they are subject to careful review," Little said. Some U.S. corporations, the ACLU lawsuit says, "have furnished aircraft and personnel to transport persons identified by the United States as potential terrorist threats to detention and interrogation facilities overseas. Other corporations, including Jeppesen, have provided flight and logistical support services to these aircraft and crew." An ACLU official said he believes many other companies are involved and that he hopes they "take note." The ACLU filed the suit on behalf of foreign nationals Binyam Mohamed, Abou Elkassim Britel and Ahmed Agiza, who the suit says were flown overseas and tortured. It also petitioned the U.S. Supreme Court to review a suit that claims former CIA Director George Tenet violated U.S. and universal human-rights laws by authorizing agents to detain Khaled El-Masri. The suit was dismissed by a lower court after the government invoked "state secrets" privilege. "The government is the one that is liable," said Ved Nanda, a professor of international law at the University of Denver. "I think it will be very hard for the ACLU to win the case (against Jeppesen). But what it will do is bring the issue before the public, create awareness ... and so in that sense it serves the purpose." The suit cites customary international law and says Jeppesen should be punished by an award of punitive damages to be determined at trial. It also asks for compensatory damages of more than $75,000. The suit names Premier Executive Transportation Services and Aero Contractors Limited as owners and operators of aircraft that were flown to Morocco, Pakistan and other locations. "This puts other companies on notice, that they are likely to be blackballed and there are going to be people who probably think about them as also responsible for this kind of heinous act," Nanda said. A group called South Bay Mobilization has asked people to come to events in past months at Jeppesen's San Jose location and at a San Jose skating rink, urging them to "Join Us to Skate Against Torture" and "Abolish the Torture Flights," according to its website. Mark Loewenstein, a law professor at the University of Colorado at Boulder, said corporations must take into consideration potential liability. "The question is: Have they violated the law, did they knowingly violate the law, and do they have some kind of immunity (because it is work for the government)?" Loewenstein said. "If the ACLU prevails there ... the shareholders are going to come snooping around saying, 'How could you let this happen?"' Jeppesen acquired its international trip-planning-services business, which started as part of Lockheed DataPlan, in 1989. Jeppesen Sanderson is part of the Boeing Co., based in Chicago. Staff writer Kelly Yamanouchi can be reached at 303-954-1488 or Denver & the West TB patient at National Jewish Evans gets 4 more years Season wraps Sunday at A-Basin Rockies streak strikes out Touching all the bases Pahlsson a big piece of puzzle Weakest economic growth since 2002 "Potter" theme park to open in Florida Gay Chorus sets tone of harmony She shoots horses, doesn't she? Deadly disease needs to be eradicated now Lunch menu: Carrots, sticks A sign of the times in Iran Listener helps save ailing disc jockey Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking 'Faith-healing' brothers charged in scam Season wraps Sunday at A-Basin Evans gets 4 more years Suburban pet peeve: coyotes Report: Surgery best help for spine ailment 9 hurricanes predicted this year Weakest economic growth since 2002 TB patient at National Jewish Season wraps Sunday at A-Basin Evans gets 4 more years Suburban pet peeve: coyotes Report: Surgery best help for spine ailment 9 hurricanes predicted this year Weakest economic growth since 2002 Personal - Injury - Lawyer Luxury Denver Real Estate Reverse Osmosis Water Filters Cabin Kits & Building Cabins Printers & Printer Supplies Lasik Denver eye surgery All contents Copyright 2007 The Denver Post or other copyright holders. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed for any commercial purpose. E-mail Newsletters & Breaking News Alerts Subscribe / Customer Care MNG Corporate Site Map
http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_6027182&cid San Jose Mercury News - Iraq suicide blast leaves up to 25 dead san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Prosecutors: Aptos woman lived high life on &#36;1.5 million stolen... Kawakami: Bryant reveals a tortured soul Spector defense targets forensic errors Rivals Steve Jobs, Bill Gates talk like old pals Iraq suicide blast leaves up to 25 dead By SINAN SALAHEDDIN Associated Press Writers Article Launched: 05/31/2007 02:07:17 AM PDT Click photo to enlarge Residents of Sadr city, Baghdad, load a coffin on a mini bus during the funeral of a victim after an early morning U.S. air strike Thursday, May 31, 2007. A U.S. military helicopter hit a house and car at early Thursday killing two elderly people sleeping on the roof of their home a police officer said. A U.S. military statement, said U.S. and Iraqi forces had arrested two "members of the secret cell terrorist network" on Thursday in Sadr City. BAGHDAD- A suicide bomber hit a police recruiting center Thursday in Fallujah, killing as many as 25 people, police said. The U.S. military said only one policeman was killed and eight were wounded. U.S. forces backed by helicopter gunships clashed with suspected al-Qaida gunmen in western Baghdad in an engagement that lasted several hours. The American military also reported the deaths of three more soldiers, two killed Wednesday in a roadside bombing in Baghdad and one who died of wounds from a roadside bomb attack northwest of the capital Tuesday. At least 122 American forces have died in May, the third-deadliest month of the Iraq conflict. U.S. forces also continued a search for five Britons who were kidnapped Tuesday in Baghdad, as well as for two of its soldiers who have been missing since a May 12 ambush south of the capital. The Fallujah suicide bomber killed at least 10 policemen in the attack, which occurred about 11 a.m., according to a police official in the city who spoke on condition of anonymity because he was not authorized to release the information. The rest of the dead were civilians, many of them in line seeking jobs as policemen. He said as many as 50 were wounded. Fallujah General Hospital had received 15 bodies and 10 wounded, according to a doctor there, who would not allow the use of his name because he feared retribution. The physician said he believed other casualties were taken to the nearby Jordanian Hospital and private clinics. A member of the Fallujah city council, who also asked for anonymity for fear of attack by insurgents, said there were at least 20 killed and 25 injured. The coordination of information in Fallujah was particularly difficult because the mobile telephone system has been working only sporadically. Maj. Jeff Pool of the Multi-National Force-West said the Anbar province governor's office and the provincial police put the total number of dead at one Iraqi policeman, with six police and two civilians wounded in Fallujah, 40 miles west of Baghdad. Police said the bomber detonated explosives in his vest at the third of four checkpoints, standing among recruits who were lining up to apply for jobs on the force. The center had only opened Saturday in a primary school in eastern Fallujah. The U.S. military and Iraqi army and police were running the center along with members of Anbar Salvation Council, a loose grouping of Sunni tribes that have banded together to fight al-Qaida. Police stations and recruiting posts have been a favorite target of Sunni insurgents and al-Qaida throughout the war. The fighting in western Baghdad's Amariyah neighborhood exploded after residents called for U.S. help. Members of al-Qaida, who consider the district part of their so-called Islamic State of Iraq, were preventing students from attending final exams, shooting randomly and forcing residents to stay in their homes, according to an official of the district council. He spoke on condition of anonymity, fearing retribution from al-Qaida. Clashes continued into the afternoon, and the council official said the al-Qaida leader in the region, known as Haji Hameed, was killed and 45 other fighters detained. There was no immediate word on the fighting from the U.S. military. U.S. forces, meanwhile, pressed on with the search for five kidnapped Britons, and a procession of mourners, some of them women wailing and beating their chests, marched through Sadr City behind a small bus carrying the coffins of two people who police said were killed in a U.S. helicopter strike before dawn. The U.S. military said it had no report of airstrikes in Sadr City and that there were no civilian casualties in the second day of a search for the Britons, who were abducted Tuesday from a Finance Ministry data processing building in eastern Baghdad. A U.S. military statement, however, said U.S. and Iraqi forces had arrested two "members of the secret cell terrorist network" in Sadr City. There was no mention of fatalities. AP Television News videotape from Sadr City showed the coffins of the victims atop a small bus with men and women walking behind, crying. A young boy could be seen sitting next to the coffins. A car in the area was punctured with big holes, as if hit by an airstrike. A police officer in Sadr City, who refused to allow use of his name because he feared retribution, said the helicopter hit a house and car at 4:30 a.m., killing two elderly people sleeping on the roof of their home&mdash;a common practice in Iraq's extreme heat through late spring and summer. The officer said a 13-year-old boy was wounded. Also in Sadr City raids, which the U.S. has been conducting with a select unit of Iraqi army forces, Shiite cleric Abdul-Zahra al-Suwaidi claimed his home was raided and ransacked by American forces at 3 a.m. Thursday. The military said it had no report of the incident. Al-Suwaidi, who runs the Sadr City political office of radical cleric Muqtada al-Sadr, said he was sleeping elsewhere at the time of the raid, expecting that he would be targeted. He said his home was badly damaged and a small amount of money was taken. Dozens of U.S. Humvees and Bradley fighting vehicles had taken up positions around Sadr City at nightfall Wednesday. The five kidnapped Britons included four bodyguards working for the Montreal-based security firm GardaWorld and one employee of BearingPoint, a U.S.-based management consulting firm. In Washington, Brig. Gen. Perry Wiggins, deputy director of operations for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the military believed a helicopter that crashed Monday north of Baghdad was brought down by small-arms fire. The Islamic State of Iraq, an al-Qaida front group, claimed responsibility. Wiggins also said that more than 100 patrols a day were being launched to search for two missing troops who vanished after a May 12 ambush near Mahmoudiya, south of Baghdad. Four Americans and one Iraqi soldier were killed in the attack and the body of another American was later found in the Euphrates River. "Our determination and resolve to locate our missing soldiers is unwavering," Wiggins said. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Commission delays San Jose Flea Market vote De Anza protest planned Edwards woos voters at Google ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Giuliani works Peninsula crowd Hazardous waste plant must close Book details UCSC's hidden treasures Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
