http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-0&fd=R&url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,21828975-5001021,00.html&cid=1116798912&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ Balibo demand cop investigated | The Daily Telegraph Welcome to The Daily Telegraph. Place a classified newspaper ad Balibo demand cop investigated By Rhett Watson and Cindy Wockner June 01, 2007 12:00 THE police officer who tried to subpoena an Indonesian politician possibly connected to the Balibo Five deaths is now under investigation as part of the diplomatic fallout. News of the internal review of the officer's actions came as NSW Premier Morris Iemma last night said he had written to Jakarta Governor Sutiyoso apologising for any distress and inconvenience during his stay in Sydney. "I apologise for the distress and inconvenience caused and regret your early departure from New South Wales," Mr Iemma wrote. Hundreds of angry protesters shouting anti-Australian slogans yesterday converged on the Australian Embassy in Jakarta for the second day. Indonesia has complained bitterly about the treatment of Mr Sutiyoso, who says police entered his Sydney hotel room unannounced to confront him on Tuesday afternoon. The NSW Coroner's Court confirmed yesterday that the officer had a subpoena for Mr Sutiyoso to appear before the Balibo Five coronial inquest, but delivered a verbal invitation when he realised the former general was in his room at the Shangri-La Hotel. Mr Sutiyoso, a retired military lieutenant-general, denies involvement in the 1975 Balibo shooting murders of five Australian newsmen, for whom war crimes charges may be brought. Police sources say Sergeant Steve Thomas, who was under instructions from the Deputy State Coroner, broke no laws in confronting the politician and his actions were now under review because of the political firestorm. Foreign Minister Alexander Downer spoke to his Indonesian counterpart Hassan Wirajuda last night, promising the matter would be investigated. "What the Governor claims is that he was having a rest in his room and two policemen just walked in . . . and suggested he may wish to go to a hearing of . . . a coroner's court," Mr Downer said. "He was, of course, outraged at this." Mr Sutiyoso, who returned to Jakarta on Tuesday night, left a 30-minute meeting with Australia's Ambassador Bill Farmer yesterday to say that the diplomat had told him he would "take care" to get a formal letter of apology. "I forgive him, he is an Ambassador, he represents Australia in Indonesia and he, in front of me and some of my staff, conveyed his apology and was very shocked and disappointed with that incident. We are a big-hearted country. Why shouldn't I forgive that?" The attempt to subpoena the senior Jakarta politician, tipped as a possible presidential candidate, sparked a chorus of condemnation from Indonesians and created a diplomatic row between the two countries. The second day of protests at the Embassy prompted the Department of Foreign Affairs to add civil unrest to its travel warning for Indonesia. Shangri-La management has revealed that the police officers arrived on Tuesday afternoon and requested access to Mr Sutiyoso's room. Staff then called the Governor's room, but when there was no answer they escorted the officers upstairs. "One of our staff rang the doorbell &ndash; they rang it a few times &ndash; and there was no answer," a spokeswoman said. The officers were let into the room, only to find Mr Sutiyoso inside. A police spokesman confirmed an internal review had begun. DPP bid to dump child sex cases Rape inquiry cop given tickets Balibo demand cop investigated Mighell ejection a Rudd strategy Unlucky Albert's prison brake Weekend jail for TV's Meakin Evil Van Krevel set free Sophia Loren hits Sydney Alleged drug kingpin in dock Aged care home site poisoned Polluters pay for high emissions Sartor's Orange Grove-style row NRL coach's sex tip-off Cut DPP budget, not travel 100 nursing facilities face fire risk We