http://www.newsday.com/news/nationworld/nation/ny-usfred0531,0,5517948.story%3Fcoll%3Dny-leadnationalnews-headlines&cid Actor Fred Thompson tests presidential waters - Newsday.com New York City News Actor Fred Thompson tests presidential waters WASHINGTON -- Actor Fred Thompson is taking a big step toward running for president, and early polls show the "Law & Order" TV prosecutor is likely to cut into support for a prominent real-life ex-prosecutor, Rudolph Giuliani. The former Tennessee senator will form a "testing the waters" committee in coming days that clears the way for him to enter the presidential race, possibly as soon as the July Fourth weekend, Thompson supporters said Wednesday. His entry would be sure to jumble an already volatile Republican field, where Giuliani leads in national polls despite deep doubts about him and two other top candidates among conservatives, who have been casting about for an ideological heir to Ronald Reagan. As a 6-foot-5 actor with a honey-dipped drawl, Thompson certainly looks the part, and he's got a solid conservative voting record to match, even if that record lacks major legislative accomplishments or executive experience. The idea of a Thompson candidacy has enticed some voters enough to push him into third place in national polls -- ahead of former Massachusetts Gov. Mitt Romney, who several analysts said yesterday has the most to lose if Thompson can pick up the conservative voters Romney is banking on. But Giuliani would suffer too if conservatives rally to Thompson's side and see in him what they have seen in the ex-mayor -- an electable candidate with the aura of celebrity. In Thompson's case, he has the added benefit of being in line with conservatives on issues like abortion and gun control, unlike Giuliani. "One of Giuliani's great strengths is that there was nobody in the race who could consolidate party support, and if Thompson does prove to be a strong candidate, he may be suddenly able to galvanize the right, which would be a problem for the mayor," said Stu Rothenberg, an independent political analyst in Washington. Giuliani Wednesday welcomed a Thompson candidacy. "He has a great deal to offer," Giuliani said. "We'll all get a chance to make our point and I'm very comfortable with the idea that the Republican Party members get to decide who the candidate's going to be." Early polling on the race has suggested that a Thompson entry would draw voters away from Giuliani -- with a CNN poll earlier this month showing Giuliani dropping 9 points since March, while Thompson moved from zero in March to 13. A Quinnipiac poll this month showed Giuliani down 13 points and .Thompson up 14 since February. Rep. Peter King (R-Seaford), a former backer of John McCain in 2000 who is now supporting Giuliani, said .Thompson's entry would cause problems for the Arizona senator because they have an almost identical voting record. He acknowledged Thompson could cause problems for Giuliani down the line as well, but said he believes voters will see the difference between real life and TV when they are looking for a strong leader. "Rudy had 9/11, and Fred .Thompson had 'Law & Order,'" King said. Subscribe to Newsday home delivery Article licensing and reprint options Post a comment |
