http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-6&fd=R&url=http://www.news24.com/News24/World/Iraq/0,,2-10-1460_2121942,00.html&cid=1116836088&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ &#39;Tough&#39; month in Iraq - Pentagon: World: Iraqi Dossier: News24 &#39;Tough&#39; month in Iraq - Pentagon Iraq's bloodshed is inflicting deep and lasting wounds on its children - both physically and psychologically. Experts fear that less dangerous bird flu subtypes such as H7N2 could spark the next flu pandemic. &#39;Tough&#39; month in Iraq - Pentagon Iraq 'least peaceful country' Bush hails US war-dead Pentagon limits web for troops No al-Qaeda, Saddam link 'Pentagon hacker' loses appeal More US troops for Iraq Gates takes over Pentagon Washington - The Pentagon admitted on Wednesday that May has been "tough" for US forces in Iraq, with no fewer than 113 soldiers killed over the course of the month. "First and foremost, it&#39;s been a tough month," Brigadier General Perry Wiggins, deputy director of regional operations with the US Joint Chiefs of Staff, told reporters at a Defence Department briefing. May has been one of the deadliest months for US troops in Iraq. The deadliest was November of 2004, when 137 US troops died in Iraq, followed by April 2004 with 135. Wiggins said that the higher casualties were not entirely unexpected, given the "operational risks" associated with President George W Bush&#39;s "surge" of thousands of additional American troops into some of Iraq&#39;s most dangerous hotspots. "We&#39;re moving into places where we haven&#39;t been, not necessarily before," Wiggins said. "We&#39;re having more contacts with the enemy." At least 3 465 US forces have died in Iraq since the March 2003 US-led invasion, many while fighting the ongoing insurgency there. News24 is now available on your cellphone. -- Top stories in this category -- &#39;Tough&#39; month in Iraq - Pentagon Three Iraqi journos murdered Iraq &#39;least peaceful country&#39; Britain won&#39;t give in - Blair
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-5&fd=R&url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200705310079.html&cid=1116767788&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ allAfrica.com: South Africa: Urges for Unbiased Actions on Lebanon (Page 1 of 1) Use our pull-down menus to find more stories São Tomé and Príncipe Asia, Australia, and Africa Latin America and Africa Middle East and Africa U.S., Canada and Africa Enter your search terms South Africa: Urges for Unbiased Actions on Lebanon Posted to the web 31 May 2007 South Africa has called for unbiased actions from the United Nations Security Council regarding Lebanon, and has thus abstained from voting on the current resolution regarding the Middle Eastern nation. "In this regard we believe that the Security Council must act on behalf of the international community impartially and without any political bias," the Department of Foreign Affairs said in a statement on the resolution which was tabled Wednesday. "South Africa as a matter of principle abstained on voting for the current resolution on Lebanon in the Security Council." The resolution imposes the formation of a Special Tribunal to prosecute any people identified by the Lebanese authorities and the United Nations International Independent Investigation Commission, as suspects in the assassination of the former Prime Minister of Lebanon, Rafiq Hariri and other prominent Lebanese leaders. South Africa embarked on the first year of its two-year non-permanent tenure in the Security Council in January, and was Council President in March. Following Mr Hariri&#39;s death as a result of a car bomb in 2005, President Thabo Mbeki extended South Africa&#39;s heartfelt condolences to the government and the people of Lebanon. Mr Hariri was also a major stakeholer in the mobile phone service provider, Cell-C. South Africa believes imposing the Special Tribunal under the current circumstances will detrimentally affect the political stability of the already fragile Lebanese State, explained the department. Further to this, the move would politicise international criminal law and thus undermine the very foundations of international law. "South Africa, joins other members of the Security Council in calling for the Lebanese ownership of the process and for the Security Council to respect the sovereignty and constitution of Lebanon and to refrain from taking sides in internal Lebanese politics," said the department. "For South Africa, the key principle is that all violators of international law including international humanitarian law in Lebanon are brought to justice and not only those who perpetrate criminal acts against one faction within Lebanon." Following Wednesday&#39;s vote, Government reiterated its strong condemnation of the assassination of former Prime Minister and called for a thorough investigation into the incident. "In this regard there exists general consensus within Lebanon and internationally for the UN to assist the Lebanese authorities in their efforts to bring to justice those responsible for this heinous act," the department said. "There is also widespread support for the creation of a Special Tribunal based outside Lebanon and composed of both international and Lebanese judges as well as prosecutors." Accordingly South Africa supports the need for a Special Tribunal to ensure those responsible for these horrific crimes to be brought to justice. "However, our view is that the Tribunal should be the product of consensus within Lebanon as required by the Lebanese constitution and not an imposition of the Security Council," the department said. During another major Security Council vote in January, South Africa voted against a draft resolution regarding the situation in Myanmar, the former Burma. The country views the situation there as a human rights issue which should be handled by the proper organ within the UN, namely the UN Human Rights Council. Political analyst at the University of South Africa, Jo-Ansie van Wyk told BuaNews that South Africa&#39;s decision was in line with its foreign policy. "In terms of its foreign policy, South Africa wants to use the right organs for the right issues and its decision to vote against the resolution is about playing by the rules," Ms Van Wyk said. "The issue is work specific to the UN Human Rights Council, which is why South Africa is against the burdening of other UN organs with work that is outside their mandate." The resolution also called for the release of Myanmar&#39;s Nobel Peace Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi, which Mr Pahad said South Africa supported. During South Africa&#39;s tenure as Council President in March, an important resolution was also tabled regarding Iran&#39;s nuclear energy programme. Adopting resolution 1747 (2007), submitted by France, Germany and the United Kingdom, the Council affirmed its decision that Iran should suspend all enrichment-related and reprocessing activities, including research and development, to be verified by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). International Organizations and Africa Middle East and Africa This resulted in the Security Council widening the scope of its December 2006 sanctions against Iran for its refusal to abandon all its Uranium enrichment-related and reprocessing activities. However, before the resolution was adopted, South Africa, later joined by Indonesia, had called for certain amendments to be made to the draft resolution to make it "proportionate, incremental and reversible" for the Council, said South Africa&#39;s Ambassador to the UN Dumisani Kumalo. South Africa has long supported Iran&#39;s and other nations&#39; use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes, and is a signatory of the Nuclear Non-proliferation treaty. &copy; 2007 BuaNews. All rights reserved. Distributed by AllAfrica Global Media ( ). To contact the copyright holder directly for corrections -- or for permission to republish or make other authorized use of this material, aggregates and indexes content from over 125 African news organizations , plus more than , who are responsible for their own reporting and views. Articles and commentaries that identify as the publisher are produced or commissioned by AllAfrica Make allAfrica.com your home page International Organizations and Africa Middle East and Africa Govt Lauds New World Bank President Unions Deny Talks Breakthrough UK Premier Blair Pushes Partnerships Inflation Soars Above Central Bank Limit Govt Presents "New Dispensation" in Wage Talks
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-6&fd=R&url=http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/topstories.aspx%3FID%3DBD4A479594&cid=1116788973&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ Business Day - News Worth Knowing Thursday, 31 May 2007 Â - Economy & Business Â - Comment & Analysis Â - The Bottom Line Â - Technology @ Work Posted to the web on: 31 May 2007 Zoellick must hit ground runningÂ  WILL newly anointed World Bank president Robert Zoellick be able to get the organisation back on its feet after the failed presidency of Paul Wolfowitz? Although hardly a megawatt star , he brings positive attributes to the job. First, as a key player in bringing China into the World Trade Organisation, Zoellick is a proven internationalist in a US administration in which internationalists have sometimes seemed like an endangered species. Second, he is a firm believer in the power of markets and free trade, which have clearly done far more to alleviate poverty over the past half-century than any aid programme. Third, he seems to have been a consistent behind the scenes supporter of the World Bank, whereas many of his Bush administration colleagues would be just as happy to see it shut down and its Washington headquarters turned into private condominiums and offices. So, presumably, he has a constructive vision for the bank&#x2019;s future. But Zoellick is not without his weaknesses. First and foremost, his appointment extends the outmoded practice of always installing an American in the job. With the bank tirelessly preaching the merits of good governance, its failure to adopt democratic principles undercuts its own legitimacy. The claim that the World Bank needs an American president to ensure that the US keeps donating money is ridiculous. The annual cost of the US contribution to the World Bank is relatively minor. Any number of developing countries, from China to Brazil, could easily step up if the US foolishly stepped down. Zoellick&#x2019;s background as a lawyer hardly makes him perfect for the job, either. The World Bank presidency is not about negotiating treaties, as Zoellick did when he was US trade representative. The bank&#x2019;s most important role in development today is as a &#x201C;knowledge bank&#x201D; that helps aggregate, distill and disseminate best practices from around the world. In this respect, the bank&#x2019;s technical assistance to governments is very similar to what private consultants offer to companies. Moreover, many of the World Bank president&#x2019;s most important decisions involve economics in an essential way. Wrong economic decisions, such as in the 1970s when Robert McNamara pushed grandiose but environmentally devastating infrastructure projects, have haunted the bank for decades. The biggest question mark, though, is whether Zoellick will be able to hit the ground running and implement desperately needed reforms. Reform number one, of course, is to ensure that the next World Bank president is not an American. Rodrigo de Rato, Zoellick&#x2019;s counterpart at the European-dominated International Monetary Fund (IMF), has already suggested that his successor should be chosen in a more inclusive process. The bank should be ashamed that its president has not yet offered a similar proposal. Second, Zoellick should ask why the bank spends only 2,5% of its budget on the &#x201C;knowledge bank&#x201D; research function it trumpets in its external relations materials, while it spends three times that amount on maintaining its executive board. Third, Zoellick should use his formidable negotiating skills to cajole rich countries into greatly increasing the grant component of World Bank aid. The idea that a big government-guaranteed global bank is needed to fill holes in private capital markets is laughable nowadays. True, the bank&#x2019;s poorest clients have little access to private capital markets. By and large, however, the poorest countries need grants, not loans that they still won&#x2019;t be able to pay in 20 years. As the bank switches from loans to grants, it can use some of its massive retained earnings to endow its &#x201C;knowledge bank&#x201D; function and related technical advice. But all this knowledge shouldn&#x2019;t be free. A lot of technical advice falls on deaf ears, with countries listening only long enough to get their hands on bank money. Instead of merely pushing its agenda, the bank should start charging for its technical advice on a graduated scale so that more of its engagements are client-driven. Last but not least, the bank needs to play a much bigger role in environmental issues and, in general, in promoting good international citizenship. Of course, Zoellick could just attempt to fill the role symbolically and do little or nothing, as some of his predecessors have done. Or, less likely, he could embrace some megalomaniacal vision of government intervention, as others have tried. In any case, let&#x2019;s wish him luck. The world needs the World Bank a lot more than it needs another condominium. Project Syndicate, 2007. www.project-syndicate.org. n Rogoff is professor of economics and public policy at Harvard University, and was chief economist at the IMF. BDFM Publishers (Pty) Ltd disclaims all liability for any loss, damage, injury or expense however caused, arising from the use of or reliance upon, in any manner, the information provided through this service and does not warrant the truth, accuracy or completeness of the information provided. Copyright Â© 2005 BDFM Publishers (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved
