http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-0&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/05/30/america/NA-GEN-US-Cuba.php&cid=1116704827&ei=muxeRumXK4OUrgO0p8XXDQ White House shrugs off Castro&#039;s comments on Bush, U.S. - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings White House shrugs off Castro&#039;s comments on Bush, U.S. Published: May 30, 2007 The White House expressed indifference Wednesday about a recent string of editorials signed by Fidel Castro criticizing the U.S. and suggesting President George W. Bush wants him dead. "Oh, my goodness," White House press secretary Tony Snow said at a news conference when asked about Castro&#039;s comments. Prompted to elaborate on whether the Bush administration is concerned, Snow added: "It&#039;s Fidel Castro." He said nothing more on the subject. The 80-year-old Castro, who has not been seen in public since becoming ill more than 10 months ago, said in an editorial published Tuesday on the front page of the Communist Party daily Granma that Bush was waiting for him to die but could not kill his ideas. "I&#039;m not the first, nor will I be the last, who Bush has ordered to be deprived of life," Castro wrote. Bush urges 15 major countries set global emission goal by 2008 Zoellick has new agenda for World Bank Bush calls on Congress to increase funds for fighting AIDS Called "Reflections of the Commander in Chief," the Cuban leader&#039;s opinion pieces are becoming an almost-daily staple in Granma. Also Tuesday, Castro lambasted Bush for opposing the European Union&#039;s goal for an agreement on carbon emissions at next week&#039;s Group of Eight summit, and criticized both Britain and the United States for heavy military expenditures. Castro shocked Cuba on July 31 when he announced that he had undergone emergency intestinal surgery and was stepping aside provisionally for his younger brother Raul, the defense minister, during his recovery. Although senior Cuban officials have said Castro is on the mend, it seems more unlikely with time that the bearded leader will return to power. In one of his essays earlier this month, Castro offered a few new details about illness, saying that he had numerous operations and that the first procedure did not go well. Castro&#039;s exact ailment and condition remain state secrets, but he is widely believed to suffer from diverticular disease, which causes sacs in the colon that can become inflamed and bleed. Snow&#039;s comments came after U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice recently accused Cuba of trying to impose a non-democratic transition of power, and criticized Spain for commercial and economic ties that she said are not helping to bring democracy to the Caribbean island. She said Cuba would be "one of the most important" topics of discussion during a meeting with Spanish Prime Minister Jose Luiz Rodriguez Zapatero in Madrid, the last stop on her European tour. French presidency gets a bold new style Man with rare tuberculosis tells his tale Naples&#39;s trash is a challenge politicians are flunking Jihadist groups fill a Palestinian power vacuum Russia worried over UN plans for Kosovo independence Ernst & Young Won&#39;t Face Criminal Charges Thai court orders dissolution of ex-prime minister&#39;s party Gorbachev lends hand to book by Putin critic Turkey masses troops at border with Kurdish Iraq Poison used in China is found in U.S.-made animal feed With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow France&#39;s universities could be first test for Sarkozy Algeria&#39;s quiet revolution: Gains by women How the body (and mind) learns a dance With measure of caution, Europe joins biofuel gold rush Letter From China: China building gigantic cit