enate. Like James Buchanan, Thompson has no recent record of his views on the divisive issues of the day&#8211;especially those issues that divide Republicans. This would be clever posturing if he looked like Charlton Heston, but Thompson doesn&#8217;t look like a hairy Moses. He doesn&#8217;t even look like a fourth generation member of the old eastern establishment posing as a Texas hick. Thompson looks like Grandpa Munster or Elmer Fudd without the animation and speech impediment. Better for the Republicans to choose Sam Waterson, with his full head of hair, if their coalition needs a political non-entity to keep it from self-destructing. God forbid that the nation actually pick someone whose experience prepares him to govern and whose personality suggests leadership rather than clever, flexible pandering&#8211;you know, play-acting a part. Why is nobody with a mustache running? Oh yeah, Teddy Roosevelt&#8217;s daughter Alice put a hex on presidential mustaches&#8211;the &#8220;man on the wedding cake&#8221; joke. If only someone could come up with a good joke about actors who seek real world power. â€” Posted by IssyWise Mr. Brownback&#8217;s Op-Ed demonstrates yet again the religionist claim to authority that has no substantiation in reality to make certain things non-negotiable. It&#8217;s a shield for irrationality and unresponsiveness, constructed out of nothing. It is simply a fraudulent falsehood to assert that there is a &#8220;guiding intelligence&#8221; to the universe and you are privy to its intentions, as Brownback baldly claims. I see nothing in either Mr. Obama&#8217;s nor Mr. Romney&#8217;s foreign relations essays that suggests they have any awareness of the damage done to the international rule of law by Bush&#8217;s Iraq invasion on a trumped-up false pretext, and the need for the US to demonstrate to the world that we can contain our own war criminals as we maintain the world&#8217;s biggest arsenal. â€” Posted by Steve Bolger Fred said he wan