http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-3&fd=R&url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/storm/content/state/epaper/2007/05/31/0531storm_prepare.html&cid=1116729647&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Poll: Most in strike zones don't feel threatened by hurricanes Jose Lambiet's Page Two PDAs & Cell Phones Poll: Most in strike zones don't feel threatened by hurricanes Palm Beach Post Staff Writer Thursday, May 31, 2007 MIAMI &mdash; Despite a rash of devastating storms in recent years, more than half of those in America&#39;s hurricane strike zones don&#39;t feel threatened by a hurricane, according to a new poll. Meteorologists, state and local leaders, emergency managers, and representatives of social groups met today at the National Hurricane Center, west of Miami, to kick of the hurricane season, which starts Friday. Audio and video clips News on PDAs, cellphones Double trouble: 2 storms form! Oh, did I mention they&#8217;re both in the Pacific? And they&#8217;re heading away from land? ... Join Bob King's blog Sound off on the forum Everything you need to know to keep yourself and family safe: Should you stay or go? June 9-10 in WPB S. Fla. emergency resources Site map and A-Z guide P.B. County, TCoast news &#34;Our nation is a vulnerable nation,&#34; center Director Bill Proenza said. &#34;Most people along our nation&#39;s coastline have little or no experience with hurricanes or tropical storms. We indeed have a challenge ahead.&#34; With Gov. Charlie Crist in Israel, Lt. Gov. Jeff Kottkamp was on hand to offer a reminder that a tax holiday on many hurricane supplies runs from Friday through June 12. &#34;The overwhelming message we have today is preparation,&#34; Kottkamp said. &#34;You can either get ready now,&#34; state emergency director Craig Fugate said, &#34;or wait until disaster strikes and not have options.&#34; Fugate conceded it&#39;s difficult for low-income, disabled, the elderly and others to prepare. &#34;It&#39;s for the rest of us who should have and could have,&#34; Fugate said. &#34;We&#39;re making them (the vulnerable) compete with us for resources.&#34; The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration has predicted an above normal season, with 13 to 17 storms reaching at least tropical storm status, seven to 10 of those becoming hurricanes, and three to five becoming major storms, of Category Three or higher on the Saffir-Simpson Scale. Of 1,100 adults surveyed by the Mason-Dixon poll in mid-May in Atlantic and Gulf states: *53 percent said they don&#39;t feel vulnerable to hurricanes or related tornadoes. *52 percent have no family plan, and 61 percent have no hurricane survival kit. *88 percent have taken no steps to make their homes stronger *One in four said they would not start to prepare until hurricanes were 24 to 36 hours away. One in five said they&#39;d wait until 24 hours. *11 percent say they&#39;re responsible for a disabled or elderly person, but one third of those said they had no plan for that person. *16 percent said they might not or would not leave even if ordered to do so. Thirty percent said that, if they left, they&#39;d travel not to friends or relatives nearby but as far as they could go. Emergency managers fear a scenario in which cars stuck in gridlock are wiped out by a storm. *43 percent said they wouldn&#39;t wait for an all clear before heading home. *One in five believed it was the government&#39;s responsibility to provide supplies in the first few days, or weren&#39;t sure who was responsible. Emergency managers have said families need to have everything they&#39;ll need for three to five days on their own. *78 percent said they did not know storm surge is the greatest killer in a storm. *Nearly eight in 10 did not know predicting changes in strength is the weakest part of hurricane forecasting. *More than half believed tornados can occur only within three miles of a storm. Actually, a hurricane can spawn tornadoes hundreds of miles away. *96 percent did not know garage doors are the part of a home most likely to fail. Nearly half still believe masking tape will keep windows from shattering. *21 percent said they weren&#39;t sure their homeowner&#39;s insurance policy included replacement coverage. More than four in 10 had not reviewed their insurance policies with an agent in the past year, some in more than five years. A fourth did not know standard policies don&#39;t cover flooding and homes need a separate federal flood insurance policy. What are your responses to some of the questions posed in the Mason-Dixon survey. Do you prepare for hurricanes when they are more than 24 hours away? Voter Limit: Once per Hour If you are responsible for a disable or elderly person, do you have a plan for them? Voter Limit: Once per Hour Would you leave your home if ordered to do so? Voter Limit: Once per Hour Is it the government's responsibility to provide supplies in the first few days? Voter Limit: Once per Hour Do you believe masking tape will keep your windows from shattering? Voter Limit: Once per Hour Does your homeowners insurance policy include replacement coverage? Voter Limit: Once per Hour Place An Ad 24/7 ad with color photos Copyright &copy; 2007, The Palm Beach Post. All rights reserved. By using PalmBeachPost.com, you accept the terms of our visitor agreement. Advertise with The Post
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-6&fd=R&url=http://voanews.com/english/2007-05-31-voa8.cfm&cid=1116756038&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ VOA News - Rice Says Iran Must Change Course on Nuclear Issue, Halt Uranium Enrichment A trusted source of news and information since 1942 Rice Says Iran Must Change Course on Nuclear Issue, Halt Uranium Enrichment U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice says it is time for Iran to change its tactics on the nuclear issue and stop enriching uranium. Speaking to reporters in Vienna Thursday - on the sidelines of a women's empowerment conference, Rice said the international community wants Iran to demonstrate that it is not seeking a nuclear weapon. Despite limited U.N. sanctions and a possibility of a tougher penalties, Tehran has continued to ignore U.N. demands to stop its uranium enrichment -- a process that can be used to make nuclear weapons. Iran's top nuclear negotiator Ali Larijani and European Union foreign policy chief Javier Solana are to meet in Madrid Thursday for another round of talks to try to resolve issue. Larijani says suspension of enrichment activity is not a way to resolve the dispute. On Wednesday, foreign ministers from the Group of Eight industrialized nations: Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Russia and the United States, renewed calls for Iran to stop uranium enrichment or face "appropriate measures." The United States and its allies accuse Iran of trying to develop nuclear weapons. Tehran says its program is for peaceful, civilian use. Some information for this report was provided by AFP, AP and Reuters. Larijani: Halting Uranium Enrichment Not Acceptable to Iran G-8 Threatens New Measures Unless Iran Halts Nuclear Enrichment Iran's Crackdown on Visiting Iranian-Americans Raises More Questions About Tehran's Agenda Suicide Bombing in Fallujah Kills 20 US: Iran Jails Third Iranian-American Sporadic Fighting at Lebanese Refugee Camp Continues Suspect in Litvinenko Murder Says Former Ru