a talks one on one with WQAD's Matt Hammill Associated Press - May 30, 2007 2:44 PM ET NEW YORK (AP) - The American Civil Liberties Union is suing a company called Jeppesen Dataplan, claiming it secretly flew 3 of the CIA's terrorism suspects overseas, where they were tortured. The cases involve allegations of mistreatment of men from Ethiopia, Italy and Egypt. Jeppesen spokesman Mike Pound says company officials hadn't seen the lawsuit and had no immediate comment. Jeppesen is a subsidiary of Boeing Commercial Aviation Services, and Pound says it provides support services, rather than the flights themselves. But ACLU attorney Ben Wizner says Jeppesen couldn't have been ignorant of the purpose of the CIA flights. Chicago-based Boeing itself isn't named in the lawsuit. Boeing spokesman Tim Neale says company officials typically don't comment on lawsuits and hadn't seen this one. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. News from the heartland of Illinois and Iowa. Business headlines, stock prices, and financial tips. Headlines from in, around and dealing with the classroom. City By City Online News, links, and information for your community. WQAD.com covers 32 counties in eastern Iowa and western Illinois. Healthy Quad Cities May Early diagnosis and appropriate management of arthritis, including self-management activities, can help people with arthritis decrease pain, improve function, stay productive, and lower health care costs. Take a test drive of the Dutchman Express-Extended, the Kodiak Expandable or Pilgrim Fifth Wheel from Kamper Korner. Eat Local for Less We&#39;ve worked out deals with some of our area&#39;s best restaurants to give you 1/2 off gift certificates - $50 gift certificates for only $25! But you have to be fast - there are only a limited number of gift certificates. Download the Weather Wizard Powerful weather tools, current conditions, news headlines, an