http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-5&fd=R&url=http://www.ireland.com/newspaper/breaking/2007/0530/breaking62.htm&cid=1116788973&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ ireland.com - Breaking News - US nominates Zoellick as WB president Wednesday, May 30, 2007 Last Updated: 30/05/2007&#160; 16:24 US nominates Zoellick as WB president US President George Bush has nominated former US trade envoy Robert Zoellick as the next World Bank president. Mr Zoellick (53) would succeed Paul Wolfowitz, who is stepping down June 30th after findings by a special bank panel that he broke bank rules when he arranged a hefty compensation package in 2005 for his girlfriend, Shaha Riza, a bank employee. He is a great defender of free trade and in any case he will not be worse than Wolfowitz. He knows the subject. He is a man who is suited to the task, unlike his predecessor. Tunisian economics expert Rida el Kefi The controversy led to calls for Mr Wolfowitz to resign from the poverty-fighting institution. A seasoned veteran of politics both inside Washington and on the international stage, Mr Zoellick is known for pulling facts and figures off the top of his head. Mr Bush's selection of Mr Zoellick must be approved by the World Bank's 24-member board. Some African leader&#160;today expressed disappointment at the US decision to nominate Mr Zoellick. After decades of Americans heading the international lender, many on the world's poorest continent felt their time had come to play a key role - and then been snatched away. "Look at the United Nations. When Africans had one of their own leading it, they felt so much closer to the organisation," Kenyan political scientist Ludeki Chweya said, referring to Ghana's Kofi Annan, who was UN secretary-general for a decade. "Such an appointment would give the impression that the Bank might just become a bit more sensitive to the needs and particularities of Africa." Mr Wolfowitz - already derided by many as a key architect of the Iraq war - stepped down after it was revealed he had authorised a hefty pay rise for his companion. Despite unwavering support from the White House until the very end, he gave up a weeks-long fight to cling onto his job and tendered his resignation two weeks ago. Some acknowledged Mr Zoellick would benefit from years of experience negotiating trade deals with developing nations. "He is a great defender of free trade and in any case he will not be worse than Wolfowitz," Tunisian economics expert Rida el Kefi said. "He knows the subject. He is a man who is suited to the task, unlike his predecessor." Others noted Mr Zoellick's diplomatic experience in Africa. As deputy to Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice he helped guide the Bush admininstration's strategy on Darfur. But some were angered by what they saw as US arrogance. Email to a Friend Email to a Friend Do you think house prices will start to rise again when proposed stamp duty reform takes place? Click a date to view the paper on that day The Irish Times Breaking News Alert, a lunchtime (GMT) roundup of breaking news 5 days a week to your mailbox. Click here to subscribe Images of the Day The day's best pictures chosen by The Irish Times picture editor.
http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/un-vote-hariri-suspects-to-be-tried/2007/05/31/1180205431409.html&cid UN vote: Hariri suspects to be tried - World - smh.com.au Welcome to The Sydney Morning Herald. UN vote: Hariri suspects to be tried Success &#133; cheering Lebanese Government supporters celebrate after the UN voted to set up an international court to try Rafiq Hariri's murder suspects. Jihadists fill void left by warring Palestinian factions Maggie Farley in New York IN A challenge to Syria, the United Nations Security Council narrowly approved an international tribunal to prosecute suspects in the assassination of a former Lebanese prime minister. But the move was opposed by Russia and China, which fear UN "interference" will inflame tensions in Lebanon. The special court to prosecute suspects in the 2005 killing of Rafiq Hariri won 10 votes, one more than necessary for approval. Russia, China, Qatar, Indonesia and South Africa abstained. "By adopting this resolution, the council has demonstrated its commitment to the principle that there shall be no impunity for political assassinations in Lebanon or elsewhere," the US ambassador to the UN, Zalmay Khalilzad, said on Wednesday. Mr Hariri, who served two terms as prime minister, and 22 others were killed by a truck bomb in Beirut on February 14, 2005. His murder sparked protests that helped push Syrian troops out of Lebanon after 29 years. The tribunal is the culmination of a UN-sponsored investigation into Mr Hariri's killing and 14 other political murders that appear to be related. But the issue of the tribunal has deadlocked the Lebanese parliament for months, pitting the Prime Minister, Fouad Siniora, against the President, Emile Lahoud, who opposes the tribunal. The battle reflects the struggle for political control of the country between factions close to Syria, and those who want to forge an independent nation. Many Lebanese believe that internal struggle led to the assassination of Mr Hariri, who had resigned as prime minister in 2004 in a dispute over Syrian troop presence in Lebanon. The UN's investigation tentatively linked Syrian officials to the crime. But Syria denies responsibility and has refused to co-operate fully with the "politicised" international court. Syria's ambassador to the UN, Bashar Jaafari, said Wednesday's vote amounted to interference in Lebanon's affairs. "Definitely this is something that goes against the interests of the Lebanese people and Lebanon as a whole," he said after the vote. The slain prime minister's son, the MP Saad Hariri, thanked the Security Council for its decision in a televised address to the nation. "This tribunal is for all of you," he said. "It's the gate to redemption from this long line of crimes. This is a moment for unity." Hezbollah, the radical Shiite Muslim group supported by Syria, also opposes the tribunal. The group has 14 seats in Lebanon's 128-member parliament and has organised mass protests to oust Mr Siniora. Gunfire and fireworks broke out in several parts of Lebanon within minutes of the decision. The French ambassador, Jean-Marc de la Sabliere, said it might take a year to establish the tribunal, which involves finding international judges, a prosecutor, financing and a venue outside Lebanon. The US-Russia disagreement over Lebanon spilled into meetings of Group of Eight foreign ministers prior to the start of the summit in Germany next week. Russia's Foreign Minister, Sergei Lavrov, and the US Secretary of State, Condoleezza Rice, had a brief but testy exchange at a press conference over US weapons shipments to the Lebanese Army, which is fighting Islamic militants at a refugee camp near Tripoli. send photos, videos & tip-offs to 0424 SMS SMH (+61 424 767 764), or us. on home delivery of the Herald - subscribe today Jihadists fill void left by warring Palestinian factions UN vote: Hariri suspects to be tried Maggie Farley in New York Success &#133; cheering Lebanese Government supporters celebrate af