http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-3&fd=R&url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-05/31/content_6180480.htm&cid=1116842015&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Tony Blair visits S Africa amid applause, expectation JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing British Prime Minister Tony Blair started his last visit to South Africa on Thursday amid applauses for his efforts to highlight Africa agenda globally and expectations on his successor to carry forward his legacy. Blair arrived in Johannesburg on Thursday morning for the two-day visit, the final leg of his so-called "farewell" African trip also to Libya and Sierra Leone, before his departure from office on June 27. Blair is expected to hold discussions with South African President Thabo Mbeki on Friday, and will deliver a major policy speech focusing on Africa, the South African foreign ministry said. He will also meet with former president and anti-apartheid leader Nelson Mandela, and visit a hospital in Soweto, Johannesburg's famous black township on Thursday. The 54-year-old prime minister is expected to elaborate his plan to launch a foundation after he steps down, which will reportedly focus on aid, primary school education, health and fair global trade for Africa. His visit has been greeted with praises on his strong leadership and efforts to set the agenda on Africa during his decade in power. Calling Blair "a great friend of Africa," South African scholar Kuseni Dlamini said he had helped "position Africa's development on the radar screen of global public opinion." He has famously called Africa's problems of poverty, disease, trade injustice and conflict "a scar on the conscience of the world." Blair championed the Commission for Africa and consistently emphasized the importance of Africa's development by designating the year 2005 as the Year of Africa, when Britain chaired the G8 (Group of Eight industrialized countries) Summit. He persuaded his fellow G8 leaders in 2005 to wipe out most of Africa's debt and to double their international development aid to 50 billion U.S. dollars by 2010. Blair also won plaudits for sending British troops to help restore order in Sierra Leone after a bitter 10-year civil conflict. "For we Africans, he (Blair) will remain a figure of stature --despite his faults and detractors in other theaters," BhekiKhumalo, President Mbeki's former spokesman at the height of Blair's premiership, wrote in an article published by the Business Day newspaper on Thursday. In Iraq and the Middle East issues Blair stood accused of uncritical support of the United States. But "Iraq aside, history will judge Blair kindly for his contribution to a better Africa," said Dlamini at the South African Institute of International Affairs. Blair told South Africa's Sunday Times newspaper earlier that he would discuss with President Mbeki on how Africa would remain at the top of the UK's agenda after his departure, Africa's security issues and the crisis in Zimbabwe. He said his greatest disappointment during his work on Africa was that "we haven't yet hammered out a trade deal which is fair to everyone." African countries complained that the huge increases in aid announced in 2005 have yet to materialize and global trade rules remain weighted against poor nations, though the debt relief goals have largely been met. Pretoria said on Wednesday Blair's visit will afford an opportunity for both sides to review bilateral political, economic and trade relations and how they can be deepened in a post-Blairera. "The British Government views South Africa as a major strategic partner in Africa and South Africa expects that this relationship will be consolidated by Prime Minister Blair's successor," Foreign Ministry spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said. Bheki Khumalo also said: "As Africans, we look to Blair's equally able successor, who will build on this prime minister's strong bequest, and perhaps even strengthen it." Blair in S Africa for last visit Blair discusses challenges with Iraq Bush, Blair vow to keep co-op on int'l focuses Blair meets French president-elect Nicolas Sarkozy Blair meets French president-elect Nicolas Sarkozy
http://www.theage.com.au/news/world/law-and-order-tough-man-eyes-presidential-role/2007/05/31/1180205426510.html&cid Law and Order tough man eyes presidential role - World - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. Law and Order tough man eyes presidential role Thompson: Former senator and actor. AMERICANS who switched on their TV last night saw Fred Thompson, the tough-minded district attorney known as Arthur Branch, tell his colleagues to stick with their instincts on a case. But in real life Fred Thompson wants Americans to believe he'll bring those same leadership qualities to the highest office in the land: the presidency of the United States of America. After much speculation, Thompson, 64, has given his clearest signal yet that he will contest the Republican race. While he has stopped short of setting up an exploratory committee &#151; the formal step requiring lodgement of papers &#151; he told a conference of 100 supporters on Tuesday that he would "test the waters" and begin raising money and employing staff as early as today. Thompson, who in real life served as a Republican senator for Tennessee from 1994 to 2003, plans to run his campaign out of Nashville and has promised a conservative agenda, in line with fellow actor-turned-president Ronald Reagan. Thompson's entry is expected to have an immediate impact on the battle for the race for the Republican nomination, adding a fourth candidate to the field's top tier, which includes former New York mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Senator John McCain of Arizona and former Massachusetts governor Mitt Romney. All three have struggled to win the confidence of conservative Republicans. Thompson will attempt to make the case that he is the true heir to the mantle of Mr Reagan and, if successful, would become a formidable candidate for the nomination. Even though he has not yet entered the race, a CNN/Opinion Research Corp poll conducted on May 4-6 placed Thompson third among Republican candidates with 13 per cent of the vote. Mr Giuliani had the most support with 25 per cent, two percentage points ahead of Senator McCain. Mr Romney was fourth with 10 per cent. However, Mr Romney has gained ground in more recent polls and is now edging up on Senator McCain. Having left it relatively late to enter the race, Thompson now needs an error-free run and a strong start in key states such as Iowa and New Hampshire to gain the momentum he needs. "That's what the campaign will be all about for him &#151; persuading a significant portion of the party that he truly is the right leader for a set of issues and an outlook on the world," said Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster. An announcement could come as soon as the first week of July. As a lawmaker in the Senate, Thompson exuded a folksy charm but did not set the world on fire. But his decades of movie and television appearances will give him an immediate national presence. he will not return in September, although he did not indicate any political intentions, producer Dick Wolf said in a statement. Republican strategists predicted that Thompson would get an immediate boost in the polls by entering the race. When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! Law and Order tough man eyes presidential role Thompson: Former senator and actor. Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Age Company Ltd. Browse for a Date Spy murder suspect to reveal 'sensation' Xiang Xiang dies in wild Anti-whaling countries win vote Fourth prisoner suicide at Guantanamo Aussies face drug, sex charges in Dubai Soldiers killed as chopper goes down South Americans inch towards whale sanctuary Bush faces Zoellick challenge Thai judges ban exiled PM's 'dangerous' party NATO chopper goes down in Afghanistan Amnesty calls for effort to end Darfur crisis Loren lands in Oz Fans greet movie legend with flowers as she arrives for a film festival. Britney's ex to fund own second album 