m in southeast Last Tuesday's terror attack in the Turkish capital Ankara in which six people were killed and more than 100 were wounded was met with much fury in the Turkish street as well as in the cabinet. 's immediate response to the latest of a long series of Kurdish attacks was to increase its military build-up close to its border with . Twenty more tanks were sent to the border region, where the army is already engaged in an offensive against PKK rebels &ndash; still within has threatened a number of times in the past few months that it would invade if the latter did not put an end to PKK infiltrations. "The PKK must be eliminated as a problem between 's special envoy to , Oguz Celikkol, told CNN-Turk television station on Wednesday. "The [Iraqi] Kurds are fairly powerful, with about 70,000 fighters, probably the largest single most unified paramilitary force inside This paramilitary force is, however, no match for the Turkish army that could easily field 100,000 solders with the most advanced equipment, Brown adds. position regarding a Turkish invasion four years ago, it held preliminary discussions with its allies in the region, including , which asked to send 50,000 soldiers into to ensure the Kurds did not declare independence. , according to Brown, has strongly resisted the Turkish request. Such a move was likely to make the already impossible situation in even harder for the , as its two best allies &ndash; the Kurds and the Turks &ndash; are in conflict with each other. In the event that might have to take sides, and that would be awful for relations with the other side," says Brown. But this might well be the case if the KRG decides to take one more step and declare independence, or if the PKK launches more deadly attacks at the heart of does not wish to anger its ally, the It also has no desire to implicate itself in a protracted war in an inhospitable mountainous region, unless it absolutely has to. That is why 's Prime Minister Recep Teyyip Erdogan urged the on Tuesday to deal with the PKK bases in northern and to destroy them. Aware of the public's &ndash; as well the army's &ndash; unrest following the terror attack in , Erdogan did not rule out a unilateral cross-border Turkish operation. Meanwhile, adding fuel to the fire, a group of PKK gunmen attempted to cross the border into on Wednesday night. The Turkish security forces spotted them and opened fire in their direction. Two Turkish F-16 aircrafts were seen patrolling the region later on, as the border becomes increasingly agitated. Copyright © 2007 The Media Line. All Rights Reserved. copyright &copy; 2001- 2007 The Media Line. All Rights Reserved.
http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007506056&cid AHN | U.S. Military Says The Death Of Guantanamo Detainee Was Apparently A Suicide | May 31, 2007 global news for the digital world U.S. Military Says The Death Of Guantanamo Detainee Was Apparently A Suicide May 31, 2007 11:54 a.m. EST Shaveta Bansal - AHN Staff Writer Guantanamo, Cuba (AHN) - The U.S Military said that the Saudi Arabian detainee who was found dead in his cell at the Guanatanamo Bay prison facility in Cuba on Wednesday apparently committed suicide. If proved, it would be the fourth suicide case at the prison since it was opened following the September 11 terror attacks. In a statement released on its Website, the U.S. military's Southern Command said that the detainee was found unresponsive and not breathing in his cell by guards. A physician pronounced the detainee dead "after all lifesaving measures had been exhausted," it said. The statement went on to say an investigation into the circumstances surrounding the death was being held and that a cultural adviser was assisting the military to ensure that the remains of the deceased were handled in a culturally sensitive and religiously appropriate manner. The incident comes nearly a year after two Saudi detainees and one Yemeni hanged themselves with bed sheets. Since then, the military has taken various steps to tighten the security at the prison, including removing prisoners' access to light fixtures and other potential makeshift weapons and taking away bed sheets in the daytime, the Associated Press reports. However, critics of the detention facility say it is the inhumane treatment of prisoners at the camp and the surging level of frustration among detainees that leads to such incidents. The U.S. government established the detainment camp in January 2002, just few months after the September 11, 2001. The prison holds people suspected by the U.S. government of being al-Qaeda and Taliban operatives. Copyright © AHN Media Corp - All rights reserved. Redistribution, republication. syndication, rewriting or broadcast is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AHN. © 2007 by AHN Media Corp.
