http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007502687&cid AHN | 20 Militants In Lebanon Charged With Terrorism | May 31, 2007 global news for the digital world 20 Militants In Lebanon Charged With Terrorism May 31, 2007 5:28 a.m. EST Joseph S. Mayton - AHN Middle East Correspondent Cairo, Egypt (AHN) - The Lebanese government has charged 20 Fatah al Islam militants with terrorism as clashes between the army and the Palestinian group in northern Lebanon continue into the 11th day. According to reports, 19 Lebanese and one Syrian were charged with fighting around the Nahr al Bared refugee camp, which has killed 79 people, including 18 civilians. If convicted, the 20 charged could face the death penalty. Beirut accuses Fatah al Islam for starting the country's worst clashes since the end of the civil war that raged in Lebanon from 1975-1990. The fighting began on May 20 as the Lebanese Army began to bombard the refugee camp following a failed bank robbery linked to the group. The Lebanese government and analysts have argued that Fatah al Islam is connected with Al Qaeda. Beirut has continuously called for the militants to surrender. The Palestinian group has argued they are acting in self-defense and reject demands to hand over their fighters. The Red Crescent in Lebanon has said that the camp is virtually cut off from the outside world, with residents struggling to survive. They reported that there is no electricity in the camp; no running water and supplies are running dangerously low. Lebanese Prime Minister, Fouad Siniora, has repeatedly said the army will fight until the group is eradicated from Lebanese soil. Copyright © AHN Media Corp - All rights reserved. Redistribution, republication. syndication, rewriting or broadcast is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AHN. © 2007 by AHN Media Corp.
