ny steps to fortify their homes. Forty-five percent still believed the old wives' tale that masking tape helps keeps windows from shattering during hurricanes. But only a small amount of people -- 16% -- said they would defy orders to evacuate and ride out a hurricane in their homes. Public safety officials tell residents to stockpile at least a 3-day supply of bottled water, nonperishable food and medicine. Despite the predictions for a busy season, public safety officials worry that an uneventful 2006 lulled residents into complacency; there were only 10 named storms, and the two that hit the U.S. were weak. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Get more information on all the web tools we have available. Get some helpful homeowner hints from the do it yourself expert, Danny Lipford. Get the latest information on road conditions and arrivals and departures at the Greenville Spartanburg International Airport. This Week's Weather Pic Here you can send us your weather pictures or view this week&#39;s weather pic We&#39;re helping local law enforcement track down the Carolina&#39;s most wanted criminals. You can find our reports here. Heather On The Hunt Catch Heather on the Hunt every Friday on The Morning News. Click for an archive of Heather&#39;s latest hunts. All content &copy; Copyright 2001 - 2007 WorldNow and FOX CAROLINA. All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070531.wnewipper0531/BNStory/National/%3Fpage%3Drss%26id%3DRTGAM.20070531.wnewipper0531&cid globeandmail.com: Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says Letters to the Editor Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says TENILLE BONOGUORE AND BRODIE FENLON AND ANTHONY REINHART Globe and Mail Update May 31, 2007 at 12:41 PM EDT &#151; The Ontario Government has apologized for the events that led to Dudley George's death and pledged to move forward in honour of his memory. David Ramsay, Minister of Natural Resources and Aboriginal Affairs, announced the formation of an Ipperwash response team to implement the recommendations of Commissioner Sidney Linden in his inquiry report released Thursday. Mr. Ramsay said this was a &ldquo;turning point&rdquo; for the province, which will benefit all Ontarians. &ldquo;The message is clear. Only by working together can we achieve the common goal of prosperity and equal opportunity for Aboriginal people across this province,&rdquo; Mr. Ramsay said. Sept. 7, 1995. A spray painted sign at Ipperwash Provincial Park reflects Natives' anger about the 1995 confrontation that left protester Anthony O'Brien (Dudley) George dead. (The Globe and Mail) Aboriginal Affairs Minister David Ramsay speaks Ontario's aboriginal affairs minister talks with reporters following release of Ipperwash report Sam George comments on findings Dudley George's brother speaks with reporters following the release of Thursday's report Inquiry Commissioner Sidney Linden speaks Inquiry Commissioner speaks with reporters from Forest, Ont. Report a road map to unity, peace, aboriginal leaders say Murray Klippenstein on the Ipperwash Inquiry Report Bob Runciman on the Ipperwash Inquiry Report Storm of scandal to finally clear In the 1433-page report, Commissioner Linden offered a scathing review of Ontario Provincial Police operations on the night 38-year-old Dudley George was shot at Ipperwash Provincial Park. He apportions blame to federal and provincial governments as well as the OPP for the stand-off, and makes 98 recommendations that he hopes will help all peoples reach a path of healing. Minutes before the provincial apology, Dudley George's older brother Sam said he was hoping for an apology from Mike Harris, who was Premier at the time. Failing that, he said it was fitting for the province to apologize for him. &ldquo;What Mr. Harris did was act too fast, and closed off many options including negotiations, communications,&rdquo; Mr. George said. &ldquo;We hold him partially responsible for what happened, because of that acting too fast. &ldquo;We wonder if it might be appropriate at this time for Mr. Harris to apologize to my family, or maybe, if Mr. Harris chooses not to, for the government of Ontario to do so. Maybe that is not too much to ask.&rdquo; But Peter Downard, lawyer for Mr. Harris, immediately rejected calls for an apology. &ldquo;This commissioner has made it clear that no apology is required,&rdquo; Mr. Downard said in a testy exchange with reporters. &ldquo;As far as Mr. Harris is concerned, this commission has found specifically in the report that there's no evidence to suggest that either Premier Harris or any member of his government is responsible for the death of Dudley George.&rdquo; Prime among the report recommendations is a call to establish a stand-alone Aboriginal Affairs Ministry within the provincial cabinet, with adequate resources, and for the Federal Government to publicly apologize to the people of Kettle and Stony Point First Nation for failing to honour its promise to return its land. He also urged the creation of a treaty commission of Ontario to settle land and treaty claims, an Aboriginal Reconciliation Fund, more federal involvement with land claim disputes, and new regulations under the Police Services Act to ensure all government directions are in writing and made public to the Commissioner. Judge Linden calls for the OPP to make a public apology to Cecil Bergard George for the beating he sustained in the parking lot where Mr. George was fatally shot by police officer Ken Deane. But in his report, Judge Linden says the matter goes well beyond Mr. Deane and the Inspector who sent him in at 11 p.m. along with a riot squad and other specialist officers. The OPP as an institution also needs to be accountable and share responsibility for the tragedy, as does the Federal Government, he says. &ldquo;Unfortunately, the issues that were at the heart of the Ipperwash occupation remain unresolved by the federal government to this day. This inexcusable delay and long neglect, by successive federal governments, are at the heart of the Ipperwash story.&rdquo; Politically, the hotbed that was Queens Park after the 1995 election played a substantial role in proceedings by Lake Huron that night. Judge Linden found that Premier Mike Harris or someone in his office did convene a meeting on the evening of Sept. 6, 1995, commonly referred to as &ldquo;the dining room meeting&rdquo;. While he found that Mr. Harris did make the controversial comment that he &ldquo;wanted the fucking Indians out of the park&rdquo;, he questions exactly when that comment was made. It was Natural Resources Minister Chris Hodgson who said the same phrase the &ldquo;dining room meeting&rdquo;, Judge Linden said. The report also finds that Mr. Harris knew at least one person at the meeting was a seconded OPP officer, and that by the end of the meeting &ldquo;Premier Harris had made it clear he wanted the occupiers out of the park as quickly as possible.&rdquo; The Premier's comments in the dining room, and the speed at which he wanted a resolution, &ldquo;unduly narrowed the scope of the government's response&rdquo; and &ldquo;closed off many options endorsed by civil servants,&rdquo; Judge Linden said. And the Premier's push to have an immediate injunction and to remove the Indians from the park within 24 hours was inappropriate. &ldquo;It is for the police to decide whether and when arrests will be made.&rdquo; All of that &ldquo;created the risk of placing political pressure on the police&rdquo; when, in contrast, &ldquo;the Premier could have urged patience, rather than speed&rdquo;. But he concluded that the sum of those factors did not equate to political interference. &ldquo;In my view, although Premier Harris was critical of the police, I do not find that he interfered with or gave inappropriate directions to the police at Ipperwash,&rdquo; he wrote. &ldquo;The Premier did not inappropriately direct the OPP on its operations at Ipperwash or enter the law enforcement domain of the police.&rdquo; The Commissioner confirms that the natives were unarmed, and that Premier Harris and Attorney-General Charles Harnick misled the legislature about the &ldquo;dining room meeting&rdquo;. Julian Falconer, the lawyer representing Aboriginal Legal Services at the inquiry, said the report was &ldquo;historical&rdquo; in that Judge Linden rejected some of Mr. Harris' testimony. &ldquo;It is absolutely unprecedented for a commissioner to make a finding that expressly finds that both the premier and the attorney general misled the house about the key dining room meeting,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;That is a startling revelation and it is unprecedented that I know of for a commissioner to reject evidence under oath by a then premier.&rdquo; The actions of the Ontario Provincial Police were viewed scathingly by Judge Linden, whose references to &ldquo;critical failures&rdquo; on the night of Dudley George's shooting are wearyingly regular. Negotiators should have been called in first. Crowd Management Unit should not have been deployed at night. And, most importantly, the protesters should have been told that they were safe inside the fence. The police had no intention of entering the park. &ldquo;The CMU were busy yelling commands to each other when the officers should have been yelling these crucial messages to the Aboriginal people,&rdquo; Judge Linden wrote. Ontario Provincial Police lawyer Mark Sandler said the Ipperwash standoff was a catalyst for significant change within the force and that the OPP is one of the most progressive police services in the world in terms of aboriginal issues and policies. &ldquo;The OPP came to this inquiry a very different police force than it was 12 years ago,&rdquo; Mr. Sandler said. Judge Linden's criticisms hit upon many of the people mentioned during the Inquiry hearings, including the Premier's executive assistant Deb Hutton. &ldquo;Neither Deb Hutton nor Michael Harris fully appreciated at that time the power of the Premier and the Premier's office,&rdquo; he wrote. &ldquo;Regrettably, Ms. Hutton had little experience in aboriginal issues, nor did she have a sound understanding of Aboriginal culture, section 35 of the Constitution, or concepts such as colour of right.&rdquo; In response to the report, Ms. Hutton said the findings &ldquo;conclusively set to rest the unfounded allegations&rdquo; made since Dudley George's death. &ldquo;Commissioner Linden has made clear in his report that there was no political direction of the OPP,&rdquo; she said in a statement issued by her lawyer. As for the land itself, the Commissioner said allowing the status quo to continue is not in anyone's interest. Among the possibilities they could consider, he says, is the reopening of Ipperwash Park under the management of the Kettle Point and Stony Point communities, &ldquo;for the benefit of all Ontarians and visitors alike.&rdquo; On the question of reopening the park, Mr. Ramsay told reporters Thursday: &ldquo;That is not something I've been contemplating, so let's just leave it at that,&rdquo; Mr. Ramsay said. Comments are closed for this story | Send a letter to the editor Add TENILLE BONOGUORE AND BRODIE FENLON AND ANTHONY REINHART to my e-mail alerts Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Three Canadians blocked from hearings into ordeal Ottawa offers $125-million settle Caledonia dispute Go to the National section Blame the brats for untimely death of Sam the Record Man Union to pay for student's funeral A calm hand set to take the helm at World Bank Top Stories by Section CIBC profit rises sharply, but shares slip Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Hewitt rallies to reach third round A robust hit that never falters Alleged top world spammer arrested in Seattle A 40-year wait for wedded bliss Tories take another swipe at Dion Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Senators slide into 2-0 hole Has big business turned organics into 'yuppy chow'? Submit post to digg.com Seed this post at Newsvine Technorati links to this post A tag is a keyword or descriptive term supplied by our editorial staff used to associate related articles with one another. Tags make it easier for you to find other stories that share the same theme or topic with the article you&#8217;re currently reading. Globe Insider E-mail Alerts Have all subsequent stories by this writer e-mailed to you. Add TENILLE BONOGUORE AND BRODIE FENLON AND ANTHONY REINHART to my breaking news e-mail alerts What are e-mail alerts? What are e-mail Alerts? E-mail alerts deliver the news to your inbox as it happens. &#169; Copyright 2007 CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc. All Rights Reserved. The Globe and Mail are divisions of CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc.,
