http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-0&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/money/world/2007-05-30-zoellick-usat_N.htm&cid=1116788973&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Zoellick says unity, healing are World Bank goals - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Stock Market Answers: Ask Matt Test Drive: James R. Healey Managing Your Money Home Your Money: Sandra Block CD and Loan Rates Small Business Blog: Jim Hopkins Ask an Expert: Steve Strauss Entrepreneurial Tightrope: Gladys Edmunds Real solutions for your real estate needs. Choose from the selections below: Click here to begin Full service relocation assistance Apartments for rent in your area Need help financing or refinancing a home? NAME: Robert B. Zoellick EDUCATION: Master of Public Policy and J.D., Harvard University, 1981; B.A., Swarthmore College, 1975 EXPERIENCE: Executive at Goldman Sachs, 2006 to present; Deputy Secretary of State, Feb. 2005 to June 2006; U.S. Trade Representative, 2001 to 2005; Fellow, at Washington think tank, German Marshall Fund, 1999-2001; chief executive officer-designate, Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington, 1998-99; Olin professor of national security, U.S. Naval Academy, 1997-98; executive vice president, Fannie Mae, 1993-97; deputy chief of staff to President Bush, 1992-93; undersecretary of state, 1989-92; at Treasury Department in various positions including counselor to Secretary James A. Baker III, 1985-88; chief executive officer of board, Fannie Mae, 1983-85 Zoellick says unity, healing are World Bank goals By Barbara Hagenbaugh, USA TODAY WASHINGTON &#151; President Bush's nominee to head the World Bank vowed Wednesday to heal wounds at the embattled anti-poverty group and said his years of international experience made him qualified to do the job. "This institution has been through a traumatic period," Robert Zoellick, wearing globe-shaped cufflinks, told reporters a few hours after Bush's announcement. Bush says Zoellick is devoted to World Bank mission Some advice for the World Bank's new boss "There is a lot of anxiety, frustration and anger that has been built up," Zoellick said. "We need to try to calm the waters, but also then try to get a sense from people together about how we can build some consensus about the direction of the institution." Zoellick's nomination follows the resignation of Paul Wolfowitz. Wolfowitz, one of the architects of the 2003 invasion of Iraq while at the Defense Department, is leaving the bank June 30 after a protracted dispute about his handling of a pay raise and promotion for his girlfriend, a bank employee. Before joining Wall Street firm Goldman Sachs last year, Zoellick was deputy secretary of State, where he oversaw relations with Sudan's Darfur region. He also was U.S. Trade Representative in the Bush administration. Zoellick, 53, is a "committed internationalist," Bush said Wednesday. "He wants to help struggling nations defeat poverty, to grow their economies and offer their people the hope of a better life." The nomination, which needs approval from the bank's board of executive directors, was welcomed by officials around the globe. "His leadership and extensive experience in dealing with international organizations, as well as his clear understanding of the complexities of development issues, make him an excellent choice for this post," Angel Gurr&#237;a, Secretary-General of the Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development, said in a statement. Created in July 1944, the World Bank provides financial and technical aid to developing nations. Although the bank is owned by its member countries, the USA nominates the bank's president under an informal agreement. Officials from some countries have recently questioned the process for selecting the head of the World Bank. In a statement issued Saturday, South African Treasury Minister Trevor Manuel advocated "an open, transparent selection process with candidates not restricted by nationality." Zoellick said Manuel had offered him his support Wednesday, admiring his experience in Africa. White House spokesman Tony Fratto said large countries in the World Bank are not seeking change. "The major shareholders have indicated they're not looking to change the process," he said. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-4&fd=R&url=http://www.turkishpress.com/news.asp%3Fid%3D179044%26s%3D%26i%3D%26t%3DSolana_urges_Iranian_flexibility_ahead_of_nuclear_talks&cid=1116756038&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Solana urges Iranian flexibility ahead of nuclear talks Thursday, May 31, 2007 Fifth Anniversary of 9/11 Solana urges Iranian flexibility ahead of nuclear talks EU foreign policy chief Javier Solana, seen here 29 May 2007, has urged greater flexibility from Iran in the growing row over its nuclear programme, but Tehran remained defiant ahead of key talks in Madrid. EU foreign policy chief Javier Solana on Thursday urged greater flexibility from Iran in the growing row over its nuclear programme, but Tehran remained defiant ahead of key talks in Madrid. Solana "is asking the Iranians to show flexibility during the meeting today," his spokeswoman Cristina Gallach said before Solana met here with Iran's top nuclear negotiator Ali Larijani. Earlier, US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice had also called on Iran "to change tactics" from its persistent defiance of UN Security Council demands to suspend uranium enrichment work, which Washington charges is part of a covert nuclear weapons programme. "The international community is united on what Iran should do and that is to suspend; to demonstrate that it is in fact not seeking a nuclear weapon under cover of civil nuclear power," Rice said in Vienna. Rice repeated Washington's offer to join multiparty talks on trade, security and technological benefits for Iran if the Islamic state halted the enrichment work. Thursday's meeting in Madrid will be the second between Solana and Larijani in just over a month after a fruitless head-to-head in Turkey in late April. It is also their first encounter since the expiration of a 60-day time limit set by the United Nations for Iran to stop enriching uranium, a process which can be used both to make nuclear fuel and, in highly purified form, the fissile core of an atomic bomb "This is a very difficult issue, the questions are very sensitive but a maximum effort must be made so that formal negotiations can start. For that to happen Iran must respect the Security Council resolutions," said Gallach. Oil-rich Iran denies it is seeking nuclear weapons, saying it wants only to produce energy for a growing population whose fossil fuels will eventually run out. The meeting in Madrid has only a slim chance of achieving any breakthrough, with Tehran showing no sign of buckling under increasing international pressure. "There is no possible path for the suspension of the enrichment of uranium," Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Ali Hosseini said Thursday. "Iran will use all legal and judicial means to realise its legitimate rights and will not halt its nuclear activities," Hosseini added. And Larijani, speaking before flying to Madrid on Wednesday, had said that suspending enrichment was "not a logical way" to resolve the nuclear issue. Foreign ministers from the Group of Eight most industrialised nations said Wednesday that they were prepared to back "appropriate measures" if Iran failed to change its stance. The US is leading calls by Western powers for existing sanctions on Iran to be tightened. The UN Security Council first imposed sanctions on Iran in December for rejecting its demands, and then modestly increased them in March. The five permanent members of the UN Security Council -- China, Britain, France, Russia and the United States -- are growing increasingly frustrated and are determined to see the punitive measures strengthened, an analyst said. "Iran would be deceiving itself to believe that they won't," said Mark Fitzpatrick, senior fellow for non-proliferation at the International Institute for Strategic Studies, a London think tank. "They will give Iran a chance to come to the bargaining table with something to offer, but if Iran does not budge, additional sanctions will surely be imposed." Bush unveils new climate change plan 5 Americans Among 7 Dead in Afghan Crash Iraq's bloodiest month for US troops since Fallujah invasion Solana urges Iranian flexibility ahead of nuclear talks Russian suspect says British secret service killed Litvinenko Whaling commission meeting faces another row on final day Putin issues sharp warning to US, vows to counter 'imperialism' World's only human-bred panda in wild dies Protesters brave clampdown after Thai party dissolved Blair urges greater efforts to combat poverty in Africa More violence shakes Gaza despite calls for calm © 2007 Agence France Presse. All rights reserved. The information contained in the AFP News report may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed without the prior written authority of Agence France Presse. &copy; 1997-2007 Anatolia.com Inc
