interfered in the Ontario Provincial Police's handling of the occupation of Ipperwash Provincial Park in September 1995. However, Justice Linden does find that Mr. Harris made racist comments and pushed for a speedy resolution of the conflict. Email to a friend "These comments and the speed at which the premier wished to end the occupation created an atmosphere that unduly narrowed the scope of the government's response to the occupation," Justice Linden said this morning. Following the release of the report, Sam George, the protestor's brother, called upon Mr. Harris to apologize for his role in the incident. "We hold him partly responsible for what happened for acting too fast," Mr. George said. But Peter Downard, a lawyer representing Mr. Harris, said the report exonerated his client and he would not apologize. "He didn't do anything wrong," Mr. Downard said. The Ontario government, however, did apologize to the George family and vowed to begin a new era of consultation with native people over land claims and other issues. "We apologize for the events that led to the loss of life and we deeply regret the death of Dudley George," Aboriginal Affairs Minister David Ramsay told a press conference here. "This report and the implementation of its recommendations will serve as a testament to his memory." Justice Linden's four-volume report blames the federal government's inaction on land claims and shoddy police planning for Mr. George's death, along with the impatience of provincial politicians. The report states that while it was OPP officer Ken Deane who ultimately killed Mr. George during a confrontation between police and native protestors, the officer "should not have been in a position to shoot Mr. George in the first place." Justice Linden rebuffs allegations that Ontario politicians, including Premier Mike Harris, attempted to interfere in OPP operations. "The provincial government had the authority to establish policing policy, but not direct police operations. The Premier and his government did not cross this line," the report states. However, Justice Linden does accuse Mr. Harris of making racist remarks, which "did not contribute to resolving Ipperwash peacefully." The report states Mr. Harris "could have urged patience, rather than speed" and criticizes the provincial government for not appointing a mediator at the outset of the conflict in September 1995. John Mayer acts out a bizarre ... Privacy czar warns web users to be wary Students cruising online networking... Deaths may be linked to diabetes drug Health Canada says the deaths ... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
