http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-0&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DazDnIuQABog8%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116846157&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ , May 31 12:57 , May 31 17:57 , Jun 01 01:57 Bush Proposes Initiative for Cutting Greenhouse Gases (Update2) By Brendan Murray and Tina Seeley May 31 (Bloomberg) -- President George W. Bush, in a counter-offer to European leaders on climate change, proposed convening a new round of talks with the world&#39;s biggest economies to set targets for cutting greenhouse gas emissions. In a speech today in Washington, the president softened his past opposition to setting global goals to cut the pollution that is causing the Earth&#39;s atmosphere to warm without saying what targets should be adopted or how they should be met. ``My proposal is this: By the end of next year America and other nations will set a long-term global goal for reducing greenhouse gases,&#39;&#39; Bush said in an address that set out the U.S. agenda during next week&#39;s meeting of the Group of Eight industrial nations in Heiligendamm, Germany. The talks would ``establish a new framework&#39;&#39; for when the Kyoto Protocol on emissions expires in 2012. Bush is heading into the G-8 summit having rejected a proposal by host German Chancellor Angela Merkel to set a target of limiting global warming to 2 degrees Celsius (3.6 degrees Fahrenheit), effectively cutting emissions to half of 1990 levels by 2050. The administration also opposes a cap-and-trade system, favored by Europeans, that would allow the buying and selling of credits to meet carbon dioxide targets. By proposing to convene talks on climate change, Bush is positioning the U.S. to begin negotiations on the next steps to take. The president&#39;s critics said the administration was still trailing behind allies, state officials and U.S. companies in addressing global warming. ``The White House is just trying to hide the fact that the president is completely isolated among the G-8 leaders by calling vaguely for some agreement next year, right before he leaves office,&#39;&#39; said Philip Clapp, president of the National Environmental Trust. The proposal addresses one of Bush&#39;s objections to the 1997 Kyoto agreement, which required industrialized nations to cut greenhouse gas emissions by 2012, by including India and China. Bush pulled the U.S. out of the accord. ``To develop this goal, the United State will convene a series of meetings of nations that produce the most greenhouse gas emissions, including nations with rapidly growing economies like India and China,&#39;&#39; Bush said. ``In addition to his long- term global goal, each country would establish mid-term national targets and programs that reflect their own mix of energy sources and future energy needs.&#39;&#39; The climate change initiative that Bush proposed, under his 18-month timeline, would likely be among the last international agreements of his two-term administration. He&#39;s scheduled to leave office in January 2009. Bush said the U.S.-led climate change talks would include industry leaders so that technological advances are part of the solution. ``We need to harness the power of technology to help nations meet their growing energy needs while protecting the environment and addressing the challenge of global climate change,&#39;&#39; Bush said. Bush&#39;s plan may help head off criticism from European leaders that the U.S. refuses to go along with a proposal to set specific targets to help mitigate global warming. Concerned that mandatory cuts would hurt the economy, Bush had maintained support for new technologies and investment in alternative fuels such as ethanol to help curb harmful emissions. In his speech Bush outlined his broader agenda for the G-8 meeting and emphasized his initiatives on AIDS prevention and treatment in poor nations, fighting malaria and the need to finish work on a global trade accord that will open markets for developing nations as well as the world&#39;s richest. ``Trade will improve lives a lot faster than government aid can,&#39;&#39; Bush said. ``The United States will take the lead in making sure those markets are open.&#39;&#39; At the G-8 meeting, Bush said he would argue that lowering trade barriers also would help address energy and environmental challenges. ``If you are truly committed to helping the environment, nations need to get rid of their tariffs, need to get rid of those barriers that prevent new technologies from coming into their countries,&#39;&#39; he said. Bush said U.S. aid to developing nations has more than doubled during his presidency, from more than $10 billion in 2001 to $23 billion in 2006. He said it was the largest increase since the Marshall Plan that rebuilt Europe after World War II. Earlier this week, Bush imposed U.S. economic sanctions against Sudan in a bid to curb the violence in Darfur and called on the United Nations to step up financial pressure on Sudanese President Umar al-Bashir. Yesterday, Bush asked Congress to approve $30 billion during the next five years to mount a more aggressive campaign against the spread of AIDS worldwide, particularly in sub- Saharan Africa. The request would double the current U.S. program of $15 billion, which expires in 2008, and extend it to 2013, five years after Bush leaves office. The G-8 countries are the U.S., Japan, Germany, the U.K., France, Italy, Canada and Russia. The U.S. economy accounts for about 45 percent of the group&#39;s $29.3 trillion in annual economic output. To contact the reporter on this story: Brendan Murray in Washington at ; Tina Seeley in Washington at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 12:43 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Stocks in U.S. Gain on Takeover Speculation; A.G. Edwards, Ceridian Climb
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-3&fd=R&url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/society/law_order/lugovoi%2Bmi6%2Bpoisoned%2Blitvinenko/539222&cid=1116515252&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Channel 4 - News - Lugovoi: MI6 poisoned Litvinenko Skip to main content Channel 4 News > About Channel 4 News Lugovoi: MI6 poisoned Litvinenko Last Modified: 31 May 2007 Former Russian spy Andrei Lugovoi claims MI6 was behind the poisoning in London of Alexander Litvinenko. In a press conference in Moscow this morning, Mr Lugovoi also claimed the security services tried to recruit him to inform on Russian president Vladimir Putin. The Foreign Office has dismissed the allegations, and one of the exiles accused by Mr Lugovoi, Boris Berezovsky, told Channel 4 News that today&#039;s events proved the Kremlin was behind his friend&#039;s murder. Andrei Lugovoi, suspected of causing Litvinenko&#039;s death last November, held forth for an hour and a half - live on Russian state television. He declared he wanted to reveal the hidden truth behind the murder. He said Alexander Litvinenko was a British agent who tried to recruit him into MI6. "Litvinenko gave me a book. He said that we&#039;re like spies in the films now and have to use a code," he said. Lugovoi went on to claim that Litvinenko had fallen out with his MI6 handlers. He had ceased to be an asset and was killed. &#039;Litvinenko gave me a book. He said that we&#039;re like spies in the films now and have to use a code.&#039; But Lugovoi has provided no evidence for this claim. The Foreign Office responded: "This is a criminal matter, not an issue about intelligence." The Foreign Office is still awaiting a formal response to its request for Lugovoi&#039;s extradition so that he may face trial in the UK. Send this article to a friend Related Articles in Law & order New curbs on knives in school Fears over &#039;stop and quiz&#039; plans Moscow gay rights demo attacked McCann parents speak of guilt Call for easing conte