http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-5&fd=R&url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21829502-2703,00.html&cid=1116817584&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ US bid to rescue British hostages | The World | The Australian The Australian &mdash; The World US bid to rescue British hostages US forces raided Shia militia strongholds in eastern Baghdad yesterday after mounting evidence emerged that an Iranian-backed group was behind the abduction of five Britons. According to Iraqi and British officials working on the case, the kidnapping of a British IT expert and four private security guards bore all the hallmarks of the Mahdi Army, the militant group headed by Moqtada al-Sadr. The Shia religious leader returned to Iraq last week and there have been fears he would order a new wave of attacks against US and British targets. The US military announced yesterday that two more American soldiers had been killed in Iraq, confirming that May had become the deadliest month for American forces since 2004. The soldiers were killed late on Wednesday when a roadside bomb hit their foot patrol and brought US casualties for the month to 116 - the most since November 2004, when marines fought a fierce battle to retake the city of Fallujah. April was bloody for the US-led coalition, with 104 deaths. Taken together, the two past months have been the deadliest since the war began. Also yesterday, a suicide bomber hit a police recruiting centre in Fallujah, killing up to 25 people and wounding 50, police said. In another blow, a Sunni police chief praised by US forces for clearing his city of insurgents was arrested following an investigation into alleged murder, corruption and crimes against the Iraqi people. Colonel Hamid Ibrahim al-Jazaa, his brother and 14 bodyguards were taken into custody Tuesday in the city of Hit, 140km west of Baghdad, according to a statement by the public affairs office of Multinational Corps-Iraq. The statement gave no details of the allegations. As the hunt for the five Britons continued, it has been revealed British SAS troopers hunting for al-Qa'ida in Iraq are being diverted to lead the search for the men. The SAS and the Special Boat Service, the Royal Marine equivalent of the army's elite regiment, have squadrons in Baghdad, although their main task has been to work alongside American special forces. The SAS and SBS have been engaged in covert missions against al-Qa'ida for four years, giving them experience of operating in the most hostile and complex environment. Military sources said the search would need to be done with the greatest sensitivity. The "kinetic option" used against al-Qa'ida targets - tracking and eliminating - was not going to be the best solution. US commanders have backed away from taking on Mahdi Army gunmen because of the Iraqi Government's desire to keep al-Sadr, the Islamic cleric who controls the militia force, in the political process. If his men have taken the Britons, the focus will be on negotiating the safe release of the hostages, not going in with guns blazing. The Britons - a consultant and his four armed bodyguards - were snatched late on Tuesday by a large group of gunmen in Iraqi police uniforms. In an interview with BBC radio, Iraqi Foreign Minister Hoshyar Zebari noted the raid had taken place near Sadr City, an al-Sadr stronghold. He said it was too soon to blame a specific group, but said the nature of the kidnapping clearly pointed to the involvement of one of the Shia militant groups. Meanwhile, an Iraqi court yesterday sentenced a former minister in absentia to seven years in prison for spiriting more than $US1 billion ($1.25 billion) out of the country during his brief tenure. Hazem al-Shaalan was accused along with scores of other officials of embezzling money earmarked for weapons. He denied the charges, which were first raised in 2005. Appeal to junta on Thai parties Star's new role: the candidate US bid to rescue British hostages Bans could send threatene