http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm%3Falias%3Dnine-atlantic-hurricanes%26chanId%3Dsa003%26modsrc%3Dreuters&cid=1116729647&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07: Scientific American Does the length of a baseball player's arm affect the distance of his throw? If so, how? 50, 100 & 150 Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07 Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07 File photo shows Key West resident Gregorio Nodal walks in the flooded North Roosevelt coast boulevard after Hurricane Wilma hits Florida's southern west coast October 24, 2005. A hurricane research team has renewed its forecast for an "above average" 2007 Atlantic storm season. REUTERS/Carlos Barria MIAMI (Reuters) - The Colorado State University hurricane research team renewed its forecast for an "above average" 2007 Atlantic storm season on Thursday and predicted 17 tropical storms, with nine growing to hurricane strength. Of those, five would grow into major hurricanes of Category 3 or higher with winds over 110 mph (177 kph), the team founded by forecast pioneer William Gray said in its revised forecast. The updated forecast issued on Thursday was unchanged from the team's April 3 forecast for the six-month storm season that starts on Friday. ADVERTISEMENT (article continues below) The researchers said there was a 74 percent chance that at least one major hurricane would hit the U.S. coastline in 2007, with a 50 percent chance that would happen on the U.S. Atlantic Coast and a 49 percent chance on the Gulf of Mexico coast. An average season brings 11 tropical storms, with six reaching hurricane wind speed of 74 mph (119 kph) and two growing into major hurricanes. Other private and government weather researchers have also predicted a more active season than average. But so far none have forecast anything like a repeat of record-breaking 2005, when 28 tropical storms spawned 15 hurricanes, including Katrina which flooded New Orleans and parts of the Gulf coast. Spain scraps highway plan to save lynx EU split on funding for Galileo satellite project Nokia unveils three new phones YouTube signs broad licensing pact with EMI G8 greenhouse gas emissions rise 15 Answers to Creationist Nonsense The New Math: Kids Can Add and Subtract without Arithmetic A.D. 100 Billion: Big Bang Goes Bye-Bye A Genetic Basis for Language Tones? The New Math: Kids Can Add and Subtract without Arithmetic A Genetic Basis for Language Tones? Researchers Tap Cellular Communication Between Species A.D. 100 Billion: Big Bang Goes Bye-Bye Submit your videos > Official faces death penalty Cat's bibs stop them killing wildlife TB scare for airplane passengers I found this leopard in my bedroom Breaking Science News from Reuters Updated today at 12:26 PM Spain scraps highway plan to save lynx EU split on funding for Galileo satellite project Nokia unveils three new phones YouTube signs broad licensing pact with EMI G8 greenhouse gas emissions rise Chronic pain may impede short-term memory Bird flu waning but global pandemic risk still high There's something in the air in Rome: cocaine Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07 Scientists shed new light on male infertility Surgery can fix many back problems: studies New games for weathering the summer doldrums Warner to put ad-supported video archive online WHO official says flu pandemic "almost certain" China scientists shed new light on male infertility NEWS FROM OUR PARTNERS Profile: Edmund D Pellegrino The policy outlook from the Hill HDAC inhibitors overcome first hurdle Upward trend in financing continues, but fewer feel flush See your ad here &copy; 1996-2007 Scientific American, Inc. All rights reserved. Reproduction in whole or in part without permission is prohibited.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.metimes.com/storyview.php%3FStoryID%3D20070531-060254-2871r&cid=1116756038&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Iran, EU talks seek way out of nuclear impasse - Region - Middle East Times Thursday, May 31 2007 Iran, EU talks seek way out of nuclear impasse Iran's top negotiator Ali Larijani and EU foreign policy chief Javier Solana braced for another round of talks Thursday in their latest bid to break an increasingly tense standoff over Tehran's atomic program. The meeting, which is expected to get underway in Madrid at 5.00 pm (1500 GMT), will be their second in just over a month after a fruitless head-to-head in Turkey in late April. The dispute over Iran's refusal to heed UN demands to suspend uranium enrichment work has intensified in recent days, with stepped up rhetoric on both sides of the debate. Foreign ministers from the Group of Eight most industrialized nations said Wednesday in a statement that they were prepared to back "appropriate measures" if Iran persisted in defying the United Nations. "If Iran continues to ignore demands of the Security Council, we will support further appropriate measures as agreed in Resolution 1747," they said in a statement following at a meeting in Potsdam, Germany. Security Council resolution 1747 set a 60-day deadline for Tehran to freeze all enrichment work, which expired last week. Western powers accuse oil-rich Iran of seeking nuclear weapons, a charge vehemently denied by Tehran, which says that it just wants to produce energy. They are now pressing for Iran to face further penalties for its continued defiance over uranium enrichment, the process that can be used both to make nuclear fuel and, in highly purified form, the fissile core of an atomic bomb. Iran insists that it has a right to enrichment for peaceful ends as a signatory to the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. The meeting in Madrid has only a slim chance of achieving any breakthrough, with Tehran showing no sign of buckling under growing international pressure. "There is no possible path for the suspension of the enrichment of uranium," Iranian foreign ministry spokesman Mohammad Ali Hosseini said Thursday. "Iran will use all legal and judicial means to realize its legitimate rights and will not halt its nuclear activities," Hosseini added. And Larijani, speaking before flying to Madrid Wednesday, had said that suspending enrichment was "not a logical way" to resolve the nuclear issue. A diplomat in Vienna, headquarters of the International Atomic Energy Agency, said that the talks "won't reach any decision. It's just an exchange of ideas." The five permanent members of the UN Security Council - China, Britain, France, Russia, and the United States - are growing increasingly frustrated with Iran and are determined to impose more sanctions if it shows no willingness to suspend its program at the talks, an analyst said. "Iran would be deceiving itself to believe that they won't," said Mark Fitzpatrick, senior fellow for non-proliferation at the International Institute for Strategic Studies, a London think tank. "They will give Iran a chance to come to the bargaining table with something to offer, but if Iran does not budge, additional sanctions will surely be imposed." Last week US President George W. Bush said that he would work with European allies, Russia, and China to toughen existing penalties. The United Nations Security Council first imposed sanctions on Iran in December for rejecting its demands, and then modestly increased them in March. The talks held last month between the EU foreign policy chief and Larijani were "positive in form but not fruitful in substance," Solana's spokeswoman Cristina Gallach said in Brussels Wednesday. Larijani has said "positive points were discussed in Ankara," describing them as "buds which need to grow on an international level to resolve the issue." Explosion rocks Yemeni capital Iran sets parliament vote for March 2008 'Enemy fire' may have brought down NATO helicopter Iran, EU talks seek way out of nuclear impasse 50 Baghdad gas stations to be 24-hour Was Iraq invaded to boost oil prices? Value of Exxon reserves rose by $666bn Qatar orders 80 Airbus A350s worth $16bn Malaysian woman criticizes court in religious row Israel prevents Muslim burials in Jerusalem cemetery 1967 war - One page in Egypt's history, literally British lecturers vote to back Israel boycott Jordan names first woman to head court Mideast women defy regional divides to promote peace Senegal, Gambia villages give up female circumcision Egypt women blame selves for harassment says report Google takes online software applications offline Apple sells music without piracy protection YouTube videos to play on Apple TV US Internet 'Spam King' arrested Commentary: Self-inflicted deadly wounds Review of Arab Editorials Commentary: Something radically different Commentary: No substitute for substance Paris, Nicole, now Lindsay Fully Loaded Ex KKK member on trial for 1964 Mississippi murders Giant cranes to move Acropolis marbles to new museum 'Priceless' Callas robe stolen from Greek exhibition Polo Beach Wailea; Lake Tahoe rentals Laantec Hardware PC Shop Copyright &copy; 2007 News World Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-2&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-05-30-hostages-nigeria_N.htm&cid=1116841644&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ 4 American hostages released in Nigeria - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Sign up to receive our free Daily Briefing e-newsletter and get the top news of the day in your inbox. Breaking news E-mail alerts Get breaking news in your inbox as it happens 4 American hostages released in Nigeria WARRI, Nigeria (AP) &#151; Four American hostages seized weeks ago in Nigeria's restive southern oil heartland were publicly handed over to authorities on Wednesday. As journalists looked on, a judge who mediated in the dispute escorted the four men taken May 9 to the governor's offices in southern Rivers State where he handed the liberated hostages over to authorities. U.S. embassy officials weren't immediately available for comment. Some 200 foreign workers have been kidnapped since armed militants stepped up their attacks against oil companies and the government in late 2005. Most have been quickly released for ransom. Growing lawlessness, including armed attacks, in the oil-rich Niger Delta have cut about a quarter of exports from Africa's leading oil producer. The impoverished region has nearly all of Nigeria's oil, and most inhabitants want an increased share of revenue. In his inaugural speech Tuesday, President Umaru Yar'Adua appeal for an immediate end to violence in the region of swamps, creeks and mangrove forests. The largest militant group said it would consider the overture. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe