http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-0&fd=R&url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21829705-2703,00.html&cid=1116362226&ei=j_1eRrflEJCWrgOwmaXSDQ Appeal to junta on Thai parties | The World | The Australian The Australian &mdash; The World Appeal to junta on Thai parties Peter Alford, Tokyo correspondent DEMOCRAT Party leader Abhisit Vejjajiva, suddenly the man most likely to become Thailand's next prime minister, has asked the country's military leadership to set "a clear road map for democracy". Mr Abhisit yesterday called on the Council for National Security junta to lift its embargo on public political activities and to allow members of the banned Thai Rak Thai party to form new groups. "We encourage the regime to open up a political space, to remove restrictions on the formation of new parties, to allow supporters of Thai Rak Thai to regroup and use the parliamentary system," said Mr Abhisit. "The country needs at this moment stability by setting a clear road map for democracy," he told the CNBC satellite news service. "Even the military must now feel the pressure. The experience of the last six to seven months has proved there is no other alternative to democracy to restore stability and solve (our) economic problems." CNS chief General Sonthi Boonyaratglin, who overthrew Thaksin Shinawatra's Thai Rak Thai government on September 19, said he would consult military-appointed prime minister General Surayud Chulanont about lifting the political activities ban within a fortnight. The generals have offered a tentative timetable for a popular vote on a new draft constitution in September and national elections, though under sharply different conditions from the 1997 constitution, by mid-December. The junta had been awaiting Wednesday night's Constitutional Tribunal verdicts before taking further steps towards the promised restoration of a democratic government. The tribunal's decisions to sustain allegations of electoral abuses against Thai Rak Thai during the abortive April 2006 election campaign but to exonerate the Democrats has left 50-year-old Mr Abhisit as Thailand's only likely next prime minister. As a result of Wednesday's rulings, described by one Bangkok pundit as "a political massacre", Mr Thaksin and 110 other Thai Rak Thai executives - the politicians who ran Thailand from early 2001 until the coup - have been banned from politics for the next five years. Chaturon Chaisaeng, Thai Rak Thai's acting leader while Mr Thaksin remains indefinitely based in London, said in a statement yesterday the party was looking at ways of challenging the banning orders. Mr Chaturon was apparently relying on reports that the tribunal's decision to convict Thai Rak Thai and exonerate the Democrats was not unanimous. However, the interim national constitution allows no appeal against a tribunal decision. At best, Thai Rak Thai supporters can hope to be allowed to register a new party in the same name as the dissolved group. Their only recourse appears to be a direct appeal to the interim government, which is filled with Mr Thaksin's opponents. However, the military and the interim government remain wary of provoking widespread civil disobedience among supporters of Mr Thaksin, who remains widely popular, especially among Thailand's poor rural dwellers. In its judgment on Wednesday night, the Constitution Tribunal acknowledged Thai Rak Thai's membership still numbered 14 million, in a total population of 61.5 million. The military and police maintained tight security in the capital yesterday, although by the evening none of the feared mass demonstrations by Thai Rak Thai supporters had eventuated. Mr Thaksin in London yesterday released a message urging his supporters to accept the tribunal ruling and calling on the junta to convene elections as soon as possible. "Although I announced that I would wash my hands out of politics, I would like to urge (party) members to work and implement political activities for the sake of the country and the people," he said in a letter read out in Bangkok by his lawyer, Noppadon Pattama. The 57-year-old former telecommunications tycoon, whose party in 2005 was the first in Thai electoral history to win an absolute majority of votes and seats, apologised to his supporters that their efforts had come to such an end. Appeal to junta on Thai parties Star's new role: the candidate US bid to rescue British hostages Bans could send threatened species under Indo-US nuke deal faces critical mass Taliban claims NATO chopper kill $1.22bn Harry Potter theme park, Hogwarts and all Blair defends his record on Africa Patented yoga has Indians in a twist Ukraine deadlock after poll vote fails Guantanamo Bay prisoner in 'apparent suicide' Spy suspect accuses Britain Where there's water, there's growth. Get your FREE water investment kit today 1st mth best package + install 4 NOTHING*. HSBC's Low Rate Credit Card - Switch to HSBC's Low Rate Credit Card today and save. Apply now. Celebrate 60 yrs of Saab Free sat nav, 3 yrs servicing & auto trans. $4,300 value. Ends June 27 It won't just be another day at the office. See the full demo. Buy, sell or hold? Get 60 free recommendations in a 6-week trial of sharemarket advice. Try Weight Watchers Online and save
