http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-6&fd=R&url=http://www.cnsnews.com/news/viewstory.asp%3FPage%3D/ForeignBureaus/archive/200706/FOR20070604b.html&cid=1116878342&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Amnesty Report Ignores Self-Defense, Israel Says -- 06/04/2007 News on the Web Jefferson Indicted on 16 Counts of Bribery, Corruption Larry Flynt Trolling for Political Sex Scandals Federal Funding of Abstinence Education May Expire Soon Backers of Immigration Bill More Optimistic About Passage Republican McConnell Seen As Key to Immigration Bill Commentary: The Demise of the Republican Party 'Anti-Catholic' Laws Hamper School Choice, Voucher Backers Say Sidebar: Zelman v. Simmons-Harris Vox Populi: Gun Control-Touting Priest Is Not a Real Catholic FCC Broadband Auction Rules Called 'Fundamentally Flawed' Wal-Mart 'Just Not American Anymore,' Group's Ad Charges China Rejects Mandatory Measures to Cap Emissions Bush Heading to G8 Summit Russian President Says He May Aim Nukes At Europe Amnesty Report Ignores Self-Defense, Israel Says 'People of All Faiths' Urged to Combat Ahmadinejad's Message of Hate Islamic Extremists Threaten Female Newscasters With Beheading Amnesty Report Ignores Self-Defense, Israel Says -- 06/04/2007 Amnesty Report Ignores Self-Defense, Israel Says CNSNews.com Jerusalem Bureau Chief - Israel charged on Monday that an Amnesty International report blasting its presence in the West Bank is "one-sided, immoral" and doesn't take into consideration Israel's right to self-defense. The report, "Enduring Occupation: Palestinians Under Siege on the West Bank," released on Monday, launched a scathing attack on Israel on the occasion of the 40th anniversary of the 1967 Six-Day War, which began four decades ago on Tuesday. As a result of that war, Israel gained control over the entire West Bank, Gaza Strip -- and their Palestinian populations -- the Sinai Desert and Golan Heights, which had previously been under the occupation of Jordan, Egypt and Syria respectively. Israel offered to return all of the Golan Heights and Sinai Desert in exchange for full peace treaties with Syria and Egypt and offered the creation of a Palestinian entity. But in September of that year, Arab states gathered for a summit in Khartoum in which they affirmed what has become known as the "three no's:" no peace with Israel, no recognition of Israel and no negotiations with it. In 1979, Egypt became the first Arab nation to sign a full peace treaty with Israel, and in 1994, Jordan became the second, but the Israeli-Palestinian conflict remained. The 45-page AI report calls on Israel to remove roadblocks and restrictions on Palestinian travel, remove the security barrier between Israel and the West Bank, and remove Israeli settlements -- where more than 225,000 Israelis currently live on land that they believe was given to them by God as an eternal inheritance known biblically as Judea and Samaria. The report documents what AI calls the "relentless expansion of unlawful settlements on occupied land that deprives the Palestinian population of crucial resources and documents a plethora of measures that confine Palestinians to fragmented enclaves and hinder their access to work, health and education facilities." One of the measures, it says, is the 700-kilometer (420-mile) barrier and more than 500 checkpoints and roadblocks. Israel's security barrier, which is sometimes a fence and sometimes a wall, juts at points into the West Bank where Palestinians want to establish a state. Israel credits the barrier with a dramatic reduction in suicide bomb attacks in its major population centers. "Palestinians living in the West Bank are blocked at every turn," charged Malcolm Smart, director for AI's Middle East and North Africa Program. "This is not simply an inconvenience -- it can be a matter of life or death" as they sometimes face long delays or detours en route to the hospital, he said. Israel rejected the findings of the report, saying it was /ldblquote one-sided, immoral and riddled with mistakes and numerous factual and legal inaccuracies, including scant mention of Palestinian terrorism, which holds non-combatants hostage, using them as human shields and camouflage."" Israel considers safeguarding human rights to be of "utmost importance," said Justice Ministry spokesman Moshe Cohen. The report does not acceptably deal with Israel's right of self-defense or its legitimate security needs, he said. "The lack of emphasis on the centrality of Palestinian terrorism and the [army's] responsibility to protect Israeli citizens as a direct result ... creates a deliberate distortion," Cohen said in a statement. Cohen also charged that the report totally disregarded the actions of Palestinian terrorist organizations "when they directly and indiscriminately target civilian populations while using the local population as human shields." Foreign Ministry spokesman Mark Regev said Israel has a problem with the "perspective" of the report and noted it is the only country in the region that values human rights. "Israel is the only country in the region where human rights are central to our political experience; the only country in the region with an independent professional and powerful judiciary; [and] the only country in the region where the security services, defense establishment are open to civilian scrutiny and judicial review," said Regev. Yisrael Medad, a resident of the Jewish West Bank settlement of Shilo and a volunteer spokesman for the Jewish communities there, said that the claim in the report that the barrier can be a "matter of life or death" for Palestinians is a "classic example of perverting morality." "They seem to prefer that Jews and Arabs die rather than seeing Israel even in a stopgap manner halting the cycle of death and terror," Medad said in a telephone interview. Medad said that the report had it backwards when it claimed that Israel was imposing "collective punishment" on the Palestinians by erecting roadblocks and placing travel restrictions on them. "If there is any collective punishment, it is that of the Arabs who single out every single Jew as a legitimate target for their illegitimate terror," said Medad. No international body has ever condemned the terrorism in the same manner that it has condemned Israel's right to self-defense, he said. Subscribe to the free CNSNews.com daily E-Brief. Send a Letter to the Editor about this article. All original CNSNews.com material, copyright 1998-2007 Cybercast News Service.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-0&fd=R&url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/world/us-judge-throws-out-case-against-canadian/2007/06/05/1180809459735.html&cid=1116793406&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg US judge throws out case against Canadian - World - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. US judge throws out case against Canadian June 5, 2007 - 6:30AM In a stunning reversal for the US administration's attempts to try Guantanamo detainees in military court, a military judge today dismissed terrorism-related charges against a prisoner charged with killing an American soldier in Afghanistan. The chief of military defence attorneys at Guantanamo Bay, marine Colonel Dwight Sullivan, said the ruling could spell the end of the war-crimes trial system set up last year by Congress and President George Bush after the Supreme Court threw out the previous system. Canadian detainee Omar Khadr, who was 15 when he was captured after a deadly firefight in Afghanistan and who is now 20, will remain at the remote US military base along with about 380 other men suspected of links to al-Qaeda and the Taliban. The judge, army Colonel Peter Brownback, said he had no choice but to throw out the Khadr case because he had been classified as an "enemy combatant" by a military panel years earlier - and not as an "alien unlawful enemy combatant". The Military Commissions Act, signed by Mr Bush last year, specifically says that only those classified as "unlawful" enemy combatants can face war trials here, Colonel Brownback noted during the arraignment in a hilltop courtroom. Colonel Sullivan told journalists the dismissal has "huge" impact because none of the detainees held at this isolated military base in south-east Cuba has been found to be an "unlawful" enemy combatant. "It is not just a technicality; it's the latest demonstration that this newest system just does not work," Colonel Sullivan told journalists. "It is a system of justice that does not comport with American values." Colonel Sullivan said in order to reclassify the detainees as "unlawful" combatants, the whole review system would have to be overhauled, a time-consuming act. Carl Tobias, a law professor at the University of Richmond, said because Brownbeck dismissed the case without prejudice, the US may be able to retry Khadr. He also said it is unclear whether the Combatant Status Review Tribunals will have to reclassify all detainees. A prosecuting attorney said he would appeal the dismissal. The new war-crimes trial system give prosecutors 72 hours to appeal, but the court designated to hear the appeal - known as the court of military commissions review - doesn't even exist, Colonel Sullivan noted. Colonel Sullivan said the judge hearing the case of the only other Guantanamo detainee currently charged with crimes is not bound by Colonel Brownback's ruling, but that he expected the same decision. That other detainee is Salim Ahmed Hamdan, who is accused of chauffeuring Osama bin Laden and being the al-Qaeda chief's bodyguard. His arraignment was scheduled for this afternoon. Australian David Hicks, the third detainee to be charged under the new system, pleaded guilty in March to providing material support for terrorism and has been sent home to Australia to serve a nine-month sentence. Under his plea agreement, Hicks agreed that he was "an alien unlawful enemy combatant, as defined by the Military Commissions Act". Colonel Brownback's ruling came just minutes into Khadr's arraignment on charges he committed murder in violation of the law of war, attempted murder in violation of the law of war, conspiracy, providing material support for terrorism and spying. Khadr allegedly killed a US Army soldier with a grenade in the firefight, in which he was wounded. He appeared in the courtroom with a beard and wearing an olive-green prison uniform. "The charges are dismissed without prejudice," Colonel Brownback pronounced as he adjourned the proceeding. A prosecutor, army captain Keith Petty, said he had been prepared to show Khadr was an unlawful combatant because he fought for al-Qaeda, and videotapes showed Khadr making and planting explosives targeting American soldiers. Khadr seemed oblivious to the impact of the ruling. He calmly watched the judge throw out the case - looking not at Colonel Brownback but at a computer screen at the defence table that showed a live TV broadcast of the proceedings. Khadr could see himself on the screen. The US military has hoped to accelerate its prosecutions of Guantanamo detainees, with the Pentagon saying it expects to eventually charge about 80 of the 380 prisoners held at this isolated base, but questions lingered about the legitimacy of the process. The US Supreme Court, ruling in favour of a lawsuit brought by Hamdan, last June threw out a previous military tribunal system that was set up in the wake of the September 11, 2001, attacks, calling it unconstitutional. Congress responded by creating new guidelines for war-crimes trials and Bush signed them into law. Hamdan's lawyer, navy Lieutenant Commander Charles Swift, told The Associated Press he will challenge the new system as unconstitutional. For example, the Military Commissions Act retroactively made certain acts, such as conspiracy, a crime, Swift said. "This case raises significant questions" about the separation of powers, Swift said. "Congress cannot violate the Constitution to fix things ... but they are backdating anything and making it a crime." Hamdan is charged with conspiracy - centred on his alleged membership in al-Qaeda and purported role in plotting to attack civilians and civilian targets - and with providing material support for terrorism. As part of the second charge, Hamdan is accused of transporting at least one SA-7 surface-to-air missile to shoot down US and coalition military aircraft in Afghanistan in November 2001. Hamdan's alleged war crimes were committed between February 1996 and November 2001, according to the charge sheet. Swift, in the interview, said some acts predate the start of the Bush administration's war against terrorism, saying it generally is considered to be September 11, 2001. But army Lt-Col William Britt, the chief prosecutor in the Hamdan case, told the AP there is no established date when hostilities commenced and that the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Centre could be construed as the war's opening shot. In an interview yesterday at Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington - as prosecutors, defence lawyers, human rights monitors and journalists waited to board a plane to Guantanamo for the arraignments - Britt said he expects a courtroom battle over the matters Swift raised. "These are novel issues," Britt said. "We're talking about new legislation, with the Military Commissions Act of 2006. We, the government, are looking forward to litigating (them)." The son of an alleged al-Qaeda financier, Khadr is accused of killing US Army Sergeant Christopher Speer with a grenade during a firefight in Afghanistan on July 27, 2002. Khadr's lawyers said he was a child soldier and should be rehabilitated, not imprisoned. "The US will be the first country in modern history to try an individual who was a child at the time of the alleged war crimes," the lawyers said in a joint statement in April. When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! US judge throws out case against Canadian Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Age Company Ltd. Browse for a Date Putin threatens to point nuclear missiles at Europe Clinton in front as Democrats clash over Iraq Lebanese refugee camp battle spreads Guitarists cut a different record A man of letters leaves a rich laundry list Threat to despot's trial Abba's Waterloo on Israel boycott Artist bares Blairs and casts them from No. 10 Spanish police warn of possible ETA attack Australians to be deported from UAE Out of the bed Porn today is part of everyday life. Brides with face paint, anyone? A peek inside the new glossy home magazines. Paris reports to jail Paris Hilton begins serving her jail sentence after attending the MTV movie awards. Lions v buffalo v crocs ALL MEN ARE LIONS The most incredible peices of wildlife footage you'll ever see. "Barbecue stopper" and "hoodies" among new items in an updated version of the dictionary. Shark divorce nears end Greg Norman's ugly divorce battle may soon be resolved. Time to help Jack Marx score another Walkley. How much do Wii know? Despite success, there is disquiet on the Wii software front. TODAY'S TOP 10 ARTICLES Putin threatens to point nuclear missiles at Europe Clinton in front as Democrats clash over Iraq Howard hastens on broadband When porn becomes commonplace Headscarf was erased from school photo: claim Australia in 20 years China takes hard line on climate Smile, you're on Google's candid camera Sharapova a winner, but not with fans Paris reports to jail More most viewed articles News Store Alert will keep you informed. Get free news emails from theage.com.au.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-3&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/04/africa/ME-GEN-Iraq.php&cid=1116960165&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Insurgents issue video claiming 2 missing U.S. soldiers were killed; U.S. military says search will continue - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Insurgents issue video claiming 2 missing U.S. soldiers were killed; U.S. military says search will continue Published: June 3, 2007 Insurgents linked to al-Qaida issued a video Monday claiming they killed all three U.S. soldiers captured in an ambush last month. "They were alive and then dead," a voice said during a sequence of images that included the military IDs of two Americans who are the subject of a massive manhunt south of Baghdad. The nearly 11-minute video offered no proof for its claims that the soldiers had been killed and buried, and the U.S. military insisted the search for the two missing soldiers would continue. "We condemn the tactics used by these terrorists, and are using all means available to pursue those responsible," said Brig. Gen. Kevin Bergner, the chief military spokesman in Baghdad. "We continue to search and hope that our two missing soldiers will be found alive and in good health." The nearly video, which included grainy black-and-white footage of what the Islamic State of Iraq said was taken during the May 12 predawn ambush on a road south of Baghdad, was the latest distraction for the U.S. military as it seeks to quell the sectarian violence raging in Iraq and pave the way for American forces to go home. Military officials also acknowledged Monday that U.S.-led forces have control of fewer than one-third of Baghdad&#039;s neighborhoods despite thousands of extra troops nearly four months into a security crackdown &#8212; an assessment that came as the U.S. death toll approached 3,500, with at least 15 American troops reported killed in the first three days of June. Today in Africa &#038; Middle East Dreams of college destroyed in Iraq Militant video shows missing soldiers&#x27; IDs Lebanon Army keeps up siege of Palestinian camps Lt. Col. Scott Bleichwehl, a military spokesman for Baghdad operations, confirmed that a status report completed in May found that American and Iraqi forces were able to "protect the population" and "maintain physical influence over" only 146 of the 457 Baghdad neighborhoods, while troops have either not begun operations aimed at rooting out insurgents or still face "resistance" in the others. It appeared to be the first comprehensive analysis of the progress of the operation that began Feb. 14. Gen. David Petraeus, the top U.S. commander in Iraq, is due to report in September on whether the current troop increase is working amid a fierce debate in Washington over whether President Bush should begin withdrawing American forces. But Bleichwehl stressed that the assessment, which was first reported by the New York Times, did not mean a lack of progress and said the setbacks were largely due to a higher-than-expected need to return to some areas that had previously been cleared, as well as problems with the availability and reliability of Iraqi police. "It&#039;s way too early to try and project what Baghdad will look like in September," he said in a telephone interview. U.S. officials also pointed out that they have warned from the beginning that it would not be easy to pacify Baghdad and did not expect to see serious progress until the fall amid unrelenting bombings by suspected Sunni insurgents and execution-style killings usually blamed on Shiite militias. "We have stated all along that this was going to be harder before it gets easier," military spokesman Lt. Col. Christopher Garver said. "It&#039;s going to be a tough fight over the summer and the plan is just in its beginning stages." The Bush administration, which has ordered some 30,000 extra American troops to Baghdad and surrounding areas as part of the security crackdown, has warned that the buildup will result in more U.S. casualties as more American soldiers come into contact with enemy forces and concentrate on the streets of Baghdad and remote outposts. The three U.S. soldiers were abducted after a 4:44 a.m. ambush as they were participating in an operation to watch for insurgents placing roadside bombs on a dangerous road near Mahmoudiya, about 30 kilometers (20 miles) south of Baghdad. The militants breached the concertina wire surrounding the stationary outpost composed of two Humvees, killing four other American troops and an Iraqi. The attack triggered a massive search in the area south of Baghdad known as the "triangle of death" for the rampant insurgent activity there. The Islamic State of Iraq issued Web statements shortly after the attack claiming responsibility and warning the Americans to call off the hunt "if you want their safety." But the military insisted the search would continue. "We are further analyzing the video, however it doesn&#039;t appear to contain any definitive evidence indicating the status of our missing soldiers," Bergner said. Jon Alterman, the Middle East program director for the Center for Strategic and International Studies, agreed the video was not definitive and said the insurgents could have many reasons for releasing it regardless of the soldiers&#039; status. Africa &#038; Middle East Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing 