http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-1&fd=R&url=http://www.thedesertsun.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070604/UPDATE/70604022&cid=1116951270&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg thedesertsun.com | Plane crashes into homes in Upland Search The Coachella Valley: Plane crashes into homes in Upland Paris Hilton completes first night in jail Two dead in crash; eastbound Hwy. 111 reopened When's graduation? Here's a list of local high schools' plans Coachella police officer's foot smashed by erratic driver Have something to say about it? Join the conversation in Talk of the Day A twin-engine plane with three people on board lost power and slammed into homes in Upland while trying to land, authorities said. The pilot and two passengers suffered minor injuries. No one on the ground was hurt, said Ian Gregor, spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration. The plane came to rest atop a garage without catching a fire. Its wing rested on the roof of another home. The Piper Seneca was approaching Cable Airport when it lost power and crashed into three homes on Blossom Circle. The plane departed from Van Nuys Airport in the San Fernando Valley. Upland is about 72 miles from Palm Springs. “They were on approach when the pilot reported engine problems,” Gregor said. Weather didn’t appear to be a factor. It was sunny with no clouds or fog. Upland is about 45 miles east of Los Angeles, near the junction of Interstates 10 and 15, in San Bernardino County. Cable Airport, described as “The World’s Largest Family-Owned, Public-Use Airport” on its Web site, occupies 105 acres and is home to more than 450 aircraft. It opened as Cable-Claremont Airport in 1946 and is operated by the Cable family. Housing tracts surround the small airport. A plane crashed into a home in nearby Claremont on Dec. 14, 2003, killing the pilot. Federal safety investigators concluded last week that pilot Steven Kaplan, 45, became disoriented and lost control of his Cessna while approaching the airport. Send