http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/06/03/ap3782846.html&cid Crash in Sierra Leone Kills at Least 20 - Forbes.com Crash in Sierra Leone Kills at Least 20 06.03.07, 8:04 PM ET A helicopter ferrying passengers to Sierra Leone's main airport crashed late Sunday, bursting into flames and killing at least 20 people, local radio stations and a witness at the airport said. One station, Kalleone FM, said 22 people died, including a pilot who jumped from the helicopter as it crashed at the airport. A witness at the airport, who asked not to be identified, confirmed the crash and said its two pilots both jumped out. One survived and was hospitalized. The witness said the helicopter burst into flames upon crashing. It was destroyed before airport firefighters could put out the flames. Helicopters and a sea ferry are the only ways to get to the airport, located across a bay from the capital, Freetown, which is on the Atlantic Ocean. In 2001, a U.N. helicopter traveling from U.N. headquarters in Sierra Leone to the airport crashed into the bay, killing all seven aboard. The U.N. said at the time a mechanical problem appeared to have been the cause. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-3&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/national/1102AP_Terrorism_Plot_Trinidad.html&cid=1116967600&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Group denies link to NYC terror plot Skip ads and navigation Last updated June 4, 2007 1:38 p.m. PT Group denies link to NYC terror plot Trinidadian Kareem Ibrahim, 56, arrives to the Magistrate Court for an extradition hearing in downtown Port-of-Spain, Trinidad, Monday, June 4, 2007. Ibrahim and Guyanan Abdul Kadir, who are in custody of Trinidadian authorities, are suspects in a plot to blow up a fuel line that feeds New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport. (AP Photo/Andres Leighton) PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad -- The leader of a radical Trinidadian Muslim group denied Monday that his organization had any connection to four men accused of planning to attack New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport. Yasin Abu Bakr, the leader of Jamaat al Muslimeen, told The Associated Press he knew "nothing" about the alleged plan to bomb a fuel pipeline feeding the airport, a plot authorities say was hatched by a group that included a former Guyanese politician. U.S. authorities claim the alleged plotters sought support in Trinidad from Jamaat al Muslimeen, which staged a deadly coup attempt in the Caribbean nation in 1990. The men did not receive such support, according to court documents. But the documents also say that Abdel Nur, a Guyanese suspect thought to be still at large in Trinidad, said he met in May with Abu Bakr at his compound in Trinidad and the Islamic leader suggested that he return later with others involved "to discuss the plan in detail." Nur allegedly said the Jamaat al Muslimeen leader also wanted to do further checks on Russell Defreitas, the 63-year-old accused mastermind of the plot, and an unidentified confidential informant who had infiltrated the group, the documents said. Abu Bakr declined to say if he knew the men, but also denied any involvement. "I know nothing about these men, and I have nothing to do with whatever they are being charged for," he said in his first public comments since U.S. authorities disclosed the plot on Saturday. Two of the suspects - Abdul Kadir, a former member of Guyana's parliament, and Kareem Ibrahim of Trinidad - are in custody in Trinidad. Nur was being sought by Trinidadian authorities. Defreitas, a U.S. citizen native to Guyana and former JFK air cargo employee, was jailed in the United States. Abu Bakr's group, often accused of aiming to create an Islamic state in Trinidad, describes itself simply as a religious organization. The group stormed Parliament and took the prime minister and his Cabinet hostage in a 1990 rebellion that left 24 dead - the only Islamic revolt in the Western Hemisphere. The rebels eventually surrendered and were later pardoned. It is not known to have international reach, although a member was convicted of trying to smuggle 70 assault rifles to Trinidad from Florida in 2005. Abu Bakr faces charges stemming from a 2005 sermon in which he called for war against rich Muslims who refuse to pay zakaat, an Islamic tithe used to alleviate poverty. The following week, he was arrested by police who razed the group's compound and charged him with sedition and incitement to violence. "You know why they are linking me with this so-called plot is to bias the minds of jurors who will be sitting in my case," he said. Separately, a lawyer for the two men held in Trinidad said they would fight extradition to the United States. Ibrahim and Kadir made their initial court appearance Monday for extradition on one count each of conspiracy to commit a terrorist act against the U.S. government. "We will be opposing extradition," said Rajid Persad, a lawyer who represents both men. The judge set another hearing for June 11 to consider bail and scheduled an extradition hearing for Aug. 2. Farid Scoon, another lawyer for the men, said they intend to seek bail. The extradition fight could be a drawn-out affair. Ibrahim and Kadir could appeal all the way to the Privy Council in Britain, the highest court of appeal for the former British territory. Add AP Latin America headlines to Jogging Elvises and more Keep it simple with a high-tech kitchen He's bad with money; don't bank on him AP LATIN AM/CARIB HEADLINES Guantanamo judge dismisses terror case Group denies link to NYC terror plot Silva proposes forest preservation plan Venezuela students spur protest movement 4 indicted men testify about plane crash Thousands of Venezuelans protest Chavez Trinidad Islamic group under scrutiny Colombia fights U.S. diver for treasure Castro looks strong in rare video image Trinidad holds 2 in alleged terror plot Group claims captured troops were killed Rep. Jefferson indicted in bribery probe Bush opens Europe trip on jarring note Guantanamo judge dismisses terror case Group denies link to NYC terror plot Radio bra contest fined in Singapore 8 sets of twins to graduate high school Teens spared in impotent ostrich case 1,683 guitarists play 'Smoke on Water' Indiana kangaroo dies after capture After a half-century in the skies, pilot made mistake No. 1 Microsoft strikes another Linux deal Software Notebook: Is Microsoft turning into a hardware company? As 'Sopranos' end nears, so does Tony's Supreme Court reinstates death sentence for man convicted in carjacking, rape, murder After a half-century in the skies, pilot made mistake No. 1 Workplace Coach: Don't underestimate emotional intelligence Ann's Organic Garden: Do you know what's really in that hose? Schools streamline how math is taught Gates Foundation donates $105 million to UW for health center Bush has fear-mongering down pat State's child car-seat law tightens National Guard: War's other toll Global Warming: A painful buildup 101 Elliott Ave. W. Home Delivery: (206) 464-2121 or (800) 542-0820 seattlepi.com serves about 1.7 million unique visitors and 30 million page views each month. Send investigative tips to
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/04/AR2007060400188.html%3Fhpid%3Dtopnews&cid=1116793406&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg U.S. Judge Clears Canadian Detainee at Gitmo - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up Today's Headlines & Columnists House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted : Largest List Made Public 5 Years at Guantanamo U.S. Judge Clears Canadian Detainee at Gitmo Washington Post Staff Writer Monday, June 4, 2007; 4:28 PM A U.S. military judge today dismissed all charges against a Canadian detainee at Guantanamo Bay, , ruling that his murder trial cannot go forward under the current law governing military commissions. Army Col. Peter Brownback's decision at the island detention facility temporarily ended the case against Omar Khadr, a 20-year-old detainee who allegedly killed a U.S. serviceman during intense fighting in in July 2002. Khadr, who the military has determined is an "enemy combatant," was scheduled for arraignment today in what was to be the second case to go before a military commission. This is a photo of Omar Khadr, taken before he was imprisoned, handed out by his mother Maha Khadr following a news conference in Toronto on Feb. 9, 2005. A military judge on Monday dismissed charges against Canadian detainee Omar Khadr, saying the matter is outside the jurisdiction of the new military tribunal system. The dismissal of the charges does not mean he will be freed from Guantanamo. (AP Photo/Family Handout via Canadian Press) The week's events from around the world, captured in pictures. VIEW THIS WEEK'S PHOTOS Save & Share Article But Brownback decided that the Military Commissions Act of 2006 -- which sets forth the rules for trying detainees at Guantanamo -- limits such commissions to "unlawful enemy combatants" and concluded that the military has never classified Khadr using the term "unlawful." A military review panel decided in September 2004 that Khadr was an "enemy combatant" but did not make any distinction between whether he was a lawful or unlawful combatant. The law, as written, prohibits lawful combatants from trial before military commissions and Brownback ruled that that distinction is vitally important. So-called Combatant Status Review Tribunals examined the cases of 558 detainees held at Guantanamo between August, 2004 and March 2005, concluding in 520 cases that the detainees were "enemy combatants," according to the Defense Department. The tribunals had only two choices: to label the detainees "enemy combatants" or "no longer enemy combatants." The law written in October apparently did not mesh with the military's wording. Pentagon officials immediately dismissed the matter as a legal technicality that can be corrected, but the ruling could put a hold on all military commission prosecutions until it is resolved. Military prosecutors planned to appeal the decision to the Court of Military Commissions Review, which will be based at the military commissions offices in Crystal City but has not been constituted yet, officials said this afternoon. Maj. Elizabeth Kubala, a spokesperson for the Office of Military Commissions, said Brownback did not question whether the military commission is the appropriate forum in which to try members of al-Qaeda for alleged war crimes but that the "existing CSRT definition was not identical to the definition" under the Military Commissions Act. Khadr will not be released as a result of the decision and likely will face a new Combatant Status Review Tribunal to determine his status once again. It is possible, officials said, that any detainee scheduled to go before a military commission will be required to go through a revamped status review before he is charged. The decision received praise from human rights groups who argue that the process is fatally flawed and should be scrapped in favor of trying accused detainees in U.S. courts. The current military commissions were devised by Congress last year after the Supreme Court overturned the Bush Administration's first version of the trials. "If the administration had any sense at all, this would be the final, fatal blow to the military commissions process," said Jennifer Daskal, a Human Rights Watch representative who is at Guantanamo to monitor the commissions. Jumana Musa, who is watching the case for Amnesty International, said the ruling is the "most significant setback" since the commissions were revamped. "The judge's decision clearly indicates that a fair trial is not possible within a system that is being developed as it proceeds," Musa said in a statement. "It raises more questions about the Bush administration and Congress' wisdom and logic in rushing to patch together a new system of justice, when there are fully functioning federal courts that can not only offer fair trials but also come with established procedure." Khadr was to be the second detainee to go through a military commission. Australian David Hicks pleaded guilty to charges of aiding terrorists in March and has been returned home to serve out the remaining months of his sentence. Khadr allegedly threw a grenade at U.S. troops during heavy fighting, killing one. He also allegedly conducted surveillance against U.S. convoy movements in Afghanistan in 2002. 2 Gitmo Detainees Appear Before Tribunal Massacre Survivors Sue U.N., Dutch Gov't Srebrenica Survivors Sue U.N., Dutch Silva Proposes Forest Preservation Plan Landslide Damages Famed Valley in Russia Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed Comments that include profanity or personal attacks or other inappropriate comments or material will be removed from the site. Additionally, entries that are unsigned or contain "signatures" by someone other than the actual author will be removed. Finally, we will take steps to block users who violate any of our posting standards, terms of use or privacy policies or any other policies governing this site. Ple