http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-6&fd=R&url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php%3Fclick_id%3D3%26art_id%3Dnw20070604144524287C413781%26set_id%3D&cid=1116516999&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg IOL: Toll hits 108 deadly Lebanon strife IOL's Most Read Stories IOL on your phone The Independent on Saturday Toll hits 108 deadly Lebanon strife June 04 2007 at 08:17PM Beirut - One hundred and eight people have been killed in 16 days of fighting between the army and Islamist extremists in Lebanon, military and hospital sources said on Monday. It is the deadliest internal violence since the 1975-90 civil war. In the latest bloodshed, two Lebanese soldiers and two Islamist extremists from the Jund al-Sham (Soldiers of Damascus) group were killed in overnight clashes near a refugee camp in the southern port city of Sidon, a military spokesperson said. The army retrieved the body of a soldier on Monday from the outskirts of Nahr al-Bared Palestinian refugee camp where he was killed on Friday during clashes with Fatah al-Islam militants holed up inside the shantytown. Forty-five troops and 41 Fatah al-Islam gunmen have been killed since fighting erupted in the northern city of Tripoli and the nearby Nahr al-Bared camp on May 20, sources on both sides said. One Lebanese civilian was killed in the crossfire when troops attacked a building in Tripoli where Fatah al-Islam militants were holed up on May 20, police and hospital sources said. Seventeen Palestinian refugees have also been killed inside Nahr al-Bared where fighting has continued to rage, according to Sultan Abul Aynayn, Lebanon commander of the mainstream Fatah movement of Palestinian president Mahmud Abbas. The previous deadliest bout of internal fighting was in January 2000 when 45 people were killed in clashes between the army and Sunni militants from the Takfir wal-Hijra (Excommunication and Flight) group in the Dinnieh area of northern Lebanon. There have been much higher death tolls, however, in a series of Israeli offensives against Lebanon since the civil war. Car Insurance for Women USA Green Card Program Win Now For Real Four injured in Beirut grenade blast 'They will not scare us' More wounded in new Lebanon bomb blast 'Ready to fight until the last drop of blood' Now you can get all your news - from politics in South Africa, the quirkiest stories in Step Beyond, the latest from the worlds of Motoring, Entertainment and Business - in one place. and you'll have all the latest news at your fingertips. Jailed journalist awarded Freedom prize German serial rapist is sentenced Toll hits 108 deadly Lebanon strife Israeli tanks roll into Gaza Unfit school kids put on dancing shoes I'm a 34 year old man looking to meet women between the ages of 25 and 34. Top 5 News Stories Public service wage negotiators turn on media 'I'm not desperate for this job': Sexwale One dead, two injured in N12 collision Safa hits back at 'big earner' Parreira Ill-fated breakfast trip for Greek motorist Top 5 Reads - Yesterday Man sleeps as girlfriend is gang raped Driver's 4X4 destroyed at Durban beach Bush wants SA on the team to curb greenhouse Luke under the microscope at Ellis Park Keira to show her sexual side Welcome Elizabeth and James! Market awaits interest rate decision Former Enron executive sentenced European stocks end lower after China selloff Svelte curves, clever chic - Renault's new Laguna Britain's first '30km/h city' gets go-ahead Super Series heavies move into Raceway Mugello win pumps Rossi for title Six in a row for Rossi at Mugello Bella Roma - a contrast of ancient and modern Wild things make our hearts sing Island life and the need to preserve it Make the most of Mozambique Five best budget London hotels IT industry facing skills shortage Otis to train artisans again Getting science graduates jobs Chance to get real work experience for graduates The impact of negativity IOL on your phone &copy; 2007 Independent Online. All rights strictly reserved. Independent Online is a wh