http://www.axcessnews.com/index.php/articles/show/id/11172&cid Democrats debate in New Hampshire Democrats debate in New Hampshire (AXcess News) Washington - Democratic presidential candidates held a debate in New Hampshire last night with victories being declared by more than one of the eight presidential hopefuls, though most primary voters in NH paid closer attention to the leading Democratic candidates - Clinton, Obama and Edwards' responses. All eight Democratic presidential candidates took part in last night's debate in New Hampshire, the site of the first Democratic primary and a place known for its political activism. Wolf Blitzer moderated the debate only this time, the candidates were not held to the rigid structure of timed answers, which helped most of the candidates better respond to questions. Barrack Obama, the Senator from Illinois, responded best to questions about the Iraq war in giving a more regional insight into how it was affecting U.S. relations, both abroad as well as at home. Obama's approach was to consider not just Iraq but the war on terror as a whole in Afghanistan, Iraq and the developments in Iran and Pakistan. He also took to a winning posture against John Edwards when Edwards attempted to play down Obama's view on healthcare stating that most people can't afford the rising cost of healthcare and that making it mandatory would not resolve the gap in healthcare recipients. Hillary Clinton, the only female Democratic presidential candidate, managed to hold onto her esteem when Edward and Obama plucked at her early support for the war in Iraq, but Clinton tiptoed around the onslaught, highlighting her experience in the Senate and that would serve Americans if she were elected to the White House. But Edwards too, had voted for the war in Iraq when he served in the North Carolina Senate. Obama cut Edwards back a notch when he reminded Edwards of his own track record after Edwards criticized both he and Clinton for giving in on the party's mandate for troop withdrawal in the recent Iraq funding bill. "You're about four and a half years late on leadership on this issue," Obama quipped. His comment came after Edwards had stated, "it's the difference between leading and following." All three of the Democratic Party's front runners seemed to walk away from the debate with some measure of victory, holding onto their status in the polls, but never the less, no matter how polite and friendly the Democratic candidates were, you could tell their was friction brewing as the presidential race matures. Never the less, the war in Iraq remained the main theme across the top Democratic presidential candidates for 2008, though voters are growing tired of the same mantra and want to hear more in-depth viewpoints from the candidates. The New Hampshire Democratic presidential debate marked the second time the candidates have met before a live audience. Last month they assembled in South Carolina and the tone of that debate was far more polite. In the latest CBC News Poll, Clinton held a lead over the top Republican presidential candidate, Rudy Giuliani, with a 22 point lead over the ex-New York Mayor, though the poll came last week Thursday and the results following last night's Democratic presidential candidate debate in New Hampshire is still not in. At that time, Clinton held 49 percent of the primary voters in the poll while Giuliani had only 33 percent. But I have to point out that amongst Democrats polled, 63 percent were satisfied with their Party's candidates while only 38 percent of Republican primary voters were satisfied with their Party's slate of presidential candidates. That suggests that Republican contenders better improve their ranks on the issues if they expect to muster enough voter support this November. Your text ad here - This could be your ad, find out more about it here. - Email Marketing Software Prom Dresses exclusive Bridesmaid Gown at $49 5oz Pure Silver Bars - The only 5oz silver bar made in