http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-4&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2007-06-04-jefferson_N.htm&cid=1116966721&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Jefferson indicted in bribery probe - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Sign up to receive our free Daily Briefing e-newsletter and get the top news of the day in your inbox. Breaking news E-mail alerts Get breaking news in your inbox as it happens TIMELINE OF JEFFERSON PROBE FBI begins investigating Jefferson's financial activities. The investigation was touched off by a complaint from a woman who said she was defrauded after investing in a Western African technology project championed by Jefferson. FBI searches Jefferson's homes in Washington and New Orleans. Agents confiscate files and find $90,000 in cash in a freezer. Former Jefferson aide Brett M. Pfeffer pleads guilty to bribery charges. Kentucky businessman Vernon Jackson pleads guilty to paying more than $400,000 in bribes to a congressman identified by federal sources as Jefferson. House ethics committee announces an investigation of Jefferson's activities and appoints a subcommittee to carry it out. FBI agents raid Jefferson's congressional offices, drawing protests from Republican and Democratic House leaders. The search leads to a court challenge that is still pending. Rep. Nancy Pelosi, then the House minority leader, urges House Democrats to vote Jefferson off the House Ways and Means Committee. They agree on a 99-58 vote. Jefferson is forced into a runoff after winning 30 percent of the vote against 12 other candidates. U.S. Court of Appeals rules Justice Department can immediately begin examining documents seized from Jefferson's office that aren't challenged by his attorney. Court delays decision on disputed documents. Jefferson defeats state Rep. Karen Carter, a Democrat, in runoff election, 57 percent to 43 percent. Pelosi refuses to return Jefferson to his seat on the Ways and Means Committee. Assigns him to the Small Business Committee instead. Jefferson is sworn in to his ninth term. A 16-count indictment accuses Jefferson of a pervasive pattern of bribery and corruption and using his office to enrich himself and his family. Jefferson indicted in bribery probe By USA TODAY staff WASHINGTON &#151; Rep. William Jefferson, a Louisiana congressman who garnered nationwide attention after the FBI seized $90,000 from his home freezer in 2005, was named Monday in a 16-count indictment involving elaborate schemes to solicit bribes and hide the proceeds. The congressman is charged with racketeering, soliciting bribes, wire fraud, money-laundering, obstruction of justice, conspiracy and violations of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act. He allegedly solicited bribes for himself and his family, bribed a Nigerian government official and set up a shell company to help hide the money, law enforcement officials said at a news conference. Jefferson, 63, was involved in "a pervasive pattern of fraud, bribery and corruption that spanned many years and two continents," said Chuck Rosenberg, U.S. attorney for the eastern district of Virginia. "The schemes charged are complex. The alleged criminal behavior is spread over time and distance, but the essence of the charges in this case are really rather simple," said Rosenberg. "Mr. Jefferson corruptly traded on his good office and on the Congress, where he served as a member of the United States House of Representatives, to enrich himself and his family through a pervasive pattern of fraud, bribery and corruption that spanned many years and two continents." Jefferson, in Louisiana on Monday, could not immediately be reached for comment. His lawyer was planning a late afternoon news conference. Two of Jefferson's alleged associates have reached plea bargains with prosecutors and have been sentenced. Former congressional aide Brett Pfeffer said he solicited bribes on Jefferson's behalf and was sentenced to eight years in prison. Former Louisville telecommunications executive Vernon Jackson pleaded guilty in May 2006 to paying $400,000 to $1 million in bribes to Jefferson in exchange for his assistance securing business deals in Nigeria and other African nations. Jackson was sentenced to more than seven years in prison. Both Pfeffer and Jackson agreed to cooperate in the case against Jefferson in exchange for their pleas. "If convicted, we will also seek the forfeiture of hundreds of thousands of dollars that Mr. Jefferson obtained through fraud and by his corrupt acts," Rosenberg said. The congressman, whose district includes New Orleans, was re-elected to a ninth term last December despite widespread reports that he was under investigation. In an affidavit sworn out in late May 2006 to obtain a search warrant for the congressman's office, the FBI describes Jefferson retrieving a briefcase filled with $100,000 from a car parked outside the Ritz-Carlton in Arlington, Va. An unnamed witness who is an investigator in iGate, a Kentucky telecommunications firm, alleged Jefferson planned to use the money to coax African officials into deals. Four days later, the FBI raided Jefferson's homes in New Orleans and Washington. The FBI found $90,000 of the cash, which was marked and wrapped in foil in his Washington freezer. The May 20, 2006, raid on his Capitol Hill offices was criticized by leaders of both political parties, who said it was a violation of the constitutional separation of powers. Its legality is being appealed. The impact of the case has stretched across continents and even roiled presidential politics in Nigeria. According to court records, Jefferson told associates he needed cash to pay bribes to the country's vice president, Atiku Abubakar. Abubakar denied the allegations, which figured prominently in that country's presidential elections in April. He ran for the presidency and finished third. The indictment does not name Abubakar. But it describes Jefferson's dealings with an unnamed "Nigerian Official A" who was a high-ranking official in Nigeria's executive branch who had a spouse in Potomac, Md. One of Abubakar's wives lived in that Washington suburb. Contributing: Donna Leinwand in Washington; Randy Lilleston in McLean, Va.; the Associated Press. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor Jefferson in 2006. The indictment is 94 pages long and lists 16 alleged violations of federal law that could keep Jefferson in prison for up to 235 years. USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-4&fd=R&url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007543170&cid=1116944600&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg AHN | Twenty-Two People Killed In Sierra Leone Helicopter Crash | June 4, 2007 global news for the digital world Twenty-Two People Killed In Sierra Leone Helicopter Crash June 4, 2007 3:36 p.m. EST Mary K. Brunskill - AHN News Writer Freetown, Sierra Leone (AHN) - Twenty-two people died in a helicopter crash in Sierra Leone late Sunday, the majority of them Togolese sports officials and fans, government officials said Monday. A committee has been set up to investigate what caused the crash, Sierra Leone Vice President Solomon Berewa's office said in a statement. None of the members of the football team were on board the Russian-made Mi-8 helicopter, which burst into flames as it was landing at Lungi airport. One of the pilots was the only survivor, but he is said to be in critical condition. The passengers on board the helicopter were returning to the airport after watching a football match. Togo's Sports Minister Richard Attipoe was among the dead, along with a flight engineer, a female journalist and members of both the Togolese Sports Ministry and Football Federation. BBC quotes Chernor Ojuku Sesay of the Sierra Leone Football Association as saying, "From what we hear, most of the victims were burnt beyond recognition." On Monday the Togolese government declared three days of national mourning, and sports fans could be seen wearing black armbands in Freetown. Copyright © AHN Media Corp - All rights reserved. Redistribution, republication. syndication, rewriting or broadcast is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AHN. © 2007 by AHN Media Corp.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-4&fd=R&url=http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/FB6DB194-3DF2-4D0D-91D3-69D9660F1DD2.htm&cid=1116516999&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Al Jazeera English - News - More Clashes At Second Lebanon Camp MONDAY, JUNE 04, 2007 10:51 MECCA TIME, 7:51 GMT There are no main images More clashes at second Lebanon camp Fighting spread to the Ain al-Hilweh Palestinian refugee camp in southern Lebanon on Sunday [AFP] Overnight clashes at a Palestinian refugee camp in south Lebanon between the army and the group, Jund al-Sham, have left at least four people dead. Six soldiers and two civilians were also wounded at Ain al-Hilweh camp, hospital sources said on Monday. Shortly after calm was restored, a bomb detonated in east Beirut, injuring seven people. Two soldiers and two fighters were killed in the fighting in the south and the army has accused Jund al-Sham (Soldiers of the Levant) of firing rocket-propelled grenades at one of its checkpoints in the city of Sidon. Fighting has also continued at the Nahr al-Bared camp in north Lebanon. Witnesses said fighters of the group had been involved in clashes with Lebanese troops three times since Sunday night. Munir Maqdah, Fatah's military leader in Lebanon, said the fighting at Ain al-Hilweh had ceased and that the situation was "completely calm". As the Nahr al-Bared refugee camp, the siege continued into Monday evening, and a bomb exploded in Christian east , injuring seven bystanders, a senior security official said. Reports said the bomb exploded on an empty bus close to a commercial centre and a church in the residential and industrial Bouchrieh suburb. A series of bombings has occurred in and around since clashes between Fatah al-Islam fighters and Lebanese army forces began on May 20. Exclusive video of Ain al-Hilweh camp in southern Lebanon , troops resumed pounding the Nahr al-Bared refugee camp near Tripoli around 9am local time (0600 GMT) on Monday, targeting fighters from the Fatah al-Islam group holed up inside. Fifteen days into the seige, Fatah al-Islam has refused to give up its weapons or surrender and is putting up stiff resistance. Since Friday, the army had conducted an intensive assault on the group's positions at the camp's entrances with the aim of wiping out the group. John Cookson, Al Jazeera's correspondent at Nahr al-Bared, said the Lebanese army called Monday's attack the "final stages" of its assault on the camp. Cookson said the attacks "come in waves". He said: "Secret Lebanese security forces are inside the camp, electronically painting buildings they believe fighters are in. It takes hours, or even a day or so to get the guns lined up." A 1969 agreement prevents the army from entering Lebanon's 12 Palestinian camps. The violence, which erupted on May 20, is Lebanon's worst internal fighting since the 1975-1990 civil war. At least 113 people have died and about 25,000 of Nahr al-Bared's 40,000 refugees have fled due to worsening humanitarian conditions. "The Palestinian refugees are not being treated properly by Lebanon" Send us your views The fighting has raised concerns that the violence could spread to more of Lebanon's 12 refugee camps, which hold more than 200,000 Palestinians mostly in conditions of abject poverty. Mike Hanna, Al Jazeera's correspondent at the camp, said a senior Lebanese army intelligence source informed him that there has been intense communication between Jund al-Sham in the south and Fatah al-Islam in the north, as well as a couple of other armed groups. The intelligence source said this communication indicates the attacks are co-ordinated and not random. speaking to Al Jazeera from Ain al-Hilweh, said a meeting between members of the mainstream Palestinian factions in the camp - of which Mahmoud Abbas's Fatah is the most powerful - and the Lebanese army aimed to broker a lasting ceasefire and to " re-organise the distribution of checkpoints in the area" He said: "[The group] Usbat al-Ansar has pledged to control Jund al-Sham members. It is supported by all Palestinian political forces in the camp in order to control the situation. "An extended meeting will be held with the forces in the camp in order to set the mechanism to avoid other such incidents. We will try to form a field security force where all parties in Ain al-Hilweh refugee camp take part. Maqdah also said that Fatah was taking security measures inside Ain al-Hilweh to prevent the conflict from expanding. Source: Al Jazeera and agencies Lebanon camp siege enters third day Army tightens Lebanon camp siege Many dead in Lebanon camp battle Shelling resumes at Lebanon camp Beirut bomb follows camp clashes Bush kicks off Europe tour Group says missing US soldiers dead Pakistan tightens broadcast laws Former Liberia ruler boycotts trial Group says missing US soldiers dead Iran: No retreat on nuclear plan Report doubts US control of Baghdad 1967: 40 years of occupation Fear in Israel's 'ghost city' Group says missing US soldiers dead Iran: No retreat on nuclear plan Report doubts US control of Baghdad 1967: 40 years of occupation Fear in Israel's 'ghost city'
