http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-5&fd=R&url=http://en.rian.ru/world/20070604/66635165.html&cid=1116944600&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg RIA Novosti - World - Russian, Moldovan pilots killed in copter crash in Sierra Leone -1 U.S. claims to defend from Iran's missiles "a joke" - Larijani Putin warns of measures against U.S. missile shield in Europe Russia-U.S. on verge of crisis - paper Russia's first deputy PM says Iskander tests were successful Russia knows how to prevent global warming - academic Russian, Moldovan pilots killed in copter crash in Sierra Leone -1 (Updates headline, figure in lead, adds quote in para 3, new facts in paras 2, 4-6) MOSCOW, June 4 (RIA Novosti) - Two pilots, one Russian and the other Moldovan, were killed and the Russian crew commander gravely injured in a helicopter crash in Sierra Leone late Sunday, the Russian Embassy in nearby Guinea said. The crash killed a total of 23 people, including 20 Togolese soccer officials flying from Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone, to the local international airport following a soccer match between Sierra Leone and Togo, which Togo won 1-0. The flight normally takes seven minutes. "Twenty-three people were onboard, including three crewmembers," Anatoly Maleshov, head of the embassy's consular department, said. "The information concerning the deaths of Russian pilot Alexander Khovaiko and Moldovan pilot Vyacheslav Zaitsev has been confirmed." Maleshov said the only survivor, Russian crew commander Sergei Perlakov, was in hospital. The Reuters news agency quoted local officials as saying Togolese Sports Minister Richard Attipoe, chief of the national soccer delegation, was also one of the crash victims. No soccer players were onboard the helicopter, which belonged to Paramount Airlines. The company operates flights between Freetown and the international airport of Sierra Leone, divided by a river. The cause of the crash is being investigated. Preliminary reports suggest the helicopter could have burst into flames in the air. For more information in Russian back to main page New ICBM debut test Political crisis in Ukraine Russia-EU summit in Samara CFE Treaty on brink of collapse U.S. missile shield plans in Europe LETTERS TO THE EDITOR
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-4&fd=R&url=http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx%3Fid%3DNEWEN20070014362&cid=1116948212&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg NDTV.com: Chinese mark Tiananmen Square massacre June 05, 2007 01:10 [IST] Afghan boat mishap kills 60 Four charged with JFK airport plot Female TV broadcasters threatened Man wakes up from 19-year coma Q.Should bandh organisers be fined for the losses they cause? Do not call registry to come in force Politics fuels demand for caste quota Delhi witnesses Gujjar violence Chinese mark Tiananmen Square massacre For latest headlines SMS (in India & UAE), to Fighting continues at Lebanon camp Transmission of Pak TV channels blocked US senate set to discuss immigration bill JFK plot charges wrong: Isha Kadir Monday, June 4, 2007 (Beijing) Tourists on Monday flocked to Beijing's Tiananmen Square on the 18th anniversary of the Chinese government's bloody crackdown on student protests in 1989. But the atmosphere on the historic square was in most ways no different than any other day. A free-of charge favourite with tourists, cameras flashed during the raising of a Chinese flag by honour guards - a daily ceremony unrelated to the anniversary of the bloodshed. Hundreds, if not thousands were killed as Chinese troops and tanks broke up a seven-week demonstration of the ''Student Democracy Movement'' in Beijing on June 4, 1989, according to accounts of journalists, activists and other eyewitnesses. Information about the incident is heavily censored in China and many people from outside Beijing - particularly the young - still don't know what happened on this day 18 years ago. China's government, which called the protest a counter-revolutionary riot, has yet to fully disclose what happened, and to this day, the former British colony Hong Kong continues to be the only city in China where a large-scale Tiananmen commemoration event is held in public. At the time, many Hong Kongers were horrified by the bloodshed - with only a few years to go before the handover to Chinese rule in 1997, and thousands of people marched in the streets protesting the military action. On Monday, people planned to hold candles and sing commemorative songs in Victoria Park in Hong Kong in an annual ceremony to commemorate those who lost their lives in the bloodshed. [ +Comment on the story ] Be the first to comment...
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-0&fd=R&url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/13439431/detail.html&cid=1116951270&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Three Survive Plane Crash Into Upland Homes - News Story - KTVU San Francisco Make KTVU.com Your Homepage Sign up for E-News DEVASTATING CRASH: See Raw Footage Of Damage From Small Plane Crash Into SoCal Neighborhood Three Survive Plane Crash Into Upland Homes POSTED: 12:09 pm PDT June 4, 2007 UPDATED: 12:54 pm PDT June 4, 2007 A twin-engine plane with three people on board lost power and slammed into homes Monday while trying to land, authorities said. The pilot and two passengers suffered minor injuries. No one on the ground was hurt, said Ian Gregor, spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration. The plane came to rest atop a garage without catching a fire. Its wing rested on the roof of another home. The Piper Seneca was approaching Cable Airport when it lost power and crashed into three homes on Blossom Circle. The plane departed from Van Nuys Airport in the San Fernando Valley. "They were on approach when the pilot reported engine problems," Gregor said. Weather didn't appear to be a factor. It was sunny with no clouds or fog. Upland is about 45 miles east of Los Angeles, near the junction of Interstates 10 and 15, in San Bernardino County. Cable Airport, described as "The World's Largest Family-Owned, Public-Use Airport" on its Web site, occupies 105 acres and is home to more than 450 aircraft. It opened as Cable-Claremont Airport in 1946 and is operated by the Cable family. Housing tracts surround the small airport. A plane crashed into a home in nearby Claremont on Dec. 14, 2003, killing the pilot. Federal safety investigators concluded last week that pilot Steven Kaplan, 45, became disoriented and lost control of his Cessna while approaching the airport. . The Associated Press contributed to this report. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. La. Congressm