(AP) - Republican presidential contenders John McCain and Mitt Romney clashed today over how to solve immigration problems. McCain embraced a bipartisan bill in Congress as a practical solution. Romney dismissed it as unworkable. McCain spoke in politically crucial Florida, with its heavy concentration of Cuban and Haitian immigrants. He argued that while the bill is imperfect, it is an attempt to secure US borders, help the economy and identify those who have entered the nation illegally. The four-term Arizona senator chided rivals who he says are trying to score points on the issue. McCain never mentioned any names but his target was obvious - Romney. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Learn more about your favorite KVOA personalities. KVOA and KVOA-DT&#39;s program schedule The latest in national and international headlines. Read about your favorite NBC stars and programs. Contact NBC . Get NBC gear. Find out how you can include KVOA.com headlines in your RSS news reader or website. Search by zip code or movie title. Order online when you see the All content &copy; Copyright 2003 - 2007 WorldNow and KVOA. All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-6&fd=R&url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm%3Fc_id%3D2%26objectid%3D10443632&cid=1116957627&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Climate change 'onus on wealthy nations' - 05 Jun 2007 - NZ Herald: World / International News The New Zealand Herald: Tuesday June 05, 2007 Climate change 'onus on wealthy nations' Tuesday June 05, 2007 Rag pickers carry plastic scrap for recycling on the eve of United Nations' World Environment Day in Hafania, India. Photo / Reuters ASX ready for carbon Green hue gives Howard big boost Putin threatens Europe with new missile targets Merkel between Bush and a hard sell It's World Environment Day. What's your one simple, day-to-day tip to help the planet? Send us your views BEIJING - China promised yesterday to integrate climate change policy into its industrial and energy sectors, but said it would not cave in to international pressure over global warming by sacrificing economic growth. China's first national plan on climate change vows to combat global warming through energy saving, agricultural adaptation, and forest expansion. The plan promises "to integrate climate change policy into other interrelated policies". But the broad blueprint also says developed powers bear the most blame for filling the atmosphere with greenhouse gases. The unveiling of Beijing's climate action plan comes as President Hu Jintao prepares to attend the G8 summit in Germany at which global warming will be major issue. China yesterday welcomed United States President George W. Bush's proposals on global warming as a "positive change", but stressed that any new agreements should not displace the Kyoto Protocol. The Bush plan aims to gather representatives from 15 top polluting nations this year to discuss climate change and come up with long-term goals to combat global warming by the end of 2008. Ma Kai, chief of China's National Development and Reform Commission, which steers climate policy, said any new agreement should complement the United Nations' accord. China, the world's second largest emitter of greenhouse gases after the US, is under international pressure to spell out targets for taming greenhouse gas emissions. The country of 1.3 billion people says it is tackling emissions but ensuring economic growth is its top priority. "The first and overriding priorities of developing countries are sustainable development and poverty eradication," says the plan. Among other steps, the document promises to encourage clean power generation, develop new crop varieties that can withstand long dry spells, and to expand forests that will soak up carbon dioxide. China said it was willing to co-operate with other nations to combat the threat of climate change, but Ma said developed countries had the "unshirkable responsibility" for taking the lead in tacking global warming. "The international community should respect the developing countries' right to develop," Ma said. China estimated its 2004 emissions of greenhouse gases were the equivalent of about 6.1 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide. But Ma said the country's per capita emissions were about one fifth of those of the US. China hopes to reduce greenhouse gas emissions through more use of hydropower, wind and biomass energy, boosting nuclear power generation and increasing the efficiency of coal-burning stations. Hottest May on record - and rain - in Australia Latest ruling may preclude all Guantanamo trials Putin threatens Europe with new missile targets JFK airport plot suspects appear in Trinidad court Qaeda-led group shows video of missing soldiers' IDs Day of reckoning for ex Liberian President 8:30AM Ethiopia urges Queen to return remains of royal orphan 7:30AM Hospital refuses kidney from religious sect 7:15AM Help for spat on bus drivers Angry elephant prompts appeal Green hue gives Howard big boost Lebanese army faces fight on two fronts Climate change 'onus on wealthy nations' Hottest May on record - and rain - in Australi