http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-6&fd=R&url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2007/0605/p02s01-usmi.html&cid=1116745519&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg A leaner, looser 'Star Wars' system | csmonitor.com Letter to the Editor from the June 5, 2007 edition A leaner, looser 'Star Wars' system President Bush's missile-shield plans are stoking cold-war tensions, as Putin threatens to re-aim Russian weapons at Europe. | Staff writer of The Christian Science Monitor Page 1 of 2 The missile-defense plans of today's Pentagon are far less ambitious than those envisioned by the Reagan-era Strategic Defense Initiative. Out, is the concept of an impenetrable domed shield for the US. In, is possible limited security against an accidental launch or rogue power such as North Korea. Yet 30 years after "Star Wars" roiled world geopolitics, US missile defense remains a contentious issue, both in Washington and abroad. Support for missile defense in Congress remains mixed. Meanwhile, Russia continues to hammer at Bush administration plans to deploy missile-defense elements in Europe with rhetoric that harks back to US-Soviet cold war days. In an interview released Monday, Russian President Vladimir Putin suggested that he might respond by re-aiming nuclear weapons at Europe. Military sites on the Continent could be targeted with "ballistic or cruise missiles or maybe a completely new system," said Putin. So far the US has placed 17 long-range interceptor missiles at Fort Greely, Alaska, and Vandenberg Air Force, Calif., according to US Missile Defense Agency officials. This system is still under development, though it was raised to operational status during a recent North Korean missile test. In Europe, plans call for ten interceptors based in Poland, with a radar in the Czech Republic. Overall, the Missile Defense Agency has conducted more than 35 major tests, Air Force Lt. Gen. Henry Obering III, Missile Defense Agency director, told Congress in April. "Overall, since 2001 we have built a record of 26 successful hit-to-kill engagements in 34 attempts," said Gen. Obering. This year the Pentagon is requesting $8.9 billion in missile defense funds, with $7.1 billion of that devoted to developing near-term capabilities, and $1.8 billion earmarked to develop defenses against future threats. Missile defense has enthusiastic boosters on Capitol Hill. Sen. Daniel Inouye (D) of Hawaii, chairman of the Senate Appropriations Subcommittee on Defense, said on April 25 that "after nearly 25 years and over $90 billion spent, I believe we can finally say that ... we have turned a corner. The United States has a [missile defense] system in place that could be operational if needed." Letter to the Editor Get Monitor stories by e-mail: (Your e-mail address will be protected by csmonitor.com's tough Red-state senators feel the heat of a fiery immigration debate Climate debate heats up G-8 Years later, Valdez's stain remains Charles Taylor's trial puts dictators on notice Red-state senators feel the heat of a fiery immigration debate In nouveau riche India, even the poor show off What do we owe the wrongly convicted? Like the look of a traditional newspaper? Try the Monitor's Treeless Edition ChÃ¡vez is no enemy of free speech In nouveau riche India, even the poor show off Red-state senators feel the heat of a fiery immigration debate A leaner, looser 'Star Wars' system Give a gift subscription Receive our free e-mail newsletters: T-Shirts - Design Online Free DIY Logo Design MA in Diplomacy - Online Subscribe to our RSS Feeds Stay up to date with the latest news Today's Article on Christian Science www.csmonitor.com | Copyright &#169; 2007 The Christian Science Monitor. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-3&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/06/04/europe/hong.php&cid=1116948212&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Hong Kong remembers Tiananmen - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings A soldier looked over a group of visitors in Beijing&#039;s Tiananmen Square on Monday, the anniversary of a 1989 crackdown there. Hong Kong remembers Tiananmen International Herald Tribune, Reuters, The Associated Press Published: June 4, 2007 People gathered Monday to commemorate the anniversary of the bloody crackdown on the Tiananmen Square protests in Beijing 18 years ago at a candlelight vigil here - the only place in China where such a large public commemoration is traditionally held. The day began quietly in Tiananmen Square in Beijing, where tourists gathered to watch a daily flag-raising ceremony amid tight security. There were no immediate reports of demonstrations on the mainland. Tiananmen Square was full of the usual tour groups, both Chinese and foreign, and locals flying kites, as well as plainclothes security and police vans. At its north end, in front of the giant portrait of Mao Zedong, the police surrounded a woman and rifled through her bag before bundling her off in the back of a van, a sign of the tight rein China keeps on petitioners and protesters. Security forces try to snuff out Tiananmen memorials quickly on the mainland. But Hong Kongers are allowed to mark the anniversary publicly because the former British colony has been promised a wide degree of autonomy since its 1997 handover to China. Today in Asia - Pacific Hong Kong remembers Tiananmen Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps Philippine troops defuse bus bomb after U.S. warning Thousands of people usually gather for Hong Kong&#039;s Tiananmen memorial, lighting candles and singing solemn songs in Victoria Park, a spacious venue near the city center. Many residents of the city had supported the Tiananmen protesters, thinking they might help bring political change to China. They were horrified when troops and tanks crushed the demonstration, killing hundreds - maybe thousands. The violence raised fears that the Communist leadership would not honor its promise to allow Hong Kong the civil liberties its people enjoyed under British rule. But 10 years after the handover, Hong Kong still enjoys freedoms that people on the mainland can only dream about. Street protests are common and the press often criticizes the government, though media observers say self-censorship is also frequent. China&#039;s government has called the Tiananmen protest a counterrevolutionary riot and has yet to fully disclose what happened. Human Rights Watch said Beijing&#039;s failure to account for the crackdown has cast a pall on the nation&#039;s campaign to project a new image, even as it prepares to hold the 2008 Olympic Games in 14 months. The New York-based group also said that survivors and victims&#039; families had been subjected to intrusive scrutiny by security officials ahead of the anniversary. "What kind of Olympic host marks the annual anniversary of a brutal massacre by persecuting victims&#039; families and detaining dissidents?" asked Sophie Richardson, the group&#039;s deputy Asia director. "Beijing - and by extension, the 2008 Olympic Games - will remain tarnished by this legacy until the Chinese government provides a complete and truthful account of what happened in June 1989," she said. At least 13 little-known Chinese are still behind bars for their roles in the pro-democracy movement, a human rights group said Monday. "I want to tell those who claim that Tiananmen &#039;belongs to another era&#039; that, behind the high, barbed-wire-ringed walls of the Chinese prisons, Tiananmen prisoners are still suffering and forced to engage in hard labor day and night today," the Chinese Human Rights Defenders said in an e-mailed statement, quoting an unidentified former prisoner of conscience. Few details were known about the 13, beyond their names, the group added. At least three were convicted of "counterrevolutionary sabotage" and one of "counterrevolutionary assault." Seven are serving suspended death sentences and six are imprisoned for life, it said. In Beijing, one victim&#039;s mother, Ding Zilin, was allowed to mourn her son&#039;s death Sunday night in the place where he was shot, the Hong Kong-based Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy said. Plainclothes security officers stood by Ding but did not stop her, the center said. Ding, who founded the group Tiananmen Mothers, placed flowers on the spot near the western gate of Tiananmen Square, the Hong Kong broadcaster Commercial Radio reported. The Tiananmen crackdown also shocked Taiwan - a self-ruled, democratic island that Beijing insists should reunited with the mainland. Many Taiwanese cite Tiananmen as a reason to continue resisting China&#039;s calls for unification. Ma Ying-jeou, an opposition presidential candidate in the election next year, issued a statement saying, "The June 4 Tiananmen incident was China&#039;s most drastic suppression of the mainland&#039;s democratic movement." He urged China to push for democratic change. The governing Democratic Progressive Party in Taiwan also criticized Beijing. "China has moved backward since the Tiananmen incident," a party spokesman, Lai I-chung, said. Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Advertise with the IHT Copyright &#169; 2007 the International Herald Tribune All rights reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-2&fd=R&url=http://euronews.net/index.php%3Fpage%3Dinfo%26article%3D425826%26lng%3D1&cid=1116579515&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg EuroNewsEuroNews : UN war crimes prosecutor moves Serbia closer to EU talks UN war crimes prosecutor moves Serbia closer to EU talks In Belgrade, Serbia's latest moves towards eventually joining the EU took another step, with the arrival in the city of the chief prosecutor from the UN war crimes tribunal. Carla Del Ponte is there to assess the government's co-operation with the tribunal in the Hague, which is key to the prospect of EU membership. Once she reports back, preliminary talks on joining - which stalled last year because of non-cooperation - could resume. One sticking point was overcome last week, when Serb authorities arrested and delivered to the Hague Zdravko Tolimir, who is accused of genocide during the Bosnian war. Tolimir was the right-hand man to the one on the top of the tribunal's wanted list - Ratko Mladic - who is still at large. Observers say it is unlikely the EU will actually sign anything with Serbia until Mladic is before the court. More clashes ahead of G8 summit China won't sacrifice growth in climate change battle Uncertainty in Czech Republic over US missile defence project Families sue Dutch government over Srebrenica Former Liberian President Taylor boycotts trial opening Charles Taylor's long road to the Hague Kurdish rebels blamed for deadly Turkey attack Fighting in Lebanon spreads to second camp Home Shopping at Next Online New home shopping in the next summer directory with next-day delivery. Request your copy of the new directory or order online from our wide range of quality products. Online Home Shopping at JD Williams The latest designs and fashions at JD Williams. Clothing, lingerie, swimwear and footwear available online today. Sizes from 12 to 38. Get 10% off your first order today. Fashion That Fits Your Lifestyle at Fifty Plus Fashion that fits in size