http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-5&fd=R&url=http://www.annistonstar.com/opinion/2007/as-editorials-0604-editorial-7f03w1534.htm&cid=1116849505&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg The Anniston Star » A presidential pledge to keep A presidential pledge to keep The 2008 race for president has been placed in a microwave oven set on high. Democratic and Republican hopefuls are already debating on TV. Big-time contributors are being hit up for dollars. Candidates are staking out policy positions. States are jockeying for position to put their presidential primary even earlier in the 2008 calendar. The Anniston Star » Opinion » Editorials A presidential pledge to keep The 2008 race for president has been placed in a microwave oven set on high. Democratic and Republican hopefuls are already debating on TV. Big-time contributors are being hit up for dollars. Candidates are staking out policy positions. States are jockeying for position to put their presidential primary even earlier in the 2008 calendar. Despite the likelihood that most of the public is not yet tuned in to a general election that is 18 months away, the process has merit. While candidates are making promises here's one for all of them to raise their right hand to: If elected president of the United States, I will not tolerate any member of my administration, including my vice president, disclosing the undercover status of a U.S. spy. According to court filings admitted recently by a federal prosecutor, if George W. Bush had made that pledge he would very likely be under increasing pressure to find a new vice president and a new political guru. Valerie Plame Wilson was a covert CIA officer when her identity was leaked to the media by White House officials in July 2003. In connection to the case I. Lewis “Scooter” Libby has been convicted for obstructing the probe into Wilson's outing, a move seen as revenge against her husband's truth-telling about the Bush administration's prewar fibs on Iraq's threat. Libby, former State Department official Richard Armitage and Bush political strategist Karl Rove were among those involved in the outing of a CIA agent. Libby's trial revealed that Cheney was the person who told Libby of Plame; citing various government sources, the National Journal has reported that it was Cheney who directed Libby to out Wilson in an attempt to discredit her husband. Wilson has testified that when she learned of these leaks, first reported by conservative columnist Robert Novak, she “felt like I had been hit in the gut, it was over in an instant, I immediately thought of my family's safety.” In the process of requesting Libby be sentenced to somewhere between 30 months and 36 months in prison, prosecutor Patrick Fitzgerald released the declassified summary of Plame's status. “Ms. Wilson was a covert CIA employee for who the CIA was taking affirmative measures to conceal her intelligence relationship to the United States.” There it is, despite years of denials by Bush administration water-carriers. Valerie Plame Wilson was a covert agent. She kept her connection to the Central Intelligence Agency hidden. In other words, until a revenge-minded White House played politics with the identity of a covert CIA agent in the summer of 2003, Wilson was among that secret army of intelligence agents who work to keep Americans safe. The current crop of presidential candidates who claim to be worthy of the office ought to pledge to turn away from the current White House's horrid example. About our editorial page Address letters to Speak Out, The Anniston Star, P.O. Box 189, Anniston, AL 36202. Please limit letters to 200 words. Letters may be edited for length, libel and taste. All letters are confirmed with the author before publication. Contact our editorial page More from AP » Gallery » A Man and His Land Gallery » Photo of the Quarter Video » Calhoun Co. Sheriff's Office Pipes and Drums Gallery » Above Northeast Alabama Subscribe to The Anniston Star Copyright ©