http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-5&fd=R&url=http://www.citynews.ca/news/news_11659.aspx&cid=1116793406&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg CityNews: Military Judge Drops Charges Against Omar Khadr / Military Judge Drops Charges Against Omar Khadr Send to a Friend Military Judge Drops Charges Against Omar Khadr Monday June 4, 2007 Charges against Canadian terror suspect were dropped by a military judge Monday, who ruled that the matter was outside his jurisdiction. Col. Peter Brownback's decision came only minutes into Khadr's arraignment on alleged war crimes and terror-related offences. "The charges are dismissed without prejudice," Brownback said, marking a surprisingly quick end to the proceeding. The reason for the dismissal may have been a technicality - Brownback said that only those classified as "alien unlawful enemy combatants" could be tried under the signed last year by President George W. Bush. The act replaced the previous war-cirmes trial system which was rejected by the U.S. Supreme Court. Khadr, 20, had been classified as simply an "enemy combatant." Khadr was accused of throwing a grenade that killed American soldier Sgt. 1st Class Christopher Speer in Afghanistan in 2002. He was 15 at the time. Khadr appeared in court clothed in an olive-green prison uniform and sporting a beard. Even though the charges have been dropped there's no indication the Canadian man will be freed from the military base anytime soon. He's one of roughly 380 men being held at the camp suspected of having links to terror groups like the Taliban and al-Qaida. Khadr, whose father Ahmen Said Khadr was apparently close to al-Qaida leader Osama bin Laden before he was killed by Pakistani troops in 2003, was about to go to trial at the beginning of last year before the Supreme Court put an end to the tribunals. Send to a Friend Highway 427 Ramp Cramp Will Extend Jam Into Rush Hour Third Person Dies Following Stolen Car Chase Car Chases An Instant Decision For Police Dog Park Deb