http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-2&fd=R&url=http://www.kwtx.com/nationalnews/headlines/7822992.html&cid=1116960165&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg KWTX - National News Militant Web Site Plans To Release Video Of Abducted Soldiers (June 4, 2007)--An Islamic militant Web site said Monday it will release video clips showing the capture of three American soldiers who disappeared a few weeks ago following an ambush. The body of one soldier, Pfc. Joseph Anzack Jr, was later found inIraq's Euphrates River, but the other two soldiers have not been found. The Washington-based SITE Institute said it had obtained the 10-minute, 41-second video that shows the planning stages, kidnapping operation, as well as footage from after the attack. The institute, which monitors militant Web sites, said the video also shows the identification cards of two of the two missing soldiers. A prominent Islamic Web site, which often posts videos from militant groups, said it would show the video within hours. The three US soldiers were captured south of Baghdad on May 12 in an ambush later claimed by an insurgent umbrella group, the Islamic State of Iraq, that includes al-Qaeda in Iraq. More Local And State News >> More National News >> More Business News >> Bush Arrives In Prague Woman Dragged To Her Death After Collision Official: Ruling Could End War-Crimes Trial System Michiganâ€™s Abortion Law Declared Unconstitutional Woman Who Plowed Through Crowd May Have Been High Al-Qaeda-Linked Group Says Abducted US Soldiers Are All Dead Suspects In JFK Terrorist Plot Face Extradition Federal Appeals Court Upholds Missouri Execution Procedure Murders, Robberies Rose in 2006 Gray Television Group, Inc. - Copyright Â© 2002-2007 - Designed and Powered by Clickability
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-4&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/environment/2007-06-04-china-energy_N.htm&cid=1116957627&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg China's first energy plan lacks specific cuts - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Sign up to receive our free Daily Briefing e-newsletter and get the top news of the day in your inbox. Breaking news E-mail alerts Get breaking news in your inbox as it happens Reaction cool to Bush emissions Study: Drought overstated, floods understated Biggest fear of global warming? Key findings left out Earth nearing &#39;tipping points&#39; High acidity endangers ocean reefs Too late for polar areas? Ice key to life on Earth It happens like a boat tipping Use of fossil fuels blamed China's first energy plan lacks specific cuts By Calum MacLeod, USA TODAY BEIJING &#151; China, the world's second-largest producer of greenhouse gases, unveiled its first national climate change program Monday, but a government official said other industrialized nations also bore the responsibility to combat global warming. "At some point in time China will overtake the USA as the biggest emitter of greenhouse gases," said Ma Kai, China's top economic planning official, as he introduced the new program Monday in Beijing. The International Energy Agency warns China may overtake the United States within two years. But Ma said China's right to modernize and industrialize outweighed international pressure to set caps on emissions that could hurt the country's economic development. The program announced Monday stresses improved energy efficiency to help China slow greenhouse gas emissions, which scientists say trap heat in the atmosphere, but the plan does not commit to any cut in total output. "We will not tread the traditional path to industrialization through high consumption and high emissions," promised Ma, head of the National Development and Reform Commission, which directs China's climate policy. "We want to deliver economic development and protect the environment," he said. The challenge of achieving that balance will be high on the agenda this week in Germany, when China's President Hu Jintao joins President Bush at a Group of Eight leaders meeting. Ma Kai welcomed Bush's proposals on global warming, announced Thursday, as a "positive shift in attitude," but insisted the new U.S. initiative should be "a useful complement to the U.N. Framework Convention and the Kyoto Protocol, and not a substitute for the two international documents." The breakneck growth of the Chinese economy, mainly fired by electricity from coal-burning, heavily-polluting power stations, has prompted international calls for China to set emissions caps. Beijing continues to reject such pressure as unfair interference from developed nations who have caused most greenhouse gases to date. "To ask developing countries to lower emissions too early, too abruptly and too bluntly will hinder their development and hamper efforts to achieve industrialization and modernization," said Ma. To respond to climate change, the plan stresses measures such as energy conservation, better technology in farming and forestry expansion. Beijing hopes the new measures will boost energy efficiency by 20% by 2010, and increase the percentage of renewable energy to 10% from the current 7% in 2010. While Ma did not disclose the cost of China's program, he said "whatever the cost is, it is worth it. Early action will cost less than late action." Citing historical data to show developed countries produced 77% of global CO2 emissions from burning fossil fuels from 1950 to 2002, Ma said developed nations have an "unshirkable responsibility" for climate change. Even when China overtakes the USA as the leading producer of greenhouse gases, "China's per capita output will only be one fifth of the USA's," Ma said. Referring to Bush's proposals on global warming, Ma welcomed the new initiative's link "between climate change on the one hand and economic development and energy security on the other." The "common ground" between Washington and Beijing is expanding, Ma said. However, developed nations are still not living up to their promises to supply the developing world with financial and technical aid to tackle climate change, he added. "We have heard a lot of thunder, but have not seen much rain," Ma said, reminding developed nations of their "obligations under international conventions to provide technical and financial support to developing nations." On Sunday, China's government released a work plan for energy conservation, whose targets it missed last year, and promised to reduce major pollutant discharges by 10%. In contrast to the past, when economic growth was the only criteria for promotion, local government leaders and company heads were put on notice that their records on energy efficiency and pollutant reduction will be key to future performance assessments. One concrete measure announced Sunday calls for a minimum temperature of 26 degrees Celsius (78.8 degrees Fahrenheit) in all China's air-conditioned public rooms. The move aims to save China's limited energy resources when electricity demand peaks in the country's hot summer months. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
