http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-6&fd=R&url=http://www.adnki.com/index_2Level_English.php%3Fcat%3DPolitics%26loid%3D8.0.421370722%26par%3D0&cid=1116579515&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg BOSNIA: FAMILIES OF SREBRENICA VICTIMS SUE NETHERLANDS AND U.N. BOSNIA: FAMILIES OF SREBRENICA VICTIMS SUE NETHERLANDS AND U.N. The Hague, 4 June (AKI) - The families of up to 8,000 Muslims killed in 1995 by Bosnian Serb forces in the eastern town of Srebrenica sued the United Nations and the Dutch state for failing to prevent the genocide. Marko Gericen, a lawyer for the grieving families, told journalists the case before the Dutch Supreme court "isn&#8217;t of a financial nature" but is intended to see justice done. Unfortunately, the UN and the Dutch government are not ready to assume responsibility and don&#8217;t even want to talk about it, he added. Srebrenica was a UN protected 'safe haven' when Bosnian Serb forces attacked it in July 1995, but the Dutch authorities refused crucial air support ordered by the UN for some 450 Dutch troops defending the enclave, enabling Bosnian Serb forces to abduct and massacre 8,000-10,000 Muslim men and boys, the families' lawyers said. Gericen said he would call as witnesses former UN secretary-general Boutros Ghali and Kofi Annan, to prove that the Dutch government ignored the UN order to use air support. The UN is also blamed in the suit for negligence and lack of action. &#8220;We want to show Europe what has been done to us, and demand from that same Europe only truth and justice,&#8221; Munira Subasic, president of an association of Srebrenica mothers told journalists. The suit coincided with the arrest of former Bosnian Serb general Zdravko Tolimir last week, on charges of genocide at Srebrenica. He was expected to make a plea before the Hague-based International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia on Monday. In a historic and controversial ruling in February, the top UN court, the Hague-based International Court of Justice (ICJ) acquitted Serbia of genocide during the 1992-1995 Bosnian civil war. The tribunal found that Bosnian Serb forces did commit genocide and pronounced Belgrade guilty of failing to prevent genocide. Former Dutch prime minister Wim Kok resigned in 2002, after a report blaming Dutch soldiers for inaction at Srebrenica was made public. The report fingered Kok and his government for sending Dutch soldiers on an &#8220;impossible mission&#8221; in Bosnia during the civil war. EGYPT: ITALIAN MPS IN CAIRO VISIT EAST TIMOR: OPTIMISM ON UPCOMING ELECTIONS SERBIA: DEL PONTE STEPS UP HUNT FOR WAR CRIMES SUSPECTS ISLAM: BLAIR CALLS FOR MORE UK TRAINED IMAMS PAKISTAN: MUSHARRAF TIGHTENS CONTROL OVER MEDIA INDONESIA: PRESIDENT'S AIDE DEFENDS ANTI-IRAN VOTE AT U.N. BOSNIA: FAMILIES OF SREBRENICA VICTIMS SUE NETHERLANDS AND U.N. MONTENEGRO: U.N. REFUGEE AGENCY MOBILIZES LAWYERS TO ADDRESS STATELESSNESS SYRIA: EX-PRESIDENTIAL AIDE PREVIEWS ITALIAN MINISTER'S VISIT AZERBAIJAN: JOURNALIST ARRESTED OVER ARTICLE ON IRAN
