http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-3&fd=R&url=http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp%3Fstid%3D1%26aid%3D70353&cid=1116936276&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Your S.I. News Now Your N.J. News Now NYer of the Week This Day in History NY1 Info & History On NY1 Now: Weather On 1 Weather: Mostly cloudy. High:71 Democratic White House Hopefuls Face Off In The Granite State Candidates in the Democratic presidential race debated for the second time Sunday night, with frontrunner Hillary Clinton trying to preserve a lead in the polls amid attacks on her vote for war in Iraq. NY1’s Josh Robin filed the following report. Her record on Iraq again under the microscope, Senator Hillary Clinton pointed fingers at the White House, rather than her Democratic rivals, as a crowded field of candidates took the stage in Sunday night’s Democratic presidential debate in New Hampshire, the site of the first presidential primary. "This is George Bush's war,” said Clinton. “He is responsible for this war." It was one tactic the senator used Sunday night to try hold her advantage against her Democratic opponents, even as two new books scrutinize the front-runner. CNN played host at the forum, where Clinton faced off against seven others, including Illinois Senator Barack Obama and former North Carolina Senator John Edwards, who are polling nationally second and third respectively. Obama has emerged as an anti-war favorite, the only one of the three against it from the start, although he wasn't in the Senate during the 2002 authorization vote. But it was Edwards with the sharpest attacks on Sunday, carving away at the top pair. "They went quietly to the floor of the Senate; cast the right vote. But there is a difference between leadership and legislating,” said Edwards. "You want to name names,” asked the debate’s moderator, CNN’s Wolf Blitzer. "No, I think it's obvious who I'm talking about,” said Edwards. That would be Clinton and Obama, who voted last month against continuing war funding, but, in Edwards' eyes, without enough effort at explaining their position. "I think all of us have a responsibility to lead on these issues,” said Edwards. Clinton grimaced. Obama retorted with one of the night's sharpest lines. "John, the fact is that I opposed this war from the start, so you're about four and a half years late on leadership on this issue,” he said. Clinton spent the two hours more subdued, an above the fray strategy casting herself as anti-Bush enough to win Democrats, but presidential enough to win it all. Still, new questions are rising that could block her from the nomination, like why she didn't read an entire intelligence briefing before the authorization vote, and will she apologize now for the vote. Here's as far as she'd go. "It was a mistake to trust George Bush, that he would do what he told all of us he would do,” she said. She also defended her husband's “don't ask, don't tell policy” on gays in the military. Clinton called it a transitional policy. But like all the other candidates, she supports overturning it, and letting homosexuals openly serve. The ten Republican hopefuls will debate in New Hampshire on Tuesday. Mayor Aims To Quiet Fears Over JFK Terror Plot Schumer Seeks To Make Buildings Across Country More Energy Efficient Democratic White House Hopefuls Face Off In The Granite State Off-Track Betting Terminals Could Be Heading To City Bars DOT To Outfit Streetlights With LED Detectors City Experiencing Baby Boom Among Mexican Immigrants Firefighters Extinguish Long-Burning Blaze At Brooklyn Warehouse Private Sanitation Worker Dies After Fall From Garbage Truck Sharpton To Use Soap To Symbolically Clean Up Rap Lyrics Non Profit Turns Restaurant Grease Into Bio-Diesel Fuel Looking for ways to conserve energy this summer? Check out these series of energy-saving tips from the New York Energy Smart Program. Time Warner Cable Digital subscribers can now watch NY1 Living stories and other NY1 features on channel 1110, with our n