http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-2&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/world/middleeast/04cnd-lebanon.html%3Fhp&cid=1116516999&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Fighting in Lebanese Camp Worsens - New York Times Fighting in Lebanese Camp Worsens New clashes sparked fears that a conflict in the Nahr al Bared camp outside Tripoli may be spreading. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: June 4, 2007 , June 4—Two Lebanese soldiers and two militants were killed in fighting in Ain al Hilwe refugee camp in southern Lebanon early today, capping a night of violence in both northern and southern Lebanon. Skip to next paragraph The New York Times Fighting in the north at Nahr al Bared spread to Ain al Hilwe. The clashes sparked fears that a conflict in the Nahr al Bared camp on the outskirts of this northern Lebanese town may be spreading. Militants in the northern camp have been besieged by the army for more than two weeks. In a series of skirmishes that began Sunday afternoon, fighters of the Islamist group Jund al Sham opened fire on Lebanese army soldiers. The firefight that followed left numerous houses inside the camp ablaze and ultimately resulted in the death of the four men, military officials said. Meanwhile, 60 miles north at the Nahr al Bared camp, Lebanese troops continued their offensive against another militant group, Fatah al Islam, directing machine gun fire and artillery shelling into the camp for much of Sunday and early today. At least 114 people have been killed in the siege of the camp, which began when security men raided an apartment in Tripoli seeking bank robbers. A tenuous calm set in over both camps this afternoon as Palestinian and religious leaders sought to calm tempers in Ain al Hilwe, the southern camp, and to negotiate an end to the 16 days of violence at Nahr al Bared. Both camps are home to tens of thousands of Palestinian refugees displaced in the successive wars between Israel and its Arab neighbors. Palestinian factions held talks with the Lebanese army command in Sidon this morning, as heavily armed Jund al-Sham fighters agreed to cede their positions to militiamen from other Islamist groups at Ain al Hilwe, where more than 47,000 refugees live. Despite sporadic gunfire in Nahr al Bared, aid agencies worked to get water and food into the camp today. Red Cross officials said a few civilians had managed to escape the camp, while the aid agency warned that conditions inside were worsening significantly, and made an appeal for new funds to assist refugees who have escaped the camp. Thousands of refugees have escaped over the past two weeks, but aid groups estimate that about 6,000 residents remain trapped inside in the crossfire. Reporters have been banned from the camp and have been pushed back out of sight of the fighting, making it difficult to confirm reports from either side. The army continued to reinforce its positions around the camp today, and brought in armor, troops and supplies, possibly in preparation for another push against Fatah al-Islam. Nada Bakri contributed reporting from Tripoli, Lebanon. More Articles in International &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Fighting Worsens as Lebanese Army Surrounds Militants 18 Dead in Lebanon as Army and Militants Clash Mixed Reaction in Lebanon to U.N. Assassination Tribunal U.N. Approves Court to Prosecute Hariri Killing More Articles in International &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Frida Kahlo and Diego Rivera - 1930. Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
