http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.diamonds.net/news/NewsItem.aspx%3FArticleID%3D17894&cid=1116823250&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg Diamonds.net News - Liberia's Taylor Shuns First Day of War Crimes Trial Rapaport Diamond Prices - PDF --- Quick Links --- Mon, Jun 4, 2007 Liberia's Taylor Shuns First Day of War Crimes Trial Former Liberian President Charles Taylor refused to appear at the first day of his war crimes trial in The Hague claiming he would not get a fair showing in the United Nations court. The much publicized trial â€“ the first of an African head of state accused of war crimes by an international tribunal â€“ started June 4, 2007 in the United Nations special court for Sierra Leone in The Hague. Earlier this year, the trial was moved from Freetown, Liberia due to security concerns that the high profile case would reignite violence in theÂ region.Â  Taylor stands accused of 11 counts of war crimes and crimes against humanity stemming from his role in arming rebel groups during the conflicts in Sierra Leone and in his own country Liberia between 1989 and 2003. He allegedly funded weapons purchases by selling diamonds smuggled to Liberia from Sierra Leone. If found guilty Taylor could receive a maximum life sentence, which he would serve in the United Kingdom. He has denied all charges against him. "It is with great regret that I must decline to attend any further proceedings in this case," Taylor said via a statement read to the court by his defense lawyer Karim Kahn. "At one time I had confidence in this court's ability to dispense justice. Over time, it has become clear that confidence has been misplaced. I will not receive a fair trial." In another dramatic development at the trial, Kahn told the court that he would no longer be representing Taylor after the former president withdrew his permission for representation. Kahn said that Taylor would apply to act in his own defense. The lawyerÂ subsequently left the court despite threats that he would be held in contempt should he do so, according to press reports. The trial is expected to last a year and a half and is scheduled to commence June 25. Information that means Business Â© Copyright 1982-2007 by Martin Rapaport. All rights reserved. | IndexÂ®, RapNetÂ®, RapaportÂ®, PriceGrid&#8482, Diamonds.Net&#8482, and JNSÂ®; are TradeMarks of Martin Rapaport. While the information presented is from sources we believe reliable, we do not guarantee the accuracy or validity of any information presented by Rapaport or the views expressed by users of our internet service.
