document.getElementById('auth').innerHTML = "Welcome " + x + " " + xdt + " " +" Forty years of despair Last Updated : Tuesday 05 Jun, 2007 Forty years on, the six-day war that dramatically reshaped the Middle East in 1967 still scars the region, deeply affecting the lives of Israelis, Palestinians and their neighbours. A series of demonstrations and exhibitions in Israel and the occupied West Bank will this week protest against the 40 years of Israeli occupation that human rights groups say have plunged the Palestinians into unprecedented poverty. After weeks of belligerency and brinkmanship by regional and international players, Israel launched what it called a preemptive strike in the early hours of June 5, 1967, and quickly faced off Egypt, Jordan and Syria. Six days later, the war ended with Israel the clear winner, its people brimming with joy, the Palestinians in shock and the regional geopolitical map cardinally changed. The 19-year-old Jewish state conquered the West Bank and east Jerusalem from Jordan, the Golan from Syria, and the Gaza Strip and Sinai peninsula from Egypt - an area three-and-a-half times larger than the state of Israel itself. The war marked what some in Israel have called its brightest moment, as the young state established military superiority and enlarged its borders. But others have called the war its biggest mistake, as Israel turned into an occupying power lording it over one million Palestinians - nearly half the population of Israel proper at the time. “Had we been able to transform the victory into peace, we might have been able to prevent the wars that followed,” Israel’s elder statesman Shimon Peres said. For Israelis, the image of their soldiers conquering east Jerusalem - and with it Judaism’s holiest site, the Western Wall which Jews had been prohibited from visiting since the creation of the state 1948 - was all-powerful. But the military triumph has been made to look like “one of history’s Pyrrhic victories” and has turned into “a calamity for the Jewish state no less than for its neighbours”, the Economist said recently. For Palestinians, the war marked the nadir of despair since the creation of the Jewish state: they came under Israeli occupation and their dream of a state of their own seemed to slip out of reach. “The hated enemy, who had driven the Palestinians from their homes in 1948, was now in control of their lives, lands, and property,” historian Benny Morris wrote. But it also mobilised their resistance movement and propelled the struggle onto the world stage. “The traumatic demolition of the status quo reawakened Palestinian identity and quickened nationalist aspirations in the conquered territories and in the Arab states,” Morris wrote in ‘Righteous Victims’. On the international stage, the war thrust the Arab-Israeli conflict back to the forefront, placing it smack in the middle of the Cold War between the United States and Soviet Union. The war led to Israel’s only peace treaties with Arab countries: the 1979 treaty with Egypt, with the return of the Sinai, and in 1994 with Jordan after the Palestinian autonomy deal. “We understood Israel is the biggest regional power, you cannot destroy or remove it,” said Emad Gad, an analyst with the Cairo-based Ahram Centre for Strategic Studies. But the war also planted the seeds of the many deep-rooted problems that generations of diplomats have found impossible to untangle in their search for peace - from the Jewish settler movement to sovereignty over the Holy City. These obstacles have torpedoed numerous international efforts to resolve the conflict, with peace talks moribund since the failure of Camp David talks in 2000 and little progress on a recently revived Arab peace plan that offers Israel normal ties in return for a withdrawal from occupied land and a return of Palestinian refugees. The war still casts a shadow over US diplomacy, with Washington struggling to navigate between its traditional staunch support for Israel and desire to build bridges to the Arab world. “It is scandalous the occupation has persisted since 1967.  This conflict should have been resolved long ago, and its continuation is an indictment of all involved,” from the warring parties to the big powers, said The Economist. Israel has plunged the Palestinians into unprecedented levels of poverty and despair during 40 years of occupation, yet failed to ensure its own security, Amnesty International has claimed. While acknowledging Israel’s “legitimate security concerns”, the London-based human rights group said the Jewish state could not justify building its security barrier inside parts of the West Bank and condemned its settlement policies. If Israel just wanted to keep out suicide bombers, Amnesty added, it would have only built the barrier along the Green Line that marked its boundary with the West Bank until Israeli forces invaded in the June 1967 war. “Yet, the reality is that most of it is being built on Palestinian land,” Amnesty’s Middle East and North Africa Programme director Malcolm Smart said, adding that the Israeli barrier defies the International Court of Justice and separates Palestinian towns and villages in the West Bank. His organisation said Palestinians are also restricted by more than 500 checkpoints and blockades as well as a network of roads reserved solely for settlers and linking settlements with Israel proper. The policies are aimed at benefitting “continuously expanding but unlawful Israeli settlements” while causing the “virtual collapse of the Palestinian economy”, the human rights group charged. They are also “exacerbating the increasingly fragile conditions in which Palestinians live and work - resulting in levels of despair, poverty and food insecurity never before seen in the” territories, he said. “Most Palestinians are now relying on aid for subsistence, with families reducing the quality and quantity of the food they consume and selling assets essential for their livelihoods,” he added. Israeli actions, Amnesty said, have “resulted in widespread human rights abuses and have also failed to bring security to the Israeli and Palestinian civilian populations”. Post this story to : more news from around the world - Credit: Kibaki's elections machine shapes up Floating cocaine at Axim, T'adi Mystery as 10 cops grabbed Unions reject revised govt pay offer Leave a comment for this article to enter your comments. AP-Family and friends gather around the casket of Scott Harmon Wednesday, March 7, 2007 in Lima, Ohio as the funeral service begins. Quitting smoking is pure agony I would like, If I may, to share my recent agonisi... Shocked at Maddie media circus I was really shocked to read all the stories about... Nine out of ten for Aerosmith concert A great performance by Aerosmith, and nine out of ... posted by : Mohamed Somji A conversation takes place in the textile market in Bur Dubai posted by : Mohamed Somji posted by : Hassan Al-Hassany posted by : Omar Nimer Cheating home delivery services of NANDO&#039;S Sharjah Next time you order for home delivery from Nando&#039;s Sharjah be careful.... Discrimination at "APRES at the Kimpinski I was told I can&#039;t get in to the restaurant because I was wearing a sp... Ya right PURE GOLD!! I had the worst experience with this shop, i work as a customer relations o... It only happens in the Gulf... camel on a truck... posted by : nazlinka Aerosmith is in Dubai! posted by : poppin96 posted by : Anonymous posted by : Unknown Turn your back on smoking Don’t play chicken with my sandwich Tested: Arabian Incense Cocoon, Grand Spa Welcome beautiful glowing eyes Downloading is the new packaging for our favourite boxsets Quitting smoking is pure agony Shocked at Maddie media circus Nine out of ten for Aerosmith concert Abu Dhabi - Indecent exposure Dubai - Am I being fined? Are We Done Yet? 11:30AM 1:30 3:30 5:30 7:30 11:15AM 1:45 4:30 7:00 9:30 12:00AM Grand Abu Dhabi Mall 10:30 12:45 3:00 5:15 7:30 9:45 12:00