http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-4&fd=R&url=http://english.people.com.cn/200706/04/eng20070604_380797.html&cid=1116937653&ei=iIBkRp-FDojsqgOG-ZSiBg People's Daily Online -- Six people killed in ambush against police in Mogadishu China at a glance China in brief 2004 CPC & state organs Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping UPDATED: 22:17, June 04, 2007 Six people killed in ambush against police in Mogadishu Six people were killed including two policemen and six others wounded as a result of a fighting in the capital Mogadishu on Monday, police and eyewitnesses said. "Two policemen were shot dead in Bakara (market)by unidentified gunmen who we suspect to be Islamists," a police officer told Xinhua. He asked not to be named because he was not authorized to speak to the media. Four civilians including two women were also shot dead while six others were wounded including three policemen in Mogadishu's biggest Bakara market, Omar Daahir, a businessman in the market, told Xinhua. "The police are shooting at the people after two of them were killed," Daahir said. "Four people were killed in the market, two were women. The six injured were rushed to the hospital." The situation in and around the market remains tense with the Somali security forces keeping guard at the main roads leading to the market and business people closing their premises. These latest killing in the capital came as the government promised to improve security in the capital after Sunday's suicide attack targeting the house of Somali Prime Minister Ali Mohamed Gedi, in the north of the capital. At least seven people were killed and ten others were wounded in the attack, most of them bodyguards of the prime minister. There has been an upsurge of violence in Mogadishu lately, blamed on Islamist fighters by the Somali government, which was formed in the n capital Nairobi in 2004 as a result of a national reconciliation conference there. The Horn of Africa nation has been without a central authority for more than 16 years since the overthrow of the ruler Mohamed Siyad Barre in 1991 when the country fell into chaos and lawlessness. Comment on the story Copyright by People's Daily Online, all rights reserved
